{"title_page": "Tiny Dynamine", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Tiny Dynamine\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[Cocteau Twins]]\n| cover      = cocteautwins_tiny.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 15 November 1985 (UK)\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Ethereal wave]]\n| length     = 16:28\n| label      = [[4AD]] - <small>BAD510</small>\n| producer   = [[Cocteau Twins]]\n| chronology = [[Cocteau Twins]]\n| prev_title = [[Aikea-Guinea]]\n| prev_year  = 1985\n| next_title = [[Echoes in a Shallow Bay]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = CD cover\n | type    = EP\n | cover   = cocteautwins_tinycd.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = combines both EPs\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r4252}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Tiny Dynamine''''' is an [[Extended play|EP]] by [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[alternative rock]] band [[Cocteau Twins]], released on [[4AD Records]].  The EP featured four non-album tracks. It was issued on 15 November 1985, two weeks prior to another EP, ''[[Echoes in a Shallow Bay]]''. The two EP sets, which featured complementary artwork, were also released as a combined double EP in a gatefold cover and as an eight-track CD. The EP was reissued in 1991 as part of ''[[The Box Set (Cocteau Twins)|The Box Set]]'' and in 2005 as part of the singles/EP collection ''[[Lullabies to Violaine]]''.\n\n==Release details==\nThe band did not originally intend to release these songs to the general public, presumably explaining the decision to release the material on EPs, rather than as what would have been their fourth album. The tracks on ''Tiny Dynamine'' and ''Echoes in a Shallow Bay'' were initially recorded to test the production capacities of a new studio. When the band decided the material was strong enough for release, they completed the recording process and issued the finished product on two EPs.\n\n\"Pink Orange Red\" and \"Plain Tiger\" were performed live. An acoustic version of \"Pink Orange Red\" appeared on the 1995 [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Twinlights]]'', and a remastered version appeared on the 2000 compilation ''[[Stars and Topsoil]]''.\n\nMany of the titles on the two EPs seem to have some link with [[Lepidoptera]] (butterflies and moths). Most are obscure, but the [[dynamine]] is a genus of nymphalid butterflies found in South America, the [[plain tiger]] is a common Asian butterfly and the lyrics to \"Melonella\" (on ''Echoes In A Shallow Bay'') are simply a recounting of various Lepidopteric [[family (biology)|family]] names such as [[Hesperiidae]] and [[Papilionidae]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by Cocteau Twins.\n\n===12\": 4AD / BAD 510 (UK) ===\n\n# \"Pink Orange Red\" - 4:41\n# \"Ribbed and Veined\" - 4:00\n# \"Plain Tiger\" - 4:01\n# \"Sultitan Itan\" - 3:53\n\n=== CD: 4AD / BAD 510 CD (UK) ===\n\n# \"Pink Orange Red\" - 4:41\n# \"Ribbed and Veined\" - 4:00\n# \"Plain Tiger\" - 4:01\n# \"Sultitan Itan\" - 3:53\n# \"Great Spangled Fritillary\" - 4:02\n# \"Melonella\" - 4:05\n# \"Pale Clouded White\" - 4:59\n# \"Eggs and Their Shells\" - 3:06\n\n* Tracks 5-8 from ''[[Echoes in a Shallow Bay]]'' EP\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Elizabeth Fraser]] - [[Singing|vocals]]\n*[[Robin Guthrie]] - [[guitar]]\n*[[Simon Raymonde]] - [[bass guitar]]\n\n==Release Notes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n* Produced by Cocteau Twins.  All tracks written by Cocteau Twins.\n\n* Recorded at Guerilla, London.\n* Mixed at Aosis, London, by Robin Guthrie, studio engineer Matt Wallis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cocteautwins.com/echoes-in-a-shallow-bay.html|title=Cocteau Twins: Echoes in a Shallow Bay|website=cocteautwins.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n* ''Tiny Dynamine'' was re-released in November, 1985 on a combined disc with ''Echoes In A Shallow Bay'' under 4AD catalog designation CAD 510/511.\n* A live performance of \"Pink Orange Red\" was recorded for SNUB-TV in the UK in 1985.\n* An acoustic version of \"Pink Orange Red\" appears on the 1995 EP ''Twinlights''.\n* Re-released in 1991 as part of ''The Box Set''.\n* A remastered version of \"Pink Orange Red\" appears on the 2000 compilation ''Stars and Topsoil''.\n* Digitally remastered and re-released in 2005 as part of ''Lullabies to Violaine''.\n* \"Pink Orange Red\" and \"Plain Tiger\" have appeared in live performances.\n* Sleeve design by 23 Envelope.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1985 in music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cocteau Twins}}\n\n[[Category:Cocteau Twins albums]]\n[[Category:1985 EPs]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Tiny Dynamine\n| type       = EP\n| artist     = [[Cocteau Twins]]\n| cover      = cocteautwins_tiny.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 15 November 1985 (UK)\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Ethereal wave]]\n| length     = 16:28\n| label      = [[4AD]] - <small>BAD510</small>\n| producer   = [[Cocteau Twins]]\n| chronology = [[Cocteau Twins]]\n| prev_title = [[Aikea-Guinea]]\n| prev_year  = 1985\n| next_title = [[Echoes in a Shallow Bay]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = CD cover\n | type    = EP\n | cover   = cocteautwins_tinycd.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = combines both EPs\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r4252}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Tiny Dynamine''''' is an [[Extended play|EP]] by [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[alternative rock]] band [[Cocteau Twins]], released on [[4AD Records]].  The EP featured four non-album tracks. It was issued on 15 November 1985, two weeks prior to another EP, ''[[Echoes in a Shallow Bay]]''. The two EP sets, which featured complementary artwork, were also released as a combined double EP in a gatefold cover and as an eight-track CD. The EP was reissued in 1991 as part of ''[[The Box Set (Cocteau Twins)|The Box Set]]'' and in 2005 as part of the singles/EP collection ''[[Lullabies to Violaine]]''.\n\n==Release details==\nThe band did not originally intend to release these songs to the general public, presumably explaining the decision to release the material on EPs, rather than as what would have been their fourth album. The tracks on ''Tiny Dynamine'' and ''Echoes in a Shallow Bay'' were initially recorded to test the production capacities of a new studio. When the band decided the material was strong enough for release, they completed the recording process and issued the finished product on two EPs.\n\n\"Pink Orange Red\" and \"Plain Tiger\" were performed live. An acoustic version of \"Pink Orange Red\" appeared on the 1995 [[Extended play|EP]] ''[[Twinlights]]'', and a remastered version appeared on the 2000 compilation ''[[Stars and Topsoil]]''.\n\nMany of the titles on the two EPs seem to have some link with [[Lepidoptera]] (butterflies and moths). Most are obscure, but the [[dynamine]] is a genus of nymphalid butterflies found in South America, the [[plain tiger]] is a common Asian butterfly and the lyrics to \"Melonella\" (on ''Echoes In A Shallow Bay'') are simply a recounting of various Lepidopteric [[family (biology)|family]] names such as [[Hesperiidae]] and [[Papilionidae]].\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by Cocteau Twins.\n\n===12\": 4AD / BAD 510 (UK) ===\n\n# \"Pink Orange Red\" - 4:41\n# \"Ribbed and Veined\" - 4:00\n# \"Plain Tiger\" - 4:01\n# \"Sultitan Itan\" - 3:53\n\n=== CD: 4AD / BAD 510 CD (UK) ===\n\n# \"Pink Orange Red\" - 4:41\n# \"Ribbed and Veined\" - 4:00\n# \"Plain Tiger\" - 4:01\n# \"Sultitan Itan\" - 3:53\n# \"Great Spangled Fritillary\" - 4:02\n# \"Melonella\" - 4:05\n# \"Pale Clouded White\" - 4:59\n# \"Eggs and Their Shells\" - 3:06\n\n* Tracks 5-8 from ''[[Echoes in a Shallow Bay]]'' EP\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Elizabeth Fraser]] - [[Singing|vocals]]\n*[[Robin Guthrie]] - [[guitar]]\n*[[Simon Raymonde]] - [[bass guitar]]\n\n==Release Notes==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n* Produced by Cocteau Twins.  All tracks written by Cocteau Twins.\n\n* Recorded at Guerilla, London.\n* Mixed at Aosis, London, by Robin Guthrie, studio engineer Matt Wallis.\n* ''Tiny Dynamine'' was re-released in November, 1985 on a combined disc with ''Echoes In A Shallow Bay'' under 4AD catalog designation CAD 510/511.\n* A live performance of \"Pink Orange Red\" was recorded for SNUB-TV in the UK in 1985.\n* An acoustic version of \"Pink Orange Red\" appears on the 1995 EP ''Twinlights''.\n* Re-released in 1991 as part of ''The Box Set''.\n* A remastered version of \"Pink Orange Red\" appears on the 2000 compilation ''Stars and Topsoil''.\n* Digitally remastered and re-released in 2005 as part of ''Lullabies to Violaine''.\n* \"Pink Orange Red\" and \"Plain Tiger\" have appeared in live performances.\n* Sleeve design by 23 Envelope.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1985 in music]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cocteau Twins}}\n\n[[Category:Cocteau Twins albums]]\n[[Category:1985 EPs]]\n[[Category:UK Independent Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n", "name_user": "MattyPom", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRelease Notes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiny_Dynamine"}
{"title_page": "O. B. Clarence", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{more footnotes|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = O. B. Clarence\n| image = O_B_Clarence.jpg\n| birth_name = Oliver Burchett Clarence\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1870|3|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hampstead]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1955|10|2|1870|3|25|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Hove]], [[Sussex]], England\n| occupation = actor\n| yearsactive = 1890&ndash;1948\n}}\n\n'''Oliver Burchett Clarence''' (25 March 1870, [[Hampstead]], [[London]] \u2013 2 October 1955, [[Hove]], [[Sussex]]) was an English actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b9f96f878|title=O.B. Clarence|website=BFI}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his education at [[Dover College]] and University College Hospital, he made his stage debut in 1890. His experience included Shakespearean repertory with [[Frank Benson (actor)|Frank Benson]] and [[Ben Greet]]. He performed in over eighty shows in London and also toured the provinces and appeared abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theatricalia.com/person/1ry7/ob-clarence|title=O.B. Clarence - Theatricalia|website=theatricalia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/ob-clarence-54983|title=O.B. Clarence \u2013 Broadway Cast & Staff - IBDB|website=www.ibdb.com}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{col div}}\n* ''[[Liberty Hall (film)|Liberty Hall]]'' (1914) - Todman Crafer\n* ''[[London Pride (film)|London Pride]]'' (1920) - Mr. Tunks\n* ''[[The Little Hour of Peter Wells]]'' (1920) - Peter Wells\n* ''[[The Man from Chicago]]'' (1930) - John Larwood\n* ''[[The Bells (1931 film)|The Bells]]'' (1931) - Watchman\n* ''[[Keepers of Youth]]'' (1931) - Slade\n* ''[[Goodnight, Vienna]]'' (1932) - Theater Manager\n* ''[[Jack's the Boy]]'' (1932) - Timkins (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Flag Lieutenant (1932 film)|The Flag Lieutenant]]'' (1932) - Gen. Gough-Bogle\n* ''[[Where Is This Lady?]]'' (1932) - Dr. Peffer\n* ''[[The Barton Mystery (1932 film)|The Barton Mystery]]'' (1932) - Sir Everard Marshall\n* ''[[Discord (film)|Discord]]'' (1933) - Mr. Hemming\n* ''[[Perfect Understanding]]'' (1933) - Dr. Graham\n* ''[[Soldiers of the King (film)|Soldiers of the King]]'' (1933) - Tom\n* ''[[Excess Baggage (1933 film)|Excess Baggage]]'' (1933) - Lord Grebe\n* ''[[Falling for You (film)|Falling for You]]'' (1933) - Trubshawe\n* ''[[His Grace Gives Notice (1933 film)|His Grace Gives Notice]]'' (1933) - Lord Rannock\n* ''[[A Shot in the Dark (1933 film)|A Shot in the Dark]]'' (1933) - Rev. John Makehan\n* ''[[I Adore You (film)|I Adore You]]'' (1933) - Mr. Young\n* ''[[Friday the Thirteenth (1933 film)|Friday the Thirteenth]]'' (1933) - Clerk\n* ''[[Turkey Time (1933 film)|Turkey Time]]'' (1933) - Shopkeeper (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Silver Spoon]]'' (1933) - Parker\n* ''[[Eyes of Fate]]'' (1933) - Mr. Oliver\n* ''[[The Double Event (1934 film)|The Double Event]]'' (1934) - Rev. Martingale\n* ''[[The Only Girl]]'' (1933) - Etienne\n* ''[[The Great Defender]]'' (1934) - Mr. Hammond\n* ''[[Song at Eventide]]'' (1934) - Registrar\n* ''[[Nell Gwynn (1934 film)|Nell Gwynn]]'' (1934) - Clockmaker (uncredited)\n* ''[[Father and Son (1934 film)|Father and Son]]'' (1934) - Tom Yates\n* ''[[Lady in Danger]]'' (1934) - Nelson\n* ''[[The Scarlet Pimpernel (1934 film)|The Scarlet Pimpernel]]'' (1934) - Count de Tournay\n* ''[[The King of Paris (1934 film)|The King of Paris]]'' (1934) - Mayor\n* ''[[The Feathered Serpent (1934 film)|The Feathered Serpent]]'' (1934) - George Beale\n* ''[[D'Ye Ken John Peel?]]'' (1935) - Ogleby\n* ''[[Barnacle Bill (1935 film)|Barnacle Bill]]'' (1935) - Uncle George\n* ''[[Dandy Dick]]'' (1935) - Council Member (uncredited)\n* ''[[Squibs (1935 film)|Squibs]]'' (1935) - Sir John Barratt\n* ''[[The Private Secretary (1935 film)|The Private Secretary]]'' (1935) - Thomas Marsland\n* ''[[No Monkey Business]]''