eal' Clergyman (uncredited)\n* ''[[On Approval (1944 film)|On Approval]]'' (1944) - Dr. Graham\n* ''[[A Place of One's Own]]'' (1945) - Perkins\n* ''[[The Way to the Stars]]'' (1945) - Minor Role (scenes deleted)\n* ''Great Day'' (1945)\n* ''[[Caesar and Cleopatra (film)|Caesar and Cleopatra]]'' (1945) - Egyptian (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Magic Bow]]'' (1946) - Old Gentleman\n* ''[[School for Secrets]]'' (1946) - Old Retainer\n* ''[[Great Expectations (1946 film)|Great Expectations]]'' (1946) - The Aged Parent\n* ''[[While the Sun Shines]]'' (1947) - Old Gentleman\n* ''[[Meet Me at Dawn]]'' (1947) - Ambassador\n* ''[[Uncle Silas (film)|Uncle Silas]]'' (1947) - Vicar Clay\n* ''[[The Calendar (1948 film)|The Calendar]]'' (1948) - Old Gentleman at Epsom\n* ''[[No Room at the Inn]]'' (1948) - Reporter in Council Chambers (uncredited) (final film role)\n{{col div end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0163538}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clarence, O. B.}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1955 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dover College]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kent]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n\n\n{{England-film-actor-stub}}\n{{England-stage-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O._B._Clarence"}
{"title_page": "Haynesville Correctional Center", "text_new": "{{Infobox Prison\n| prison_name    = Haynesville Correctional Center\n| image          = \n| location       = 421 Barnfield Road <br> [[Haynesville, Virginia]]\n| coordinates    = \n| status         = mixed\n| classification = \n| capacity       = 1141\n| opened         = 1993\n| closed         = \n| managed_by     = [[Virginia Department of Corrections]] \n| director       =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Haynesville Correctional Center'''  is a state prison for men located in [[Haynesville, Virginia|Haynesville]], [[Richmond County, Virginia]], owned and operated by the [[Virginia Department of Corrections]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Haynesville Correctional Center|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20160401123650/https://vadoc.virginia.gov/facilities/eastern/haynesville/|publisher=Virginia Department of Corrections|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref>  \n\nThe facility was opened in 1993 and has a daily working population of 1141 inmates, held at a range of security levels.  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{State prisons in Virginia}}\n{{coord|37.955468|-76.669036|format=dms|display=title|type:landmark}}\n\n[[Category:Prisons in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Richmond County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Prison\n| prison_name    = Haynesville Correctional Center\n| image          = \n| location       = 421 Barnfield Road <br> [[Haynesville, Virginia]]\n| coordinates    = \n| status         = mixed\n| classification = \n| capacity       = 1141\n| opened         = 1993\n| closed         = \n| managed_by     = [[Virginia Department of Corrections]] \n| director       =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Haynesville Correctional Center'''  is a state prison for men located in [[Haynesville, Virginia|Haynesville]], [[Richmond County, Virginia]], owned and operated by the [[Virginia Department of Corrections]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Haynesville Correctional Center|url=https://vadoc.virginia.gov/facilities/eastern/haynesville/|publisher=Virginia Department of Corrections|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref>  \n\nThe facility was opened in 1993 and has a daily working population of 1141 inmates, held at a range of security levels.  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{State prisons in Virginia}}\n{{coord|37.955468|-76.669036|format=dms|display=title|type:landmark}}\n\n[[Category:Prisons in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Richmond County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Jalbertbowdenii", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkrot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haynesville_Correctional_Center"}
{"title_page": "Nina Sevening", "text_new": "[[File:Nina Sevening 1902.jpg|thumb|Nina Sevening as Miss Powerscourt in ''A Country Girl'', 1902<ref name=npg/>]]\n'''Nina Gladys Sevening''' (1885 \u2013 1958) was an English stage actress, singer and light comedian.\n\n==Background==\nSevening was born in Westminster, London.  Her parents were H. W. Sevening, a German-born commercial clerk, and his English wife Gertrude.  She was educated in London and Paris.<ref>Wearing, pp. 448, 676</ref><ref>[http://www.stagebeauty.net/th-frames.html?http&&&www.stagebeauty.net/sevening/sevening-n.html Nina Sevening (c.1885-1958)]. stagebeauty.net</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSevening first appeared on stage in December 1894 in ''The House That Jack Built'' at the [[Opera Comique]]. She later appeared in:\n*''My Innocent Boy'' at [[The Royalty]] 1898\n* ''[[Florodora]]'' at the [[Lyric Theatre, London|Lyric Theatre]] 1899<ref name=\"Lamb2002\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Lamb|title=Leslie Stuart: Composer of Florodora|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=arsbsDewXqIC&pg=PA86|year=2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-93747-4|pages=86\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''The Silver Slipper'' at the Lyric Theatre 1901<ref>Wearing, p. 60</ref>\n* ''[[A Country Girl]]'' at [[Daly's Theatre]] 1902<ref name=npg/><ref>Wearing, p. 87</ref>\n* ''[[The Cingalee]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1904<ref>Wearing, p. 176</ref>\n* ''[[The Little Michus]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1905<ref>Wearing, p. 230</ref>\n* ''[[The Merveilleuses]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1906<ref>Wearing, p. 316</ref>\n* ''[[The Geisha]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1906<ref>Wearing, p. 303</ref>\n* ''[[The Merry Widow]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1907<ref name=\"Slattery-Christy2008\">{{cite book|author=David Slattery-Christy|title=Anything But Merry!: The life and times of Lily Elsie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tQsIAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA254|date= 2008|publisher=Author House|isbn=978-1-4817-7542-7|pages=254\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''Susannah and Some Others'' at the [[Royalty Theatre]] 1908<ref>Wearing, p. 391</ref>\n* ''Marjory Strode'' at [[Playhouse Theatre, London|The Playhouse]] 1908<ref>Wearing, p. 400</ref>\n* ''Mid-Channel'' at [[St James's Theatre]] 1909<ref>Wearing, p. 487</ref>\n* ''The Great Mrs. Alloway'' at the [[Globe Theatre]] 1909<ref>Wearing, p. 494</ref>\n* ''Mid-Channel'' at the [[Empire Theatre (41st Street)|Empire Theatre]] (New York) 1910\n* ''A Woman's Way'', [[Comedy Theatre]] 1910\n* ''Grace'' at the [[Duke of York's Theatre]] 1910\n* ''Passers By'' at [[Wyndham's Theatre]] 1911\n* ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' at the [[Duke of York's Theatre]] 1911\n* ''Mind the Paint Girl'' at the Duke of York's Theatre 1912\n* ''The Perplexed Husband'' at the [[Empire Theatre (41st Street)|Empire Theatre]] (New York) 1912\n* ''[[Peter Pan]]'' at the Duke of York Theatre 1913<ref name=\"Hanson2011\">{{cite book|author=Bruce K. Hanson|title=Peter Pan on Stage and Screen, 1904-2010, 2d ed.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k3HHu_CxoWkC&pg=PA339|date=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8619-9|pages=339\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''[[King's Cup]]'' at the Adelphi Theater 1913<ref>Wearing, p. 500</ref>\n* ''The Clever Ones'' at [[Wyndham's Theatre]] 1914\n* ''Caroline'' at the [[New Theatre (London)|New Theatre]] 1916 \n* ''[[Trelawny of the 'Wells']]'' at the New Theatre 1917\n\nIn 1903, Sevening toured in ''[[Three Little Maids]]''.  In 1905 she played the title role in ''[[Lady Madcap]]''.<ref>Wearing, p. 212</ref>\n\nShe married Victor Charles Hamilton Longstaffe (born 1885) and changed her last name after him.<ref name=npg>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw158740/Nina-Longstaffe-ne-Sevening-as-Miss-Powerscourt-in-A-Country-Girl Nina Longstaffe (n\u00e9e Sevening) as Miss Powerscourt in 'A Country Girl']. npg.org.uk</ref> She retired from the stage in 1917.\n\nThere is a memorial to their only son, David John Longstaffe, in Aldeburgh Parish Church in Suffolk, England. David died on 16 September 1945 in Athens, where he was a Captain in the King's Royal Rifle Corps.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/56553053 Capt David John Longstaffe]. findagrave.com</ref><ref>[http://www.gravestonephotos.com/public/gravedetails.php?fullname=Nina%20Longstaffe&grave=6&scrwidth=1600 David John Longstaffe grave monument]. gravestonephotos.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|author=J. P. Wearing|title=The London Stage 1900-1909: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o5JWAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA87|date=2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-9294-1}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sevening, Nina}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Nina Sevening 1902.jpg|thumb|Nina Sevening as Miss Powerscourt in ''A Country Girl'', 1902<ref name=npg/>]]\n'''Nina Gladys Sevening''' (1885 \u2013 1958) was an English stage actress, singer and light comedian.\n\n==Background==\nSevening was born in Westminster, London.  Her parents were H. W. Sevening, a German-born commercial clerk, and his English wife Gertrude.  She was educated in London and Paris.<ref>Wearing, pp. 448, 676</ref><ref>[http://www.stagebeauty.net/th-frames.html?http&&&www.stagebeauty.net/sevening/sevening-n.html Nina Sevening (c.1885-1958)]. stagebeauty.net</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSevening first appeared on stage in December 1894 in ''The House That Jack Built'' at the [[Opera Comique]]. She later appeared in:\n*''My Innocent Boy'' at [[The Royalty]] 1898\n* ''[[Florodora]]'' at the [[Lyric Theatre, London|Lyric Theatre]] 1899<ref name=\"Lamb2002\">{{cite book|author=Andrew Lamb|title=Leslie Stuart: Composer of Florodora|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=arsbsDewXqIC&pg=PA86|year=2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-93747-4|pages=86\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''The Silver Slipper'' at the Lyric Theatre 1901<ref>Wearing, p. 60</ref>\n* ''[[A Country Girl]]'' at [[Daly's Theatre]] 1902<ref name=npg/><ref>Wearing, p. 87</ref>\n* ''[[The Cingalee]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1904<ref>Wearing, p. 176</ref>\n* ''[[The Little Michus]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1905<ref>Wearing, p. 230</ref>\n* ''[[The Merveilleuses]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1906<ref>Wearing, p. 316</ref>\n* ''[[The Geisha]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1906<ref>Wearing, p. 303</ref>\n* ''[[The Merry Widow]]'' at Daly's Theatre 1907<ref name=\"Slattery-Christy2008\">{{cite book|author=David Slattery-Christy|title=Anything But Merry!: The life and times of Lily Elsie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tQsIAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA254|date= 2008|publisher=Author House|isbn=978-1-4817-7542-7|pages=254\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''Susannah and Some Others'' at the [[Royalty Theatre]] 1908<ref>Wearing, p. 391</ref>\n* ''Marjory Strode'' at [[Playhouse Theatre, London|The Playhouse]] 1908<ref>Wearing, p. 400</ref>\n* ''Mid-Channel'' at [[St James's Theatre]] 1909<ref>Wearing, p. 487</ref>\n* ''The Great Mrs. Alloway'' at the [[Globe Theatre]] 1909<ref>Wearing, p. 494</ref>\n* ''Mid-Channel'' at the [[Empire Theatre (41st Street)|Empire Theatre]] (New York) 1910\n* ''A Woman's Way'', [[Comedy Theatre]] 1910\n* ''Grace'' at the [[Duke of York's Theatre]] 1910\n* ''Passers By'' at [[Wyndham's Theatre]] 1911\n* ''[[What Every Woman Knows (play)|What Every Woman Knows]]'' at the [[Duke of York's Theatre]] 1911\n* ''Mind the Paint Girl'' at the Duke of York's Theatre 1912\n* ''The Perplexed Husband'' at the [[Empire Theatre (41st Street)|Empire Theatre]] (New York) 1912\n* ''[[Peter Pan]]'' at the Duke of York Theatre 1913<ref name=\"Hanson2011\">{{cite book|author=Bruce K. Hanson|title=Peter Pan on Stage and Screen, 1904-2010, 2d ed.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k3HHu_CxoWkC&pg=PA339|date=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8619-9|pages=339\u2013}}</ref>\n* ''[[King's Cup]]'' at the Adelphi Theater 1913<ref>Wearing, p. 500</ref>\n* ''The Clever Ones'' at [[Wyndham's Theatre]] 1914\n* ''Caroline'' at the [[New Theatre (London)|New Theatre]] 1916 \n* ''[[Trelawny of the 'Wells']]'' at the New Theatre 1917\n\nIn 1903, Sevening toured in ''[[Three Little Maids]]''.  In 1905 she played the title role in ''[[Lady Madcap]]''.<ref>Wearing, p. 212</ref>\n\nShe married Victor Charles Hamilton Longstaffe (born 1885) and changed her last name after him.<ref name=npg>[http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw158740/Nina-Longstaffe-ne-Sevening-as-Miss-Powerscourt-in-A-Country-Girl Nina Longstaffe (n\u00e9e Sevening) as Miss Powerscourt in 'A Country Girl']. npg.org.uk</ref> She retired from the stage in 1917.\n\nThere is a memorial to their only son, David John Longstaffe, in Aldeburgh Parish Church in Suffolk, England. David died on 16 September 1945 in Athens, where he was a Captain in the King's Royal Rifle Corps.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/56553053 Capt David John Longstaffe]. findagrave.com</ref><ref>[http://www.gravestonephotos.com/public/gravedetails.php?fullname=Nina%20Longstaffe&grave=6&scrwidth=1600 David John Longstaffe grave monument]. gravestonephotos.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|author=J. P. Wearing|title=The London Stage 1900-1909: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o5JWAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA87|date=2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-9294-1}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sevening, Nina}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n\n\n{{England-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joeykai", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:clean up, removed stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nina_Sevening"}
{"title_page": "Camille Thomas", "text_new": "{{about|the Franco-Belgian cellist|Canadian musician|Carmen and Camille}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|name       = Camille Thomas\n|image      = Pastorales d'\u00e9t\u00e9 par l'OSB, Soir\u00e9e symphonique, Grand Air 2014, Rennes-3.jpg\n|caption    = Thomas at [[Rennes]] in 2014 with the [[Brittany Symphony Orchestra]].\n|background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|birth_date = {{birth-date and age|May 1988}}\n|birth_place= [[Paris]], [[France]]\n|website    = {{URL|camillethomas.com}}\n|instrument = 1730 [[De Munck (Stradivarius cello)|''De Munck-Feuermann'' Stradivarius]]\n|genre      = [[classical music|Classical]]\n}}\n\n'''Camille Thomas''' (born May 1988 in [[Paris]], France) is a [[France|Franco]]-[[Belgium|Belgian]] [[cello|cellist]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nCamille Thomas began studying the [[cello]] at the age of 4. At 10 years old, she studied under Marcel Bardon at the ''Conservatoire national de r\u00e9gion de Paris'', where, at 16 years old, she was awarded her first competition prize for cello performance. She then studied under [[Philippe Muller]] at the national music school at [[Aulnay-sous-Bois]], before heading to [[Germany]] to study under [[Stephan Forck]] and then [[Frans Hermerson]] at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Hanns Eisler]] in [[Berlin]]. She subsequently studied under [[Wolfgang-Emmanuel Schmidt]] at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Franz Liszt]] in [[Weimar]]. She participated in numerous [[masterclass]]es and was able to learn from many renowned cellists, among them [[David Geringas]], [[Steven Isserlis]], [[Wolfgang Boetticher]], [[Natalia Shakovskaya]], [[Ralph Kirschbaum]], Boris Baraz, and [[Tabea Zimmermann]].\n\nHaving been noticed and invited by [[Seiji Ozawa]] and [[Steven Isserlis]] to perform in their festivals,<ref name=\"ozawa-academy.ch\">http://www.ozawa-academy.ch/fr/public/document/index/page/1923</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.i-m-s.org.uk/courses/participants/|title=Musicians : International Musicians Seminar|website=www.i-m-s.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Camille Thomas performed throughout Europe, notably at the Gaveau Hall in [[Paris]], the [[Victoria Hall (Geneva)|Victoria Hall]] in [[Geneva]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://orchestredesnations.com/en/home/|title=Home|website=Orchestre des nations|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> the [[Palais des beaux-arts de Bruxelles]].<ref>http://www.bozar.be/activity.php?id=10433</ref> the Jerusalem Music Center, and the [[Konzerthaus de Berlin]]. She has performed in various festivals such as the [[festival Pablo Casals]]<ref>http://www.prades-festival-casals.com/ca/artiste/593-0-0-0/</ref> de [[Prades (Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales)|Prades]], the Strasbourg festival,<ref>{{cite web|title=Festival de Strasbourg|url=http://festival-strasbourg.com/classiques74/19juin.php|website=festival de Strasbourg|publication-date=}}</ref> Encuentro de Musica de [[Santander (Espagne)|Santander]], and the Amsterdam Cello Biennale.\n\nThomas has performed as a soloist alongside the Sinfonia Varsovia, the [[Baden Baden]] Philharmonic Orchestra, the [[Orhcestre national de Lille]], the [[Philharmonisches Staatsorchester Hamburg]], the Picardy Orchestra, the [[Slovak Philharmonic]], the [[Slovak Radio Symphonic Orchestra]], the [[Lucerne Festival Strings]], the [[Young Belgian Strings]], the [[Brittany Symphonic Orchestra]], the [[Orchestre Philharmonique de Li\u00e8ge|Orchestre philharmonique royal de Li\u00e8ge]], the  [[North Czech Philharmonic]],\u00a0the [[Orchestre Lamoureux]], the [[French Republican Guard Band]], the [[United Nations]] orchestra, La Baule Symphonic. She has performed with the Junge Sinfonie Berlin under the direction of conductors [[Kent Nagano]], [[Theodor Guschlbauer]], Arie van Beek, Darrell Ang, [[Fay\u00e7al Karoui]], Mathieu Herzog, Jean-Christophe Ferreaux, Pavel Baleff, Kriistina Poska, Debora Waldman, Giedre Slekyte, Charles Olivieri-Munroe, Antoine Marguier, Rastislav Stur, and Aziz Shokhakimov.\n\n== Prizes and honours ==\n\nThomas has been awarded numerous prizes at national and international competitions such as the [[L\u00e9opold Bellan]] competition in Paris, the Edmond Baert competition in Bruxelles, and the {{7th}} international Antonio Janigro competition in [[Croatia]].\n\nIn 2010, Thomas was awarded a number of distinctions. She was awarded the title of \"Classical revelation\" ({{lang|fr|R\u00e9v\u00e9lation classique}}) by Adami<ref>[http://www.adami.fr/promouvoir-la-culture/les-talents-adami/revelations-classiques/les-revelations-classiques-2010.html R\u00e9v\u00e9lations classiques 2010] on the Adami website</ref> and became laurate of the Bleustein-Blanchet vocational foundation, the Yamaha Music Foundation of Europe, the DAAD, Villa Musica, LiveMusicNow, the Carl-Flesch Akademie,<ref>http://www.philharmonie.baden-baden.de/cfa/cfa-index.htm</ref> the [[Mannheim]] Sinfonima Stiftung,<ref>http://www.mannheimer.de/privatkunden/sinfonima/stiftung/</ref> and the AMOPA Berthier Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amopa.asso.fr/bourse_berthier_2010.htm|title=AMOPA : Bourse Raymond Berthier 2010|website=www.amopa.asso.fr|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, she was awarded a prize from the Fondation Banque Populaire.<ref>http://www.fnbp.fr/29-nouveaux-laureats-en-juin-2012.html</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, her first album was released under the Fuga Libera record label. A collaboration with the Swiss pianist [[Beatrice Berrut]] dedicated to [[20th century]] [[Russia]]n music, it received accolades from international press.\n\nIn 2014, Thomas was awarded the title of Revelation, Instrumental soloist, at the [[Victoires de la musique classique]]. She was selected by the Musiq'3 - RTBF radio station to represent Belgium at the [[European Broadcasting Union]] competition, where she is awarded first place and declared \"New Talent of the Year\".\n\nIn 2015, she is invited to appear on [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tkg89ne7mMg ARTE \u00ab Les Stars de Demain \u00bb] by Rolando Villaz\u00f3n.\n\nIn 2016, her second album, ''R\u00e9miniscences'', is released on the [[Dolce Volta]] label. It receives a CHOC prize from [[Classica (magazine)|Classica]] and a [[ECHO Klassik|ECHO KLASSIK PREIS]].\n\nIn 2017, she signs an exclusive international contract with [[Deutsche Grammophon]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutschegrammophon.com/en/artists/camille-thomas|title=Camille Thomas|website=www.deutschegrammophon.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> the first woman cellist to sign with the record label. Her first recording with them was released in October 2017, consisting of works by [[Saint-Sa\u00ebns]] and [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]], performed with the [[Orchestre national de Lille]] under conductor [[Alexandre Bloch]].\n\n== Other work ==\n\nIn addition to her work as a soloist, Thomas is a passionate chamber musician. In 2011 and 2012, she is selected to participate in the Seiji Osawa International Academic in [[Switzerland]]. She has performed regularly with them alongside musicians such as Beatrice Berrut, Julien Libeer, Frank Braley, and G\u00e9rard Causs\u00e9.\n\nIn 2011, Thomas appeared in the film [[Un baiser papillon]], taking on the role of a cellist and performing [[Vivaldi]] [[concerti]] accompanied by the Orchestre des Solistes Fran\u00e7ais.\n\n== Instruments ==\n\nThomas has played{{when|date=April 2020}} a 1788 Ferdinand Gagliano cello, dubbed the [[Ch\u00e2teau Pape Cl\u00e9ment]], loaned to her by [[Bernard Magrez]], along with a bow by [[Eug\u00e8ne Sartory]] on extended loan from the Fondation Roi Baudoin - Fonds Bollandsee.<ref name=\"laphil-profile\">{{cite web|title=Camille Thomas {{pipe}} LA Phil|url=https://www.laphil.com/musicdb/artists/6719/camille-thomas|website=LA Phil|language=en|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince 24 September 2019, she has played the [[De Munck (Stradivarius cello)|De Munck-Feuermann]], a 1730 [[Stradivarius]] cello, loaned by the [[Nippon Music Foundation]] for a period of one year.<ref name=\"thestrad-feuermann\">{{cite web|title='De Munck, Feuermann' Stradivarius cello is loaned to Camille Thomas|url=https://www.thestrad.com/news/de-munck-feuermann-stradivarius-cello-is-loaned-to-camille-thomas/9506.article|website=The Strad|language=en|date=24 April 2019|access-date=19 April 2020|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.fondationvocation.org/la-communaute-des-laureats.html Bleustein-Blanchet Vocational Foundation] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.fnbp.fr/-Notre-philosophie,40-.html Fondation Banque populaire Natixis] {{in lang|fr}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Camille}}\n[[Category:Classical cellists]]\n[[Category:Women classical cellists]]\n[[Category:Belgian cellists]]\n[[Category:Belgian classical cellists]]\n[[Category:French cellists]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Grammophon artists]]\n\n[[fr:Camille Thomas]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Franco-Belgian cellist|Canadian musician|Carmen and Camille}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|name       = Camille Thomas\n|image      = Pastorales d'\u00e9t\u00e9 par l'OSB, Soir\u00e9e symphonique, Grand Air 2014, Rennes-3.jpg\n|caption    = Thomas at [[Rennes]] in 2014 with the [[Brittany Symphony Orchestra]].\n|background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|birth_date = {{birth-date and age|May 1988}}\n|birth_place= [[Paris]], [[France]]\n|website    = {{URL|camillethomas.com}}\n|instrument = 1730 [[De Munck (Stradivarius cello)|''De Munck-Feuermann'' Stradivarius]]\n|genre      = [[classical music|Classical]]\n}}\n\n'''Camille Thomas''' (born May 1988 in [[Paris]], France) is a [[France|Franco]]-[[Belgium|Belgian]] [[cello|cellist]].\n\n== Biography ==\n\nCamille Thomas began studying the [[cello]] at the age of 4. At 10 years old, she studied under Marcel Bardon at the ''Conservatoire national de r\u00e9gion de Paris'', where, at 16 years old, she was awarded her first competition prize for cello performance. She then studied under [[Philippe Muller]] at the national music school at [[Aulnay-sous-Bois]], before heading to [[Germany]] to study under [[Stephan Forck]] and then [[Frans Hermerson]] at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Hanns Eisler]] in [[Berlin]]. She subsequently studied under [[Wolfgang-Emmanuel Schmidt]] at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Franz Liszt]] in [[Weimar]]. She participated in numerous [[masterclass]]es and was able to learn from many renowned cellists, among them [[David Geringas]], [[Steven Isserlis]], [[Wolfgang Boetticher]], [[Natalia Shakovskaya]], [[Ralph Kirschbaum]], Boris Baraz, and [[Tabea Zimmermann]].\n\nHaving been noticed and invited by [[Seiji Ozawa]] and [[Steven Isserlis]] to perform in their festivals,<ref name=\"ozawa-academy.ch\">http://www.ozawa-academy.ch/fr/public/document/index/page/1923</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.i-m-s.org.uk/courses/participants/|title=Musicians : International Musicians Seminar|website=www.i-m-s.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Camille Thomas performed throughout Europe, notably at the Gaveau Hall in [[Paris]], the [[Victoria Hall (Geneva)|Victoria Hall]] in [[Geneva]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://orchestredesnations.com/en/home/|title=Home|website=Orchestre des nations|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> the [[Palais des beaux-arts de Bruxelles]].<ref>http://www.bozar.be/activity.php?id=10433</ref> the Jerusalem Music Center, and the [[Konzerthaus de Berlin]]. She has performed in various festivals such as the [[festival Pablo Casals]]<ref>http://www.prades-festival-casals.com/ca/artiste/593-0-0-0/</ref> de [[Prades (Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales)|Prades]], the Strasbourg festival,<ref>{{cite web|title=Festival de Strasbourg|url=http://festival-strasbourg.com/classiques74/19juin.php|website=festival de Strasbourg|publication-date=}}</ref> Encuentro de Musica de [[Santander (Espagne)|Santander]], and the Amsterdam Cello Biennale.\n\nThomas has performed as a soloist alongside the Sinfonia Varsovia, the [[Baden Baden]] Philharmonic Orchestra, the [[Orhcestre national de Lille]], the [[Philharmonisches Staatsorchester Hamburg]], the Picardy Orchestra, the [[Slovak Philharmonic]], the [[Slovak Radio Symphonic Orchestra]], the [[Lucerne Festival Strings]], the [[Young Belgian Strings]], the [[Brittany Symphonic Orchestra]], the [[Orchestre Philharmonique de Li\u00e8ge|Orchestre philharmonique royal de Li\u00e8ge]], the  [[North Czech Philharmonic]],\u00a0the [[Orchestre Lamoureux]], the [[French Republican Guard Band]], the [[United Nations]] orchestra, La Baule Symphonic. She has performed with the Junge Sinfonie Berlin under the direction of conductors [[Kent Nagano]], [[Theodor Guschlbauer]], Arie van Beek, Darrell Ang, [[Fay\u00e7al Karoui]], Mathieu Herzog, Jean-Christophe Ferreaux, Pavel Baleff, Kriistina Poska, Debora Waldman, Giedre Slekyte, Charles Olivieri-Munroe, Antoine Marguier, Rastislav Stur, and Aziz Shokhakimov.\n\n== Prizes and honours ==\n\nThomas has been awarded numerous prizes at national and international competitions such as the [[L\u00e9opold Bellan]] competition in Paris, the Edmond Baert competition in Bruxelles, and the {{7th}} international Antonio Janigro competition in [[Croatia]].\n\nIn 2010, Thomas was awarded a number of distinctions. She was awarded the title of \"Classical revelation\" ({{lang|fr|R\u00e9v\u00e9lation classique}}) by Adami<ref>[http://www.adami.fr/promouvoir-la-culture/les-talents-adami/revelations-classiques/les-revelations-classiques-2010.html R\u00e9v\u00e9lations classiques 2010] on the Adami website</ref> and became laurate of the Bleustein-Blanchet vocational foundation, the Yamaha Music Foundation of Europe, the DAAD, Villa Musica, LiveMusicNow, the Carl-Flesch Akademie,<ref>http://www.philharmonie.baden-baden.de/cfa/cfa-index.htm</ref> the [[Mannheim]] Sinfonima Stiftung,<ref>http://www.mannheimer.de/privatkunden/sinfonima/stiftung/</ref> and the AMOPA Berthier Prize.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amopa.asso.fr/bourse_berthier_2010.htm|title=AMOPA : Bourse Raymond Berthier 2010|website=www.amopa.asso.fr|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, she was awarded a prize from the Fondation Banque Populaire.<ref>http://www.fnbp.fr/29-nouveaux-laureats-en-juin-2012.html</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, her first album was released under the Fuga Libera record label. A collaboration with the Swiss pianist [[Beatrice Berrut]] dedicated to [[20th century]] [[Russia]]n music, it received accolades from international press.\n\nIn 2014, Thomas was awarded the title of Revelation, Instrumental soloist, at the [[Victoires de la musique classique]]. She was selected by the Musiq'3 - RTBF radio station to represent Belgium at the [[European Broadcasting Union]] competition, where she is awarded first place and declared \"New Talent of the Year\".\n\nIn 2015, she is invited to appear on [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tkg89ne7mMg ARTE \u00ab Les Stars de Demain \u00bb] by Rolando Villaz\u00f3n.\n\nIn 2016, her second album, ''R\u00e9miniscences'', is released on the [[Dolce Volta]] label. It receives a CHOC prize from [[Classica (magazine)|Classica]] and a [[ECHO Klassik|ECHO KLASSIK PREIS]].\n\nIn 2017, she signs an exclusive international contract with [[Deutsche Grammophon]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deutschegrammophon.com/en/artists/camille-thomas|title=Camille Thomas|website=www.deutschegrammophon.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> the first woman cellist to sign with the record label. Her first recording with them was released in October 2017, consisting of works by [[Saint-Sa\u00ebns]] and [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]], performed with the [[Orchestre national de Lille]] under conductor [[Alexandre Bloch]].\n\n== Other work ==\n\nIn addition to her work as a soloist, Thomas is a passionate chamber musician. In 2011 and 2012, she is selected to participate in the Seiji Osawa International Academic in [[Switzerland]]. She has performed regularly with them alongside musicians such as Beatrice Berrut, Julien Libeer, Frank Braley, and G\u00e9rard Causs\u00e9.\n\nIn 2011, Thomas appeared in the film [[Un baiser papillon]], taking on the role of a cellist and performing [[Vivaldi]] [[concerti]] accompanied by the Orchestre des Solistes Fran\u00e7ais.\n\n== Instruments ==\n\nThomas has played{{when|date=April 2020}} a 1788 Ferdinand Gagliano cello, dubbed the [[Ch\u00e2teau Pape Cl\u00e9ment]], loaned to her by [[Bernard Magrez]], along with a bow by [[Eug\u00e8ne Sartory]] on extended loan from the Fondation Roi Baudoin - Fonds Bollandsee.<ref name=\"laphil-profile\">{{cite web|title=Camille Thomas {{pipe}} LA Phil|url=https://www.laphil.com/musicdb/artists/6719/camille-thomas|website=LA Phil|language=en|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince 24 September 2019, she has played the [[De Munck (Stradivarius)|De Munck-Feuermann]], a 1730 [[Stradivarius]] cello, loaned by the [[Nippon Music Foundation]] for a period of one year.<ref name=\"thestrad-feuermann\">{{cite web|title='De Munck, Feuermann' Stradivarius cello is loaned to Camille Thomas|url=https://www.thestrad.com/news/de-munck-feuermann-stradivarius-cello-is-loaned-to-camille-thomas/9506.article|website=The Strad|language=en|date=24 April 2019|access-date=19 April 2020|publication-date=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.fondationvocation.org/la-communaute-des-laureats.html Bleustein-Blanchet Vocational Foundation] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.fnbp.fr/-Notre-philosophie,40-.html Fondation Banque populaire Natixis] {{in lang|fr}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Camille}}\n[[Category:Classical cellists]]\n[[Category:Women classical cellists]]\n[[Category:Belgian cellists]]\n[[Category:Belgian classical cellists]]\n[[Category:French cellists]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Paris]]\n[[Category:Deutsche Grammophon artists]]\n\n[[fr:Camille Thomas]]\n", "name_user": "Laogeodritt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInstruments:- fix redlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camille_Thomas"}
{"title_page": "Prostitution in Lebanon", "text_new": "'''Prostitution in Lebanon''' is nominally legal and [[Regulated prostitution|regulated]].<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=23 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> However, no licences have been issued since 1975.<ref name=\"spl\" /><ref name=\"executive\">{{cite news|title= Prostitution \u2013 The business of sex|publisher= Executive Magazine|date=|url= http://www.executive-magazine.com/society/prostitution-the-business-of-sex|accessdate=2014-10-22}}</ref> In modern Lebanon prostitution takes place semi-officially via 'super night clubs', and illegally on the [[street prostitution|streets]], in bars, hotels and [[brothels]].<ref name=\"executive\" /> [[UNAIDS]] estimate there to be 4,220 prostitutes in the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nCases of [[child prostitution]] are known and prosecuted, but no measures are taken to [[Rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitate]] these juveniles.<ref>[http://gvnet.com/childprostitution/Lebanon.htm Child Prostitution \u2013 Lebanon]. Gvnet.com. Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> <ref>{{cite news|title= Madagascar maids: Misery in the Middle East  |work=[[BBC]]|date=|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14507719|accessdate=2012-04-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Sex trafficking]] is a problem in the Lebanon.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==Overview==\nStreet prostitution occurs in the country, the prostitutes are mainly Lebanese or Syrian.<ref name=\"executive\" /> Prostitution also occurs in 'bars', especially in the [[Hamra, Beirut|Hamra]] area of [[Beirut]] and in [[Maameltein]]. The bars are licensed, but not for prostitution. They usually have 'secret' rooms at the back and the women, mostly Egyptians, Syrians and Sudanese, are controlled by a \"Mom\". They keep their liquor licenses and a blind eye is turned to the illegal activities because of bribes to the police.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\nSome Lebanese prostitutes work independently from hotels or rented apartments.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\n[[Male prostitution]] is on the rise in the country.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Streib|first1=Matthew|title=Living outside of society: Palestinian refugee rentboys in the Lebanon|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2006/07/17/living-outside-of-society-palestinian-refugee-rentboys-in-the-lebanon/|website=PinkNews|accessdate=23 January 2018|format=17 July 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Du Verdie|first1=Paul|title=Male prostitution on the rise in Lebanon|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/02/male-prostitution-rise-lebanon-201425114310918216.html|website=Aljazeera|accessdate=23 January 2018|date=14 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Super night clubs===\nSuper night clubs serve as places of introduction between prostitutes and clients. The clients may chat with an 'artiste' if they buy a bottle of [[champagne]]. During the chat a 'date' may be arranged for the next day. No sexual services are permitted on the premises, and the woman negotiates her own price for the 'date'.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\nThe clubs operate with the implicit consent of the [[S\u00fbret\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale]] (General Directorate of General Security), who set strict regulations. The women working in the clubs must be foreign nationals, Lebanese women are not allowed in the clubs. The migrant women must have a contract to enter the country, and are issued with an 'artiste' visa, to which strict conditions are attached.<ref name=\"executive\" /><ref name=\"foreign\">{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Sulome|title=Sex for Sale in Beirut|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2012/02/09/sex-for-sale-in-beirut/|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=24 January 2018|language=en|date=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe women must be at the club between 8pm to 5am, S\u00fbret\u00e9 or police may enter the club at any time to check the artistes are all present. The women must live in a hotel room, often adjacent to or in the same building as the club. They must be in the hotel between finishing work (5am) until 1pm. After 1pm they may leave the hotel on a 'date'. The telephone number and car registration number of the client must be recorded when the women leave the hotel.<ref name=\"executive\" /><ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nThere are about 130 clubs, mainly in Maameltein. A lot of the women working in them are of East European and North African origin.<ref name=\"state17\" /> 11,284 women entered Lebanon under the 'artiste' program in 2016, more than double the number of women that entered under this program in 2015.<ref name=\"state17\" /> Their artiste visas do not exceed six months, and they are deported if they are caught overstaying their visa.<ref name=\"US state\">{{cite web|url=http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119120.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226175704/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119120.htm|url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-26|title=2008 Human Rights Report: Lebanon|date=2009-02-25|website=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|publisher=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=20 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1931, whilst the country was under French control,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stmaron.org/marhist11.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060629110712/http://stmaron.org/marhist11.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2006 |title=Aspects of Maronite History (Part Eleven) The twentieth century in Western Asia |author=Beggiani, Chorbishop Sex and suck boobs are ok.|publisher=Stmaron.org |access-date=17 January 2013 }}</ref> a new law regulated prostitution. Prostitutes needed to be registered and were only allowed to work in licensed brothels. To obtain a licence they had to be over 21, not be a [[virgin]] and have undergone a medical examination. The law criminalised working anywhere else. It also criminalised anybody facilitating working outside licence requirements.<ref name=\"spl\" />\n\nAt the start of the [[Lebanese Civil War]] in 1975, all of the licensed brothels were located near [[Martyrs' Square, Beirut|Martyrs' Square]] in the Zeitoun district of downtown Beirut. All these brothels were destroyed during the fighting.<ref name=\"executive\" /> No licences have been issued since to prostitutes or brothels.<ref name=\"spl\" /><ref name=\"executive\" /><ref name=\"foreign\" />\n\nAs a result of licences not being issued, brothels operated illegally until a new law was passed in 1998 criminalising businesses making rooms available for commercial sex.<ref name=\"spl\" />\n\nThe \"super night clubs\" were originally regular night clubs catering to the tourist trade in the 1960s. They closed down during the Civil War, and after the end of the war there were insufficient tourists to make them viable. The business model was changed to its current format and the clubs reopened.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\n==Syrian Civil War==\nThe [[Civil War in Syria]] has led to an influx of Syrian refugees into the sex trade in Lebanon. Syrian women and girls are highly vulnerable to sex trafficking.<ref name=\"state17\" /> Some adult refugee women have been coerced into prostitution. A forced prostitution ring, run by a Syrian pimp, was dismantled in 2016 by Lebanese police, which raided the ''Chez Maurice'' and ''le Silver'' brothels, both located in the Maameltein, known for its red-light district.<ref name=\"lemonde\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/proche-orient/article/2016/07/30/les-refugiees-syriennes-au-liban-proies-des-proxenetes_4976500_3218.html|title=Les r\u00e9fugi\u00e9es syriennes au Liban, proies des prox\u00e9n\u00e8tes|date=30 July 2016|newspaper=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref> The majority of the women and girls were recruited from Syria with false promises of work and subjected to commercial sexual exploitation where they experienced mental, physical, and sexual abuse and forced abortions.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Lebanon}}\nLebanon is a source and destination country for women and children subjected to sex trafficking and a transit country for Eastern European women and children subjected to sex trafficking in other Middle Eastern countries. Women from Eastern Europe and North Africa enter Lebanon to work in the adult entertainment industry through Lebanon's artiste visa program, which sustains a significant commercial sex industry and enables sex trafficking. Some women from East and West Africa are subjected to sex trafficking in Lebanon.<ref name=\"state17\">{{cite web|title=Lebanon 2017 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271225.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703181335/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271225.htm|url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2017|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=24 January 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nSyrian women and girls are highly vulnerable to sex trafficking. Syrian girls are brought to Lebanon for sex trafficking, sometimes through the guise of early marriage. Lebanese pimps coerce some Syrian LGBTI refugees into prostitution.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nThe 2011 anti-trafficking law prohibits all forms of human trafficking. Prescribed penalties for sex trafficking range from five to 15 years imprisonment, which are sufficiently stringent and commensurate with those prescribed for other serious crimes, such as rape.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nIn 2016, the internal security forces (ISF) anti-trafficking unit investigated 20 cases of suspected trafficking, involving 87 victims of sexual exploitation and child trafficking, and referred 26 suspected traffickers to the judiciary. The directorate of general security (DGS) investigated 14 potential trafficking cases involving artiste visa holders and four were referred to judicial or law enforcement authorities for further investigation.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nThe [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] ranks Lebanon as a '[[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 2]]' country.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2016/Apr-12/347039-police-close-3-brothels-in-lebanons-red-light-district.ashx Police Close 3 Brothels]\n*[https://genrehistoire.revues.org/1781 History of prostitution in Lebanon] (in French)\n\n{{Asia in topic|Prostitution in}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution by country|Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Lebanese society]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in the Middle East|Lebanon]]\n", "text_old": "'''Prostitution in Lebanon''' is nominally legal and [[Regulated prostitution|regulated]].<ref name=\"spl\">{{cite web|title=Sex Work Law - Countries|url=http://spl.ids.ac.uk/sexworklaw/countries|website=Sexuality, Poverty and Law|accessdate=23 January 2018|language=en}}</ref> However, no licences have been issued since 1975.<ref name=\"spl\" /><ref name=\"executive\">{{cite news|title= Prostitution \u2013 The business of sex|publisher= Executive Magazine|date=|url= http://www.executive-magazine.com/society/prostitution-the-business-of-sex|accessdate=2014-10-22}}</ref> In modern Lebanon prostitution takes place semi-officially via 'super night clubs', and illegally on the [[street prostitution|streets]], in bars, hotels and [[brothels]].<ref name=\"executive\" /> [[UNAIDS]] estimate there to be 4,220 prostitutes in the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sex workers: Population size estimate - Number, 2016 |url=http://www.aidsinfoonline.org/gam/stock/shared/dv/PivotData_2018_7_22_636678151733621264.htm |website=www.aidsinfoonline.org |publisher=UNAIDS |accessdate=21 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nCases of [[child prostitution]] are known and prosecuted, but no measures are taken to [[Rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitate]] these juveniles.<ref>[http://gvnet.com/childprostitution/Lebanon.htm Child Prostitution \u2013 Lebanon]. Gvnet.com. Retrieved on 2011-03-30.</ref> <ref>{{cite news|title= Madagascar maids: Misery in the Middle East  |work=[[BBC]]|date=|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-14507719|accessdate=2012-04-11}}</ref>\n\n[[Sex trafficking]] is a problem in the Lebanon.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==Overview==\nStreet prostitution occurs in the country, the prostitutes are mainly Lebanese or Syrian.<ref name=\"executive\" /> Prostitution also occurs in 'bars', especially in the [[Hamra, Beirut|Hamra]] area of [[Beirut]] and in [[Maameltein]]. The bars are licensed, but not for prostitution. They usually have 'secret' rooms at the back and the women, mostly Egyptians, Syrians and Sudanese, are controlled by a \"Mom\". They keep their liquor licenses and a blind eye is turned to the illegal activities because of bribes to the police.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\nSome Lebanese prostitutes work independently from hotels or rented apartments.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\n[[Male prostitution]] is on the rise in the country.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Streib|first1=Matthew|title=Living outside of society: Palestinian refugee rentboys in the Lebanon|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2006/07/17/living-outside-of-society-palestinian-refugee-rentboys-in-the-lebanon/|website=PinkNews|accessdate=23 January 2018|format=17 July 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Du Verdie|first1=Paul|title=Male prostitution on the rise in Lebanon|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2014/02/male-prostitution-rise-lebanon-201425114310918216.html|website=Aljazeera|accessdate=23 January 2018|date=14 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Super night clubs===\nSuper night clubs serve as places of introduction between prostitutes and clients. The clients may chat with an 'artiste' if they buy a bottle of [[champagne]]. During the chat a 'date' may be arranged for the next day. No sexual services are permitted on the premises, and the woman negotiates her own price for the 'date'.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\nThe clubs operate with the implicit consent of the [[S\u00fbret\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale]] (General Directorate of General Security), who set strict regulations. The women working in the clubs must be foreign nationals, Lebanese women are not allowed in the clubs. The migrant women must have a contract to enter the country, and are issued with an 'artiste' visa, to which strict conditions are attached.<ref name=\"executive\" /><ref name=\"foreign\">{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Sulome|title=Sex for Sale in Beirut|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2012/02/09/sex-for-sale-in-beirut/|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=24 January 2018|language=en|date=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe women must be at the club between 8pm to 5am, S\u00fbret\u00e9 or police may enter the club at any time to check the artistes are all present. The women must live in a hotel room, often adjacent to or in the same building as the club. They must be in the hotel between finishing work (5am) until 1pm. After 1pm they may leave the hotel on a 'date'. The telephone number and car registration number of the client must be recorded when the women leave the hotel.<ref name=\"executive\" /><ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nThere are about 130 clubs, mainly in Maameltein. A lot of the women working in them are of East European and North African origin.<ref name=\"state17\" /> 11,284 women entered Lebanon under the 'artiste' program in 2016, more than double the number of women that entered under this program in 2015.<ref name=\"state17\" /> Their artiste visas do not exceed six months, and they are deported if they are caught overstaying their visa.<ref name=\"US state\">{{cite web|url=http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119120.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226175704/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2008/nea/119120.htm|url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-26|title=2008 Human Rights Report: Lebanon|date=2009-02-25|website=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor|publisher=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=20 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1931, whilst the country was under French control,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stmaron.org/marhist11.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060629110712/http://stmaron.org/marhist11.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2006 |title=Aspects of Maronite History (Part Eleven) The twentieth century in Western Asia |author=Beggiani, Chorbishop Seely |publisher=Stmaron.org |access-date=17 January 2013 }}</ref> a new law regulated prostitution. Prostitutes needed to be registered and were only allowed to work in licensed brothels. To obtain a licence they had to be over 21, not be a [[virgin]] and have undergone a medical examination. The law criminalised working anywhere else. It also criminalised anybody facilitating working outside licence requirements.<ref name=\"spl\" />\n\nAt the start of the [[Lebanese Civil War]] in 1975, all of the licensed brothels were located near [[Martyrs' Square, Beirut|Martyrs' Square]] in the Zeitoun district of downtown Beirut. All these brothels were destroyed during the fighting.<ref name=\"executive\" /> No licences have been issued since to prostitutes or brothels.<ref name=\"spl\" /><ref name=\"executive\" /><ref name=\"foreign\" />\n\nAs a result of licences not being issued, brothels operated illegally until a new law was passed in 1998 criminalising businesses making rooms available for commercial sex.<ref name=\"spl\" />\n\nThe \"super night clubs\" were originally regular night clubs catering to the tourist trade in the 1960s. They closed down during the Civil War, and after the end of the war there were insufficient tourists to make them viable. The business model was changed to its current format and the clubs reopened.<ref name=\"executive\" />\n\n==Syrian Civil War==\nThe [[Civil War in Syria]] has led to an influx of Syrian refugees into the sex trade in Lebanon. Syrian women and girls are highly vulnerable to sex trafficking.<ref name=\"state17\" /> Some adult refugee women have been coerced into prostitution. A forced prostitution ring, run by a Syrian pimp, was dismantled in 2016 by Lebanese police, which raided the ''Chez Maurice'' and ''le Silver'' brothels, both located in the Maameltein, known for its red-light district.<ref name=\"lemonde\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/proche-orient/article/2016/07/30/les-refugiees-syriennes-au-liban-proies-des-proxenetes_4976500_3218.html|title=Les r\u00e9fugi\u00e9es syriennes au Liban, proies des prox\u00e9n\u00e8tes|date=30 July 2016|newspaper=Le Monde.fr|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref> The majority of the women and girls were recruited from Syria with false promises of work and subjected to commercial sexual exploitation where they experienced mental, physical, and sexual abuse and forced abortions.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==Sex trafficking==\n{{see also|Human trafficking in Lebanon}}\nLebanon is a source and destination country for women and children subjected to sex trafficking and a transit country for Eastern European women and children subjected to sex trafficking in other Middle Eastern countries. Women from Eastern Europe and North Africa enter Lebanon to work in the adult entertainment industry through Lebanon's artiste visa program, which sustains a significant commercial sex industry and enables sex trafficking. Some women from East and West Africa are subjected to sex trafficking in Lebanon.<ref name=\"state17\">{{cite web|title=Lebanon 2017 Trafficking in Persons Report|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271225.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703181335/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2017/271225.htm|url-status=dead |archive-date=3 July 2017|website=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=24 January 2018}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\nSyrian women and girls are highly vulnerable to sex trafficking. Syrian girls are brought to Lebanon for sex trafficking, sometimes through the guise of early marriage. Lebanese pimps coerce some Syrian LGBTI refugees into prostitution.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nThe 2011 anti-trafficking law prohibits all forms of human trafficking. Prescribed penalties for sex trafficking range from five to 15 years imprisonment, which are sufficiently stringent and commensurate with those prescribed for other serious crimes, such as rape.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nIn 2016, the internal security forces (ISF) anti-trafficking unit investigated 20 cases of suspected trafficking, involving 87 victims of sexual exploitation and child trafficking, and referred 26 suspected traffickers to the judiciary. The directorate of general security (DGS) investigated 14 potential trafficking cases involving artiste visa holders and four were referred to judicial or law enforcement authorities for further investigation.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\nThe [[United States Department of State]] [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] ranks Lebanon as a '[[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|Tier 2]]' country.<ref name=\"state17\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2016/Apr-12/347039-police-close-3-brothels-in-lebanons-red-light-district.ashx Police Close 3 Brothels]\n*[https://genrehistoire.revues.org/1781 History of prostitution in Lebanon] (in French)\n\n{{Asia in topic|Prostitution in}}\n\n[[Category:Prostitution by country|Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Lebanese society]]\n[[Category:Prostitution in the Middle East|Lebanon]]\n", "name_user": "60.242.72.21", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prostitution_in_Lebanon"}
{"title_page": "Landmark Hotel & Casino", "text_new": "{{Infobox Casino\n| casino        = Landmark\n| logo          = Landmark Hotel & Casino Logo.png\n| logo_size     = \n| image         = Landmark hotel 1986.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| image_caption = The Landmark in 1986, four years before closure, and nine years before implosion\n| address       = 364 Convention Center Drive<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Diana Ross reaches out and touches Las Vegas audiences at Caesars |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/120914330/ |website=The Arizona Republic |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=July 21, 1985 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com |quote=The Landmark Hotel is located at 364 Convention Center Drive [...].}}</ref>\n|location=[[Paradise, Nevada]] 89109\n| coordinates   = {{coord|36.133051|-115.155808|region:US-NV_type:landmark|display=title, inline}}\n| date_opened   = July 1, 1969\n| names_pre     = \n| date_closed   = {{end date and age|August 8, 1990}}\n| casino_type   = Land\n| owner         = {{collapsible list|title=List|Frank Caroll (1961\u201366)<br/>Plaza Tower, Inc (1966\u201369)<br>[[Hughes Tool Company]] (1969\u201373)<br>[[Summa Corporation]] (1973\u201378)<br>Lou and Jo Ann Tickel (1978\u201380)<br>Zula Wolfram (1978\u201383)<br/>Bill Morris (1983\u201390)<br/>[[Lloyds Bank]] (1990\u201393)<br/>[[Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority]](1993\u201395)}}\n| architect     = '''Initial design''':<br>Gerald Moffitt<br>Ed Hendricks<br>'''1966 design''':<br>George Tate<br>Thomas Dobrusky\n| theme         = [[Inca Empire|Incan]]<br>[[Space Age]]\n| rooms         = 503 (1969)<br>524 (1977)<br>498 (1990)\n| space_gaming  = {{convert|14000|sqft|abbr=on}} (ground floor)<br>{{convert|3000|sqft|abbr=on}} (29th floor)\n| attractions   = \n| notable_restaurants   = \n| renovations   = 1971, 1983\n| website       = \n}}\n\nThe '''Landmark'''{{efn|Commonly known simply as the \"Landmark\". During the 1960s, it was also known as \"Landmark Tower\",<ref name=LivesUp/><ref name=NewLife/><ref name=OnAgain/> and sometimes as \"Landmark Hotel\";<ref name=WayUp/><ref name=Pearlman/> the latter name was in common usage from 1969 onward.<ref name=REG/><ref name=Ohio/><ref name=Facelift/><ref name=BankBuys/> \"Landmark Hotel and Casino\" received some usage as well.<ref name=NYT/><ref name=NYE/><ref name=Foster/>}} was a [[hotel]] and [[casino]] located in [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]], [[Nevada]], east of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] and across from the [[Las Vegas Convention Center]]. The resort included a 31-floor tower, inspired by the design of the [[Space Needle]] tower in [[Seattle]]. Frank Caroll, the project's original owner, purchased the property in 1961. Fremont Construction began work on the tower that September, while Caroll opened the adjacent Landmark Plaza shopping center and Landmark Apartments by the end of the year. The tower's completion was expected for early 1963, but because of a lack of financing, construction was stopped in 1962, with the resort approximately 80 percent complete. Up to 1969, the [[Topping out|topped-off]] tower was the [[List of tallest buildings in Nevada|tallest building in Nevada]] until the completion of the [[Westgate Las Vegas Resort & Casino|International Hotel]] across the street.\n\nIn 1966, the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|Central Teamsters Pension Fund]] provided a $5.5 million construction loan to finish the project, with ownership transferred to a group of investors that included Caroll and his wife. The Landmark's completion and opening was delayed several more times. In April 1968, Caroll withdrew his request for a gaming license after he was charged with [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] against the project's interior designer. The Landmark was put up for sale that month.\n\nBillionaire [[Howard Hughes]], through [[Hughes Tool Company]], purchased the Landmark in 1969 at a cost of $17.3 million. Hughes spent approximately $3 million to add his own touches to the resort before opening it on July 1, 1969, with 400 [[slot machine]]s and 503 hotel rooms. In addition to a {{convert|14000|sqft|abbr=on}} ground-floor casino, the resort also had a second, smaller casino on the 29th floor; it was the first high-rise casino in Nevada. Aside from the second casino, the five-story [[cupola]] dome at the top of the tower also featured restaurants, lounges, and a night club.\n\nDuring the 1970s, the Landmark became known for its performances by [[country music]] artists. The resort also played host to celebrities such as [[Danny Thomas]] and [[Frank Sinatra]]. However, the resort suffered financial problems after its opening and underwent several ownership changes, none of which resulted in success. The Landmark entered bankruptcy in 1985, and ultimately closed on August 8, 1990, unable to compete with new megaresorts. The [[Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority]] purchased the property in September 1993, and demolished the resort in November 1995, to add a 2,200-space parking lot for its convention center. In 2019, work was underway on a convention center expansion which includes the former site of the Landmark.\n\n== History ==\nFrank Caroll, also known as Frank Caracciolo,<ref>{{cite news|title=Howard Hughes confirms offer to buy Tower hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=October 24, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929092236/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> was a building developer from Kansas City. In 1960, he and his wife Susan decided to construct a hotel-casino and shopping center in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=QOTD/> Frank Caroll received a gaming license that year.<ref name=Nov66/> In 1961, the Carolls purchased {{convert|22|acre|abbr=on}} of land at the northwest corner of Convention Center Drive and [[Paradise Road (Las Vegas)|Paradise Road]] in [[Paradise, Nevada]],<ref name=lvs1>{{cite news |title=Implosions |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/history/implosions/ |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |accessdate=September 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716202302/https://lasvegassun.com/history/implosions/ |archivedate=July 16, 2017 }}</ref> approximately half a mile east of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] and across from the [[Las Vegas Convention Center]].<ref name=Finishing/><ref name=NewSkyline/> Aside from a gas station, the property was vacant.<ref name=QOTD/>\n\n===Construction (1961\u201368)===\n====Commencement====\nThe Landmark was initially planned as a 14-story hotel with a casino, although the floor count increased as the project progressed.<ref name=NewLife2/> Fremont Construction, owned by Louis P. Scherer of [[Redlands, California]],<ref name=SeenCalif/> began construction of the tower at the end of September 1961, under a $1.5 million contract.<ref name=Scherer61>{{cite news|title=Scherer building Las Vegas Landmark Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381236/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Redlands Daily Facts]]|date=October 14, 1961|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011756/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381236/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Scherer/> Frank Caroll's company, Caroll Construction Company, also worked on the tower.<ref name=InsideBubble>{{cite news|title=Inside the Bubble|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-16-1962-421918/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 16, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> At the start of construction, the tower was to include 20 stories,<ref name=Scherer61/> while completion was planned for early 1963.<ref name=Scherer>{{cite news|title=$2.5 million for completion: Scherer awarded contract to finish Vegas project|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11380987/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=August 23, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011849/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11380987/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> The tower was built on a five-foot-thick base of concrete and steel, measuring 80 feet in diameter and resting on a base of [[caliche]] that descended 30 feet into the ground.<ref name=SeenCalif/> Consolidated Construction Company was the concrete subcontractor for the tower.<ref name=InsideBubble/>\n\nBy December 1961,<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambling Applicants Approved|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/148272289/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=December 19, 1961|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093132/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/148272289/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> Caroll had opened the two-story Landmark Plaza shopping center,<ref name=Elevator/><ref name=Vegas7/> built out in an L-shape<ref name=NewLife/><ref name=NewLife2/> at the base of the tower.<ref name=Elevator/><ref name=OnAgain/> The Landmark Apartments, with 120 units,<ref name=Hofferd>{{cite news|title=Hofferd Named Manager of Landmark Tower Hotel|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-10-1962-420675/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 10, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> were also built near the tower and operational by the end of 1961.<ref name=LHM>{{cite web|title=Landmark Construction|url=https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/construction|website=Landmark Hotel Memorial|accessdate=September 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093112/https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/construction|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Apartments|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-23-1962-420651/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 23, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In 1962, a bar known as Shannon's Saloon and a western music radio station, KVEG, began operating in the Landmark Plaza.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ear to the Door|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-22-1962-424151/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 22, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=KVEG1/><ref name=KVEG2/> In addition to studios, KVEG also had its offices in the shopping center.<ref name=KVEG1>{{cite news|title=Radio KVEG Makes Debut In Las Vegas|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-23-1962-421812/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 23, 1963|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=KVEG2>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-27-1962-421730/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 27, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nBy February 1962, the tower was planned to include 31 floors, making it the [[List of tallest buildings in Nevada|tallest building in Nevada]]. While plans for a separate hotel structure were being made, work began by pouring concrete on a continuous 24-hour schedule. The concrete pour was done with a [[slip forming]] method. With 21 floors expected to be added to the tower over a 12-day period, it was expected to reach the 24th floor by the end of the month.<ref name=LivesUp>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Lives Up To Its Name|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-21-1962-420693/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 21, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Inspect>{{cite news|title=Inspect Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-14-1962-420636/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 14, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In March 1962, at the request of Caroll, [[Clark County Commission]]ers removed a restriction which specified that gaming licenses could only be issued for ground-level casinos, as Caroll wanted to open a casino on the second floor of the Landmark's shopping center.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambling Rises In the World\u2013Up to 2nd Floor|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381262/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Reno Evening Gazette]]|date=March 14, 1962|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924092959/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381262/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Casinos May Now Move Off Ground Levels|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-13-1962-420940/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 13, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> That month, Caroll received a $450,000 loan from Appliance Buyers Credit Corporation (ABCC),<ref name=May18-66/><ref name=May18-66B/> a subsidiary of [[Whirlpool Corporation|RCA-Whirlpool]].<ref name=PlansFiled/>\n\nConstruction had reached the 26th floor by the end of April 1962. Upon completion of the floor, work was to begin on the tower's bubble dome.<ref name=WayUp>{{cite news|title=Way Up|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-22-1962-424163/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 22, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> By June 1962, ABCC loaned an additional $300,000 to Caroll, who reached his $3 million loan limit with the company.<ref name=May18-66>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower May Finally Have Owner (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-18-1966-420724/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 18, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=May18-66B>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower May Finally Have Owner (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-18-1966-420717/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 18, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Caroll ultimately owed ABCC a total of $3.5 million.<ref name=PlansFiled/> In August 1962, the Landmark tower was designated as a civilian [[fallout shelter]], with the capacity to hold 3,500 people after its completion.<ref name=Shelter>{{cite news|title=Select Shelter|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-17-1962-420997/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 17, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> That month, work was underway on the steel framework base for the tower's glass bubble dome.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saucer in the Air|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-aug-21-1962-p-8/|accessdate=February 8, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 21, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nBy September 1962, the Landmark tower was nearing completion and had become the tallest building in Las Vegas<ref name=Sep1962>{{cite news|title=Pointing Skyward|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-25-1962-420754/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 25, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> and the state,<ref name=Inspect/><ref name=AP-1965/><ref name=To-Open/> being visible from 20 miles away.<ref name=AP-1965/> By that time, many stores in the Landmark Plaza had closed due to falling debris that included welding sparks, steel, tools, rivets, and cement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-28-1962-421803/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 28, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> A construction delay occurred in September 1962, when shipments of steel for the tower's dome were deemed inadequate and crews had to wait for new shipments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-25-1962-421810/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 25, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Construction was progressing rapidly on the tower's dome during October 1962, with steel and concrete still being added to the tower.<ref>{{cite news|title=Giant in Sky|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-30-1962-421930/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 30, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Completion was still scheduled for early 1963.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gigantic Mushroom|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-23-1962-421945/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 23, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The Aluminium Division of Apex Steel Corporation Limited was contracted to install a $40,000 aluminum undershine on the tower's dome, to provide a maintenance-free and clean-looking appearance for viewers on the ground. Crews used scaffolding and hoists to reach the area where aluminum sheets needed to be placed. Each day, it took crews 18 minutes to be lifted up. Due to delays arising from strong winds, it took crews two months for the aluminium to be attached.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Tale Revealed|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-24-1963-421912/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 24, 1963|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Delay====\nIn December 1962, construction of the tower was stopped when ABCC denied further funding and alleged that the Carolls had defaulted on payments.<ref name=May18-66B/><ref name=Suit1963/> The 31-story tower had been [[Topping out|topped off]] and the resort was approximately 80 percent complete, with $5 million already spent on the project.<ref name=AP-1965/> The tower's planned opening was delayed until April 1963,<ref>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-07-1962-421923/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 7, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> but it did not occur as scheduled. In May 1963, ABCC was planning a sale of the apartments, shopping center, and unfinished tower for the following month. The Carolls sought to halt the sale, and filed a $2.1 million damage suit against ABCC, alleging that the company stopped construction and refused to pay the contractors.<ref name=Suit1963>{{cite news|title=Damage Suit Filed Over New Facility|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874595/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=July 13, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=May 21, 1963|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013505/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874595/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> An [[injunction]] against [[foreclosure]] was granted in June 1963,<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Foreclosure Halted|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-19-1963-421902/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 19, 1963|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> but was later dissolved in August 1964.<ref name=May18-66B/><ref name=HeadsAuction>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Heads For Auction|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-22-1964-425411/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 22, 1964|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In October 1964, a sale of the tower was approved for later that month, after being requested by ABCC, which was still owed $3.5 million by Landmark Plaza Corporation. Up to that time, the tower had been appraised several times and was valued between $8 million and $9 million.<ref name=HeadsAuction/><ref name=Auction64>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Auction Slated|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707140/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=July 13, 2017|agency=United Press International|work=Nevada State Journal|date=October 6, 1964|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013629/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707140/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> Ownership subsequently changed, as did the resort's design plans.<ref name=AP-1965/>\n\nIn August 1965, Maury Friedman was working on a deal with [[RCA Victor]] to convert the Landmark's tower and apartment buildings into office space.<ref>{{cite news|title=Around the Horn|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-30-1965-421860/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 30, 1965|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> By the following month, Inter-Nation Tower, Inc. \u2013 a Beverly Hills-based corporation \u2013 was negotiating with RCA-Whirlpool to develop the tower and adjacent land as an international market place, an idea that was supported by local retailers and resorts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Here's the latest on the future of the Landmark Tower|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-14-1965-421886/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 14, 1965|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In December 1965, architect Gerald Moffitt said the Landmark's design had gone through many revisions and that his design plans had been impounded by a court; a spokesman said there were no plans to resume construction in the near future. It was estimated that an additional six months were needed to complete the tower.<ref name=AP-1965>{{cite news|last=Lengel|first=John|title=Nevada's Tallest Unoccupied Structure: Landmark Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438084/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|agency=Associated Press|date=December 27, 1965|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924095245/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438084/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe unfinished tower became an eyesore for visitors to the nearby convention center.<ref name=OnAgain/> During its vacancy, people noted that the building appeared to be tilted, similar to the [[Leaning Tower of Pisa]]; experts stated that this was an illusion caused when the building was viewed with nearby [[power pole]]s, which were tilted rather than the building itself.<ref name=AP-1965/><ref>{{cite news|title=Leaning Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438148/pensacola_news_journal/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=[[Pensacola News Journal]]|date=June 1, 1962|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929091137/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438148/pensacola_news_journal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Thoughts>{{cite news|title=Thoughts While Shaving|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-06-1962-420704/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 6, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Local residents nicknamed it the \"Leaning Tower of Plaza\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Hertz|first=Murray|title=Sun Dial|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-10-1962-421766/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 10, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> the \"Leaning Tower of Las Vegas\", and \"[[Folly|Frank's Folly]].\"<ref name=QOTD>{{cite news|title=Question of the Day|url=https://www.lasvegasadvisor.com/question/2007-05-14/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Advisor|date=May 14, 2007}}</ref> Moffitt said, \"It doesn't tilt. There is only three-eights of an inch difference in diameter from top to bottom.\"<ref name=AP-1965/> In May 1966, early negotiations were being held with a prospective buyer of the Landmark.<ref name=TalkProgress>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Talk in Progress|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-26-1966-420776/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 26, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Resumption====\nIn July 1966, new design plans were filed with the county for the completion of the tower.<ref name=PlansFiled>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Plans Filed in Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707018/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=August 9, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=July 6, 1966}}</ref> Scherer planned to acquire additional property for use as a parking lot to accommodate the redesigned project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flash|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-08-1966-421968/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 8, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=PlansFiled/> In August 1966, the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|Central Teamsters Pension Fund]] provided a $5.5 million construction loan for the project.<ref name=NewLife>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower--New Life (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-17-1966-420736/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 17, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=NewLife2>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower--New Life (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-17-1966-420734/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 17, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Resume/> By that time, ownership had been transferred to Plaza Tower, Inc., made up of several investors, including the Carolls and Scherer, whose construction company was awarded a $2.5 million contract to finish the Landmark tower. Because of legal problems involved with the project, the acquisition of title required over 5,000 hours of legal work and the settlement of more than 40 lawsuits.<ref name=Resume>{{cite news|title=Vegas Hotel Construction to Resume|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381501/independent/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Press-Telegram|Independent]]|date=August 19, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381501/independent/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Scherer/><ref>{{cite news|title=Work to Be Resumed on Las Vegas Casino|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381499/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 19, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013638/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381499/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> Construction was underway again in early September 1966,<ref>{{cite news|last=Cronan|first=John|title=Only on Sunday|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-04-1966-424148/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 4, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> with completion expected in early 1967.<ref name=Scherer/> The shops and taverns in the Landmark Plaza were closed,<ref name=OnAgain/><ref>{{cite news|title=Last Wake|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-26-1966-421977/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 26, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Spot|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-26-1966-421996/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 26, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> and the shopping center and gas station were demolished,<ref name=OnAgain/> so the land around the tower could be used to construct a casino, a hotel lobby, offices, and new shops.<ref name=NewLife/><ref name=NewLife2/> The adjacent Landmark apartments were to be converted into hotel rooms for the new resort.<ref name=Scherer/>\n\nIn November 1966, Caroll planned to install two slot machines inside the Landmark Coffee Shop, which sold food to construction workers from inside a temporary structure that was to become the site of a permanent building eventually. Caroll's plans were denied as his gaming license did not apply to the coffee shop. At the time, Caroll was also accused by sheriff [[Ralph Lamb]] of being uncooperative with police officers who were searching for a [[hoodlum]] at the Landmark Apartments.<ref name=Nov66>{{cite news|title=Landmark Builder Told 'License Down Drain'|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-11-1966-420950/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 11, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Landmark had been scheduled to open on September 15, 1967, but its opening was further delayed because of construction problems. In October 1967, a new opening date of November 15 was announced, with an official [[grand opening]] to be held on December 31, 1967.<ref name=The-News>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel Delays Opening in Las Vegas|url=http://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/9c03b6_1e36dace30794cd0b4c01329a4c25b9a.pdf|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=The News|location=Van Nuys, California|date=October 17, 1967|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012936/http://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/9c03b6_1e36dace30794cd0b4c01329a4c25b9a.pdf|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> In early November 1967, Scherer was awarded a $2.2 million contract for the final construction phase of the Landmark. Construction crews worked 24 hours a day for each day of the week during the final phase to have the 650-seat dinner showroom theater ready for the planned New Year's Eve opening. Also included in the final phase were clothing and jewelry shops, as well as a recreation area with swimming pools and a 20-foot waterfall.<ref>{{cite news|title=$2.183 million in Las Vegas: Scherer gets Tower bid|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707078/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=August 9, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=November 1, 1967|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011846/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707078/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy the time of its planned New Year's Eve opening, the tower was nearly complete, with an opening now scheduled for mid-January 1968.<ref name=Pittsburgh>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Harold V.|title=At Random: Report From Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381025/pittsburgh_postgazette/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 27, 1967|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012355/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381025/pittsburgh_postgazette/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> In December 1967, two groups \u2013 Plaza Tower Inc., the property's landlord group; and Plaza Tower Operating Corporation, the casino operating group \u2013 submitted a request for a gaming license to the [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]], which investigates licensees and top casino employees prior to issuing gaming licenses.<ref name=OnAgain/> The Landmark's opening did not occur as scheduled.<ref name=Withdraws/>\n\nDuring February and March 1968, the Landmark was declared as being completed,<ref name=Pearlman>{{cite news|last=Pearlman|first=Ralph|title=Vegas Daze and Nights|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-24-1968-424123/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 24, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=World's Greatest|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-25-1968-427258/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 25, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com|quote=The completed, but as yet unopened Landmark Tower hotel.}}</ref><ref name=OnAgain/><ref name=Objection/> although it was stated the following year that some construction work remained unfinished.<ref name=Revamping/> At the time of its stated completion in 1968, a total of 200,000 hours had been spent working on the project, which used 100,000 yards of concrete and 100 tons of steel.<ref name=Apr6-68>{{cite news|title=One Never Knows\u2026 Until One Goes!|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-06-1968-424133/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 6, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The tower occupied {{convert|8.21|acre|abbr=on}} of the property,<ref>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Home, Downtown Taxes Jump Oftener Than Strip|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-21-1969-425421/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 21, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> and remained as the tallest building in the state.<ref name=Hughes-Pay/>\n\n===Further developments (1968\u201369)===\n====Gaming license====\nIn February 1968, an updated list of top casino employees was submitted to the gaming control board, which had up to 90 days to make a decision regarding the issuance of a gaming license. An opening date of mid-April 1968 was considered possible.<ref name=OnAgain/> In March 1968, the Nevada Gaming Control Board recommended against the issuance of a gaming license due to \"inadequate financial capabilities and resources of the operating corporation and of its principal investor\", referring to Caroll.<ref name=Withdraws/> However, the [[Nevada Gaming Commission]] had the Gaming Control Board reevaluate the license application.<ref name=Apr22-68/><ref name=BidWithdraw/>\n\nOn April 5, 1968, the Las Vegas media was given a tour of the Landmark.<ref name=Apr6-68/> During the event, Caroll beat the Landmark's interior designer, Leonard Edward England, for allegedly flirting with Caroll's wife. Caroll was arrested on April 17, 1968, on charges of [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] against England.<ref name=Trial>{{cite news|title=Frank Caroll Trial Slated|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-19-1968-422046/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 19, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=BidWithdraw/><ref name=DA/><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Against Casino Owner: $725,000 Assault Suit Filed|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-oct-26-1968-p-3/|accessdate=February 8, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 26, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> On April 22, 1968, Caroll withdrew his request for a gaming license,<ref name=Apr22-68>{{cite news|title=Caroll Rescinds Gaming Request For Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-23-1968-422070/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 23, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> a decision that was approved two days later.<ref name=BidWithdraw>{{cite news|title=Bid To Withdraw Gaming License Given Approval|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-25-1968-422079/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 25, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The company then planned to receive new financing and to eventually submit a new gaming application. Approximately 600 people were expected to be employed at the Landmark upon its opening.<ref name=Withdraws>{{cite news|title=Vegas Casino Withdraws Game License Application|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707244/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=August 9, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=April 25, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012306/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707244/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> The Landmark was put up for sale in April 1968,<ref name=Sun-Realty/> and the charges against Caroll were dropped two months later on the condition that he not renew his gaming license application.<ref name=DA>{{cite news|title=Landmark Owner Sees D.A. Dismiss Charges|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-13-1968-422089/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 13, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Many Unanswered Questions Follow Franklin Action|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-18-1968-420919/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 18, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Plane crash====\nOn the night of August 2, 1968, 39-year-old Everett Wayne Shaw, a mechanic depressed by the break-up of his month-long marriage, stole a [[Cessna 180]] plane as part of an apparent suicide attempt. Shaw flew the plane toward the Landmark tower and pulled up just before hitting it. The plane brushed the top of the tower before crashing into the Las Vegas Convention Center across the street, approximately {{convert|200|yd}} away. Shaw was killed in the crash, which did not harm anyone else. Plane debris was found on the Landmark's roof and at its base, but the crash was not believed to have caused any damage to the building.<ref>{{cite news|title=Body Recovered From Wreck; Police Hunt Other Victims|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-03-1968-420805/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 3, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Police Hint Suicide In Plane Crash|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-04-1968-422106/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 4, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Vegas Plane Crash Considered Suicide|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/78950635/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|agency=United Press International|work=Nevada State Journal|date=August 4, 1968|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924050458/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/78950635/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Plane Crash Into Tower Held Suicide|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/166582890/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 4, 1968|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924044908/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/166582890/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Financial problems====\nIn May 1968, the Teamsters Pension Fund filed a notice of breach on the trust deed, alleging that Caroll, Plaza Tower Inc. and Plaza Tower Operating had been defaulting on loan payments since October 1967.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trust Deed Holders Sue For Building|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-16-1968-420788/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 16, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In late August 1968, Las Vegas-based Supreme Mattress Company filed a lawsuit stating that it had only received $4,250 in payments for $25,505 worth of bedding material that was sold to the Landmark in December 1967.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark May Be 'Matressless'|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-25-1968-425532/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 25, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 1968, a joint petition was filed to declare the Landmark bankrupt. The petition was filed by Vegas Valley Electric, Inc., a plumbing contractor, and Landmark architects George Tate and Thomas Dobrusky. By that time, the Teamsters Union Pension Fund agreed to delay its foreclosure until the property was sold. Simultaneously, Sylvania Electric Company had intended to foreclose on the property because of an unpaid $3.7 million bill relating to electronic equipment installed in the Landmark. The joint petition prevented Sylvania from taking over ownership of the property.<ref name=Stalled>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Foreclosure Stalled: Bankruptcy Hearings For Landmark Ordered (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-30-1968-422139/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 30, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Foreclosure Stalled: Bankruptcy Hearings For Landmark Ordered (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-30-1968-422134/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 30, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Sale negotiations and Howard Hughes====\nIn July 1968, there were five firms interested in purchasing the Landmark, which was expected to sell for $16 million to $17 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=For Sale Sign Still Out: Man Who Holds Official Pen Denies Landmark Tower Sold|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-11-1968-420793/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 11, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> One of the firms, Olla Corporation, withdrew consideration of a purchase later that month, while an announcement of the resort's sale was expected within several days.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Purchase Still Expected By Owners|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1968-422097/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Several companies made purchase offers that were ultimately rejected, including Rosco Industries Inc., based in Los Angeles.<ref name=Firm/> On October 12, 1968, Caroll denied a report that the Landmark would be leased to Royal Inns of America, Inc. and operated without a casino. At the time, negotiations were underway with three corporations interested in purchasing the resort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Lease Report Brings Swift Denial|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-13-1968-422151/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 13, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Howard Hughes 1938.jpg|right|thumb|[[Howard Hughes]], pictured in 1938, purchased the Landmark in 1969]]\nOn October 23, 1968, billionaire [[Howard Hughes]] reached an agreement to purchase the Landmark through [[Hughes Tool Company]] for $17.3 million,<ref name=Hughes-Pay/><ref name=Tool/> after previously denying reports in March 1968 that he was interested in purchasing the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaming Policy Board to View Hughes-Stardust Plan|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707311/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=March 13, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929045012/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707311/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Laxalt Calls Meet To Discuss Hughes, Stardust Resort|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-13-1968-422029/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 13, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> As part of the sale agreement, Hughes' Hotel Properties, Inc. would accept responsibility for approximately $8.9 million owed to the Teamster Union, as well as approximately $5.9 million in other debts and a balance of $2.4 million to Plaza Tower, Inc.<ref name=Debut2/> At the time of the agreement, Hughes also owned five other hotel-casinos in Las Vegas.<ref name=Hughes-Pay>{{cite news|title=Hughes Will Pay $17.3 Million For 28-Story Las Vegas Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381043/arizona_daily_star/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|date=October 24, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927113412/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381043/arizona_daily_star/|archivedate=September 27, 2017}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Justice]] then launched an [[United States antitrust law|antitrust]] investigation into Hughes' proposed purchase, after previously investigating his attempt to purchase the [[Stardust Resort and Casino]], a transaction that he was blocked from completing for antitrust reasons.<ref name=Firm>{{cite news|title=El Monte Firm Plans to Bid for Las Vegas Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616948/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 31, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927113550/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616948/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=September 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Objection/> As part of the investigation, the Department of Justice attempted to determine if there were other prospective buyers for the Landmark.<ref name=Firm/>\n\nBy December 1968, while the Department of Justice continued its investigation, negotiations were underway with several firms that were interested in purchasing the Landmark, which included a $20 million offer from Tanger Industries, a [[holding company]] based in [[El Monte, California]].<ref name=Firm/><ref name=Pearl>{{cite news|last=Pearl|first=Ralph|title=Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616924/honolulu_starbulletin/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]|date=December 15, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616924/honolulu_starbulletin/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Business Tide|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/338894725/|accessdate=February 8, 2018|work=[[The Des Moines Register]]|date=January 2, 1969|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> It was reported that Hughes' attempted purchase would be rejected by the Department of Justice, despite his offer to convert the building into office space.<ref name=Pearl/>\n\n====Hughes purchase and opening preparations====\nOn January 17, 1969, the Department of Justice approved Hughes' plan to purchase the Landmark as his sixth Las Vegas resort.<ref name=Objection>{{cite news|title=No Government Objection To Hughes on Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381065/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 18, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011941/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381065/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Gets Approval|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jKEwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oEQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2627%2C1189644|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=[[The Virgin Islands Daily News]]|date=January 20, 1969}}</ref> Later that month, a $1.5 million lawsuit was filed against Hughes Tool Company by Pennsylvania resident James U. Meiler and New York brokerage firm John R. Roake and Son, Inc. Meiler and the brokerage firm stated that they were entitled to a $500,000 brokerage fee for previously arranging a sale of the Landmark to Republic Investors Holding Company, which was to pay between $15.3 million and $16 million for the resort until Hughes Tool Company agreed to purchase it. Meiler and the brokerage firm alleged that when Hughes Tool Company agreed to purchase the Landmark, it \"purposely and intentionally caused a restraining of interstate commerce\", referring to the $500,000 fee.<ref name=Tool>{{cite news|title=Hughes Tool Co. Sued By Broker Firm|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-24-1969-425426/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 24, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of January 1969, Hughes spokesmen stated that some construction on the resort was never finished; that some maintenance systems had not yet been installed; and that some repairs were needed. Hughes also planned to have some of the hotel rooms refurbished. Because of the additional work, the resort was not expected to open until at least July 1, 1969. Approximately 1,000 to 1,100 people were expected to be employed at the Landmark.<ref name=Revamping>{{cite news|title=Landmark Revamping Delays Opening Plans|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-30-1969-420817/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 30, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The Landmark was the only casino that Hughes had taken over before it was opened. As a result, Hughes was heavily involved in details regarding the project.<ref name=Vegas7>{{cite web|last=Rodgers|first=Lissa Townsend|title=A Brief History of Howard Hughes' Landmark Hotel|url=http://vegasseven.com/2016/11/03/brief-history-howard-hughes-landmark-hotel/|website=VegasSeven.com|accessdate=May 4, 2017|date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004064241/http://vegasseven.com/2016/11/03/brief-history-howard-hughes-landmark-hotel/|archivedate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> Hughes spent approximately $3 million to give the interior a lavish design and to [[#Features|add other touches to the resort]],<ref name=To-Open>{{cite news|title=Landmark to open July 1 in Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598932/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=June 25, 1969}}</ref><ref name=Key1>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=John L.|title=$20 Million Key Opens Hughes' 6th Vegas Hotel (page one)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599143/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 3, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599143/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> while the exterior of the Landmark buildings was left unchanged.<ref name=NewSkyline/>\n\nIn March 1969, Hughes applied for approval to operate the Landmark's gambling operations, with a tentative opening date of July 1, 1969. Hughes planned to operate the casino through his Nevada company, Hughes Properties Inc., which was overseen by Hughes executive Edward H. Nigro. Hughes planned for the resort to include 26 table games and 401 slot machines.<ref name=Debut1/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Applies To Operate The Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598764/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=March 5, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598764/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> Hughes' purchase of the Landmark was not complete at that time, and his representatives stated that the sale would not be completed unless gambling and liquor licenses were issued by the state.<ref name=Debut1>{{cite news|title=Hughes Gearing for July 1 Landmark Debut (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-05-1969-425434/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 5, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Debut2>{{cite news|title=Hughes Gearing for July 1 Landmark Debut (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-05-1969-425437/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 5, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In April 1969, Hughes received approval from the Gaming Control Board and from the state.<ref>{{cite news|title=Control Board Approves Bid For Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598857/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Nevada State Journal|date=April 15, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013644/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598857/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Given State Approval For 6th Casino|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598887/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=April 24, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013224/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598887/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHughes planned to personally oversee planning for the Landmark's grand opening; [[Robert Maheu]], who had worked for Hughes since the 1950s, said \"I knew from that point on that I was in trouble. He was completely incapable of making decisions.\"<ref name=Bio/> Across the street from the Landmark, [[Kirk Kerkorian]] was planning to open his [[Westgate Las Vegas Resort & Casino|International Hotel]] on July 2, 1969. Hughes and Maheu \u2013 who never met each other in person due to Hughes' [[reclusive]] lifestyle \u2013 had intense arguments about the Landmark's opening date that lasted for months. Maheu believed the Landmark should open on July 1, but Hughes did not want to commit to an exact date for various reasons. Hughes had wanted the Landmark's grand opening event to be better than Kerkorian's, but was concerned that the opening night would not go as planned. Hughes also did not want the opening date to be publicly announced too soon in the event that it should be delayed; Hughes wrote to Maheu: \"With my reputation for unreliability in the keeping of engagements, I dont [sic] want this event announced until the date is ''absolutely firmly'' established.\"<ref name=Citizen/>\n\nAdditionally, Hughes wrote to Maheu: \"I would hate to see the Landmark open on the 1st of July and then watch the International open a few days later and make the Landmark opening look like small potatoes by comparison.\" Maheu became concerned, as it was difficult to plan the grand opening without knowing the date.<ref name=Citizen>{{cite book|last=Drosnin|first=Michael|title=Citizen Hughes|date=2004|publisher=Broadway Books|isbn=0767919343|pages=318\u2013325|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jlx-bcbx8_oC&pg=PA318&lpg=PA318|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> As the tentative opening date approached, Hughes became concerned about other events scheduled for July 1969 \u2013 such as the [[Apollo 11]] moon landing \u2013 which might distract from the publicity of the Landmark's opening.<ref name=Citizen/> By mid-June 1969, Hughes had still not given a definite opening date, which was still tentatively scheduled for July 1, although Hughes had wanted the Landmark to open sometime after the International Hotel.<ref name=Citizen/> Weeks before the tentative opening, Hughes obsessively made repeated changes to the guest list for the resort's opening night. Regarding who should be invited, Hughes had complex specifications for Maheu to follow. Maheu ultimately had to decide the guest list himself.<ref name=Bio/><ref name=Citizen/>\n\nOn June 16, 1969,<ref name=Cleared/> Sun Realty filed a claim against Plaza Tower, Inc., thus delaying Hughes' purchase of the Landmark and threatening its planned opening. Sun Realty alleged that it was owed a $500,000 [[finder's fee]] for locating Hughes as a buyer. The case was dismissed on June 25, 1969.<ref name=REG>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel Might Not Open on Schedule|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617560/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=June 24, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617560/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Way Cleared For Hughes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617572/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=June 26, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617572/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Cleared>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Opening Cleared|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617601/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=United Press International|date=June 27, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617601/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> On June 30, 1969, Sun Realty appealed the decision but was denied that day as it was unable to post a bond that would pay the $5.8 million worth of claims filed by approximately 120 other creditors after Plaza Towers Inc. entered bankruptcy.<ref name=Climax2/><ref name=Cleared/> Hughes' $17.3 million acquisition of the Landmark,<ref name=Climax1/> through Hughes Tool Company, was completed on July 1, 1969,<ref name=ownership/> a day after Hughes issued checks to three different entities to complete the purchase: $2.5 million to Plaza Towers; $5.8 million to fully pay unsecured creditors; and $9 million to pay off the Teamsters Union.<ref name=Climax1>{{cite news|title=It's Hughes' Landmark Now! 11th Hour Climax In Tower Deal (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-01-1969-421836/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 1, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Climax2>{{cite news|title=It's Hughes' Landmark Now! 11th Hour Climax In Tower Deal (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-01-1969-421842/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 1, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and operation (1969\u20131990)===\nThe Landmark opened on the night of July 1, 1969,<ref name=Finishing/><ref name=Key1/><ref name=Skyhigh>{{cite news|last=Browning|first=Norma Lee|title=Sky-High Casino|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599226/chicago_tribune/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|date=July 3, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924050517/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599226/chicago_tribune/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> a day before the International Hotel.<ref name=Hoopla/><ref name=Vegas7/> The resort was first unveiled to 480 VIP guests prior to the public opening, which was scheduled for after 9:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=Climax1/> [[Apollo 10]] astronauts [[Thomas P. Stafford]] and [[Eugene Cernan]] attended the grand opening, and were the first people to enter the new resort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Astronauts at Landmark opening|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599090/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=July 1, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093129/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599090/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Hoopla>{{cite news|last=Borders|first=Myram|title=Two Casino-Hotels Open in Las Vegas With Usual Hoopla|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11618366/lansing_state_journal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=United Press International|date=July 6, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093300/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11618366/lansing_state_journal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> Other guests included [[Cary Grant]], [[Dean Martin]], [[Jimmy Webb]], [[Phil Harris]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Sammy Cahn]], [[Steve and Eydie]], and [[Wilt Chamberlain]].<ref>{{cite news|title=It's too hot for Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149621330/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=July 8, 1969|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924092957/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149621330/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> Nevada governor [[Paul Laxalt]], as well as senators [[Alan Bible]] and [[Howard Cannon]], were also at the opening.<ref name=Regal1/><ref name=Regal2/> Three members of the [[Los Angeles Rams]] were also in attendance: [[Jack Snow (American football)|Jack Snow]], [[Lamar Lundy]], and [[Roger Brown (defensive tackle)|Roger Brown]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Snyder|first=Jimmy|title=Sports|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-02-1969-425487/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 2, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nLocal, national and international media were also present for the grand opening, which was described by the ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'' as resembling a Hollywood premiere.<ref name=Regal1/><ref name=Regal2/> A [[closed-circuit television]] camera filmed the festivities in the Landmark on opening night, with the footage being shown live to guests at Hughes' other hotels, the [[Sands Hotel and Casino|Sands]] and the [[New Frontier Hotel and Casino|Frontier]].<ref name=Regal1>{{cite news|last=Chrystal|first=Chris|title=Landmark's Debut Regal: Governor, Senators Join Vegans to Hail Grand Opening (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-02-1969-425466/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 2, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Regal2>{{cite news|last=Chrystal|first=Chris|title=Landmark's Debut Regal: Governor, Senators Join Vegans to Hail Grand Opening (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-02-1969-425480/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 2, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Hughes \u2013 who lived in a secluded penthouse at his nearby [[Desert Inn]] hotel-casino<ref name=Bio/><ref name=Citizen/> \u2013 did not attend the grand opening.<ref name=Skyhigh/><ref name=Citizen/> For opening night, comedian [[Danny Thomas]] was the first to perform in the Landmark's theater-restaurant showroom.<ref name=Key2/><ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> Hughes had earlier suggested a [[Rat Pack]] reunion or a [[Bob Hope]]-[[Bing Crosby]] reunion as the opening act, both of which were considered unlikely to happen.<ref name=Bio>{{cite news|last=Evans|first=K.J.|title=Howard Hughes|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/howard-hughes/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=September 12, 1999}}</ref>\n\nTelevision advertisements for the resort stated: \"In France, it's the Eiffel Tower. In India, it's the Taj Mahal. In Las Vegas, it's the Landmark.\"<ref name=Time/> Dick Parker, executive vice president for the Landmark, had stated during the previous year that the International and the nearby Las Vegas Convention Center would not harm the Landmark's business.<ref name=Pearlman/> The Landmark reportedly lost $5 million in its first week of operations,<ref name=QOTD/> and despite its close proximity to the convention center, the resort failed to make a profit during the subsequent years of its operation.<ref name=Ohio/><ref name=Whiz/> In October 1969, Sun Realty filed a damages lawsuit against Hughes Tool Company and Plaza Tower, Inc, alleging that the two companies conspired to avoid paying the realty company its $500,000 finder's fee. Aside from the finder's fee, Sun Realty also sought an additional $5 million in [[punitive damages]].<ref name=Suit>{{cite news|title=$5.5 million asked in suit against Hughes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617627/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=October 4, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929091349/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617627/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In February 1971, the [[Supreme Court of Nevada|Nevada supreme court]] rejected the lawsuit, which had sought $3 million by that time.<ref name=Sun-Realty>{{cite news|title=Court rejects hotel suit against Hughes firm|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381118/arizona_republic/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[United Press International]]|date=February 27, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929092234/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381118/arizona_republic/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In December 1971, Hughes paid a little over $1 million to purchase {{convert|9.86|acre|abbr=on}} of adjacent land located west of the Landmark.<ref>{{cite web|title=Parcel Ownership History|url=http://sandgate.co.clark.nv.us/assrrealprop/ParcelHistory.aspx?instance=pcl2&parcel=16209703006|publisher=Clark County Assessor's Office|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Buys10/> Hughes had previously leased the property, which he had been using as a parking lot for the resort.<ref name=Buys10>{{cite news|title=Hughes Buys 10 acres on strip|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11460142/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 22, 1972|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1973, ownership of the Landmark was transferred to Hughes' [[Summa Corporation]],<ref name=ownership>{{cite web|title=Landmark property ownership|url=http://sandgate.co.clark.nv.us/assrrealprop/ParcelHistory.aspx?instance=pcl2&parcel=16209703007|publisher=Clark County Assessor's Office|accessdate=May 11, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000829/http://sandgate.co.clark.nv.us/assrrealprop/ParcelHistory.aspx?instance=pcl2&parcel=16209703007|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> formerly Hughes Tool Company.<ref name=Sale-Fails/> That year, the Landmark was valued at $25 million in a property appraisal.<ref name=Offered12m/> By 1974, [[William G. Bennett (gaming executive)|William Bennett]] and [[William Pennington (businessman)|William Pennington]] made an offer to buy the Landmark, but Hughes raised the price several times, from $15 million to $20 million; they bought the [[Circus Circus Las Vegas|Circus Circus]] resort instead.<ref name=WorldsLargest>{{cite news|last=Macy|first=Robert|title=Las Vegas hotel opens as world's largest|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422984/the_kokomo_tribune/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=The Kokomo Tribune|agency=Associated Press|date=June 1, 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929043950/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422984/the_kokomo_tribune/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In January 1976, the Landmark began offering foreign-language gaming video tapes to its German, Japanese, and Spanish hotel guests, who frequently limited themselves to playing slot machines rather than table games because of language barriers. Summa general manager E. H. Milligan said, \"As far as we know, we are the first hotel in Las Vegas to present this service in this manner.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaming Tapes Available For Foreign Visitors|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-22-1976-423176/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 22, 1976|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The hotel and casino briefly closed in March 1976, as part of a hotel worker strike consisting of nearly 25,000 employees, affecting 15 Las Vegas resorts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas Jarred By Strike|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11436595/the_daily_herald/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency=United Press International|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]|date=March 12, 1976|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Hotels Package Deal Backfires|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-21-1976-423207/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 21, 1976|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The strike lasted two weeks before ending in late March.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Two-Week Strip Strike Comes To End|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-mar-26-1976-p-4/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 26, 1976|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Hughes died of [[kidney failure]] the following month.<ref name=Bio/> James Wadsworth, general manager for the Landmark, resigned on January 9, 1977, so he could rejoin his private law firm. Perry Lieber, a Summa employee who once served as the Landmark's general manager, was chosen to replace Wadsworth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark manager resigns|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11426838/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency= Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 10, 1977|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nBy May 1977, Summa was financially struggling; that month, the brokerage firm of [[Merrill Lynch|Merrill, Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith]] recommended that Summa sell its various holdings, including the Landmark. According to the brokerage firm, the Landmark \"has proven highly inefficient for hotel/casino operations and, in the opinion of Summa Corporation's management, does not warrant further investment.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hackman|first=Rick|title=To Survive, Summa Must Sell (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-04-1977-423236/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hackman|first=Rick|title=To Survive, Summa Must Sell (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-04-1977-423241/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Gas leak and fire====\nOn July 15, 1977, shortly after 4:00&nbsp;a.m., a water pipe burst in the tower's [[subbasement]], two floors below ground level. Two feet of water flooded the basement room and shorted out the main power panel, thereby cutting out electricity for the resort shortly before 5:00&nbsp;a.m. An [[Auxiliary generator|auxiliary power generator]] provided lighting for the resort. However, telephones, air conditioning, and four of the tower's five elevators were left non-functional because of the main power failure.<ref name=Exhaust>{{cite news|last1=Cavanaugh|first1=Wade|last2=Manning|first2=Mary|title=Generator Exhaust Found As Hotel Disaster Cause|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423270/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> [[Carbon monoxide]], [[freon]] and [[methane]], all originating from the auxiliary generator, infiltrated the tower through ventilation ducts, forcing an evacuation of the building.<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1/><ref name=Freon2/> Between 9:00&nbsp;a.m. and 11:00&nbsp;a.m., crews from [[Southwest Gas Corporation]] inspected the building with firemen and found no further traces of gas, allowing guests and employees to re-enter the building.<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1/><ref name=Freon2/>\n\nA second evacuation was ordered at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. after another power failure, which rendered the elevators inoperable once again. During the outage, 21 table games remained open with the use of [[emergency light]]s, while a bar gave away free drinks. Power was restored at 6:45&nbsp;p.m.,<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1/><ref name=Freon2/> although telephones remained inoperable. Guests were given the option to stay at one of Summa's other hotel properties.<ref name=Exhaust/> Despite the incident, hotel executives stated that the resort maintained 95-percent occupancy.<ref name=Freon2/> An investigation into the cause of the gas leaks could not begin that day due to the presence of fumes in the basement.<ref name=Probe/>\n\nDuring the incident, a news reporter and a cameraman for the local [[KLAS-TV]] news channel \u2013 also owned by Summa \u2013 were beaten and forced out of the hotel lobby by Landmark guards who were armed with clubs and flashlights. Damaged in the altercation was the recording unit for a $37,000 camera owned by KLAS. Other local news crews were allowed to stay at the property to cover the incident. Orders to remove KLAS were given to the guards by hotel management, which had been irritated by recent KLAS news stories that related to Summa's properties, including a story stating that negotiations were underway to sell the Landmark to an Arabian investor.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Newsmen Beaten by Landmark Guards|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423270/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|agency=United Press International|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=News Crew Claims They Were Beaten At Landmark Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459787/the_daily_herald/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency=United Press International|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]|date=July 17, 1977|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nA total of 138 people were hospitalized after inhaling the poisonous gases;<ref name=Defect/><ref>{{cite news|last=Spigelmyer|first=Sharon|title=Heavy Carbon Monoxide In Hotel Guests (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423264/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977 |via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Spigelmyer|first=Sharon|title=Heavy Carbon Monoxide In Hotel Guests (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423267/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977 |via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Spigelmyer|first=Sharon|title=Heavy Carbon Monoxide In Hotel Guests (page three)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423268/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977 |via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> they were treated at four local hospitals.<ref name=Probe/> Among the hospitalized were nearly 100 hotel guests, and several firemen and ambulance drivers; most of the patients were released from the hospitals within three days of the incident.<ref name=Probe/> A 55-year-old man was the sole casualty in the incident.<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1>{{cite news|title=In Landmark Disaster: Freon, Methane Filtered Through Hotel (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-17-1977-423274/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 17, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Freon2>{{cite news|title=In Landmark Disaster: Freon, Methane Filtered Through Hotel (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-17-1977-423282/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 17, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> An investigation into the cause of the gas leaks concluded on July 19, 1977, and found that a defective exhaust line on one of the emergency generators was responsible. The line had been installed during the hotel's construction. John Pisciotta, director of the Clark County Building Department, did not believe that he or anyone else would be able to determine how the line became damaged. Summa brought in the company which installed the system to have it repaired.<ref name=Probe>{{cite news|title=Hotel Poisoning Probe Scheduled|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-19-1977-423287/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 19, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Defect>{{cite news|title=Exhaust Line Defect Cause of Hotel Gas|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-21-1977-423302/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 21, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 1977, at 3:44&nbsp;p.m., a [[two-alarm fire]] was reported in a hotel room on the 22nd floor, after a bartender in the 27th floor lounge smelled smoke. The entire room had caught on fire from a cigarette. The fire was extinguished with help from 45 firefighters, who put it out within five minutes of their arrival. However, the fire led to heavy smoke infiltrating the entire hotel and ground-floor through elevator shafts. The entire hotel was evacuated, and hundreds of guests and employees were allowed to return inside at approximately 5:15&nbsp;p.m., after smoke had been cleared from the resort's interior. The 22nd through 27th floors had moderate smoke damage. Five hotel guests were treated for [[smoke inhalation]], but none required hospitalization.<ref>{{cite news|last=Adler|first=Jeff|title=Tower Fire Clears Out Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-24-1977-423410/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 24, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cavanaugh|first=Wade|title=Guests Doubt LV Welcome After Blaze In Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-24-1977-423415/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 24, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel Fire Caused By Cigarette|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-25-1977-423420/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 25, 1977}}</ref>\n\n====Prospective buyers====\nIn late September 1977, Summa began negotiations with a group of Chicago investors that was interested in purchasing the Landmark,<ref name=Offered12m/><ref name=Offered12m2/> which had approximately 1,200 employees at the time.<ref name=Ohio/> The group \u2013 consisting of physicians, lawyers, and a Las Vegas art dealer \u2013 operated several fast-food restaurants and medical buildings in the [[midwestern United States]],<ref name=Offered12m/><ref name=Offered12m2/> and was led by attorney Myron Minuskin.<ref name=Attorney/>\n\nIn October 1977, Summa was in negotiations to sell the Landmark for $12 million to Nick Lardakis, a tavern owner who lived in [[Akron, Ohio]]. Simultaneously, Summa was also holding discussions with the Scott Corporation \u2013 a group of [[downtown Las Vegas]] entrepreneurs led by Frank Scott \u2013 which wanted to purchase the resort at a price of nearly $10 million.<ref name=Ohio>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Ohio Man Negotiating To Buy Landmark Hotel|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-12-1977-420853/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 12, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=GamingFigures>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=LV Gaming Figures Seen As Landmark Buyers|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-15-1977-423342/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 15, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Lardakis' acquisition of the Landmark was rejected that month as he was unable to raise the necessary funds to make the purchase;<ref name=Offered12m/> according to Summa, Lardakis' terms were \"unrealistic.\"<ref name=NoDecision/>\n\nOn October 17, 1977, the Chicago group offered $11 million in cash for the Landmark, but the group was rejected by Summa, which sought $12 million for the resort. The group made a $12 million cash offer the following morning. However, Summa's board of directors favored the $10 million offer by Scott Corporation, which had no down payment and included a 20-year payout period, while the Chicago group was opposed to a long-term mortgage arrangement with Summa. The Chicago group noted that Summa officials repeatedly declined to let the group examine the Landmark's 1973 property appraisal.<ref name=Offered12m>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=$12 Million Offered For Landmark (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-19-1977-420849/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 19, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Offered12m2>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=$12 Million Offered For Landmark (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-19-1977-423366/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 19, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Other offers came from Las Vegas heiress JoAnn Seigal and Beverly Hills management consultant Charles Fink, both of whom offered $12 million for the resort. Seigal also complained that Summa would not provide her with a property appraisal to base her negotiations.<ref name=NoDecision2/>\n\nOn October 19, 1977, the Beverly Hills-based Acro Management Consultants made a $16 million cash offer for the Landmark, the highest of five bids that had thus far been offered for the resort. Summa spokesman Fred Lewis said that Acro's bid was considered to be \"more of an inquiry\" than a serious offer,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Summa Gets $16 Mil. Cash Offer For Hotel|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-21-1977-423396/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 21, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> a belief that was later disputed by Acro vice president Leonard Gale, who also said, \"We realize the Landmark is the biggest lemon in Las Vegas. But we have a program that would be sensational and we know we could turn the place around.\"<ref name=Retains2/> On the day that Acro's offer was made, Summa announced that no decision had been made on a sale of the Landmark, reportedly due to disagreements within the company. William Lummis, a cousin of Hughes, had been named chairman of the Summa board earlier in the year. Lummis wanted to sell all of Summa's non-profitable properties, while [[chief operating officer]] [[Frank William Gay]], citing the purported desires of Hughes, wanted to expand and modernize such properties.<ref name=NoDecision>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Landmark Sale: No Decision Yet (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-20-1977-423386/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 20, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=NoDecision2>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Landmark Sale: No Decision Yet (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-20-1977-423379/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 20, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The Landmark was considered to be the weakest of Summa's six gaming and hotel properties in Nevada, as it had never made a profit up to that time.<ref name=Sale-Fails>{{cite news |title=Landmark sale fails |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681051/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=October 20, 1977 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Chicago group subsequently offered to pay all Landmark bills and debts during the final 60 days of a 90-day escrow period.<ref name=Attorney>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Attorney Bids for Resort|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-03-1977-423431/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 3, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nSumma officials held a meeting on November 3, 1977, but the company made no decision on selling the Landmark, which lost an average of $500,000 per month. By that time, the Scott Corporation stated that it would likely withdraw its offer to purchase the Landmark because of inability to obtain long-term financing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Summa Retains Ownership of Landmark (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-04-1977-423440/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Retains2>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Summa Retains Ownership of Landmark (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-04-1977-423446/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hotel Deal Pends|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-06-1977-423450/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 6, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In December 1977, it was stated that if the Landmark remained a Summa property, then the company would add six outdoor tennis courts to the resort, as well as 10 indoor courts that would be usable by all Summa hotel guests in the Las Vegas area.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunne|first=Irene|title=Tennis Talk|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-28-1977-423454/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 28, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1978, Summa announced that the Landmark would be sold to the Scott Corporation, with the sale price reportedly ranging between $10 million and $12 million. Up to that time, the resort had reportedly lost $15 million since its opening, despite numerous attempts to increase business. Experts believed that the Landmark suffered financially as a result of its low room-count (486 guest rooms at the time) and its location across the street from the Las Vegas Hilton (formerly the International), which was the world's largest hotel at the time. Frank Scott owned downtown Las Vegas' [[Union Plaza Hotel]], which had become one of the city's most successful casinos, and he said the same management principles used at the Union Plaza would be applied to the Landmark.<ref name=SellsFamed/>\n\n{{Quote\n|text=Gambling is a business\u2014a very unique business\u2014and sound policies applied and followed will result in a successful operation. We face a strong challenge in making the Landmark one of the truly fine casino-hotel operations in Las Vegas, and we look forward to accomplishing this goal.\n|author=Frank Scott, 1978<ref name=SellsFamed/>|\n}}\n\nScott intended to change the name of the resort, with \"The Plaza Tower\" as the favorite among several names under consideration at that time. Scott planned to take over operations once the sale received approval from Summa, county and state gaming officials, and courts that were handling Hughes' estate.<ref name=SellsFamed>{{cite news|title=Summa Corp. sells famed Landmark Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11436720/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency= Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 13, 1978|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Because higher offers were subsequently made for the Landmark, the Scott Corporation's offer was rejected by a judge who was monitoring the Hughes estate.<ref name=Gambling/><ref name=Direct/>\n\n====Wolfram/Tickel ownership====\nA group of midwestern investors \u2013 led by Lou Tickel and Zula Wolfram,<ref name=Possible/><ref>{{cite news |title=Summa says it made no promises in Landmark sale |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681248/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=November 11, 1986 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> and including Gary Yelverton<ref name=Set-Reopen/> \u2013 purchased the Landmark from Summa Corporation in February 1978,<ref name=Possible/> at a cost of $12.5 million.<ref name=BetterEver/> The purchase was financed using money that Wolfram's husband, Ed Wolfram, [[Embezzlement|embezzled]] from his brokerage firm, [[Bell & Beckwith]].<ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite news |title=Indictment charges money siphoned from brokerage used to buy casino |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681166/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=April 6, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Faye Todd, the Landmark's Entertainment Director and a Corporate Executive Assistant, primarily oversaw the Landmark's operations for the Wolframs, who lived in Ohio. The Wolframs were [[high roller]]s who frequently stayed at the Desert Inn resort when visiting Las Vegas. Todd met the Wolframs while working for the Desert Inn as Special Events Coordinator, and she became close friends with Zula Wolfram, who had been planning to purchase a Las Vegas hotel with her husband.<ref name=Todd>{{cite web|last=White|first=Claytee D.|title=An Interview with Faye Todd|url=http://digital.library.unlv.edu/api/1/objects/ohr/2/bitstream|publisher=University of Nevada, Las Vegas|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=1998|pages=28\u201343|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000918/http://digital.library.unlv.edu/api/1/objects/ohr/2/bitstream|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Lou Tickel, a former [[magistrate]] judge and a resident of [[Salina, Kansas]], previously owned several other hotels. The group was confident that the Landmark would overcome its financial problems, and they planned to add a 750-room hotel tower to the property within two years.<ref name=Gambling>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Salinan gambling that Vegas hotel-casino can turn a profit |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3407581/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=February 28, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Direct>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Tickel to take direct hand in hotel operation |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3408179/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=March 1, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nThe sale was completed on March 31, 1978,<ref name=ownership/><ref name=Possible/> under the new ownership of Zula Wofram, and Lou and Jo Ann Tickel.<ref name=ownership/> However, the new owners had been unable to find someone with a gaming license and sufficient funds to continue operating the casino ahead of the sale's completion. The investment group had not yet applied with the county and state for gaming and liquor licenses, and Summa Corporation declined to continue operating the casino, citing a lack of interest in the property.<ref name=Possible>{{cite news |title=Landmark closure possible |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681075/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=March 29, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Landmark's casino, which had 272 employees,<ref name=Possible/> was closed on April 1, 1978, due to the lack of gaming licenses.<ref name=Salinan/><ref name=Set-Reopen/> The owners began a search for a suitable licensed individual who could temporarily operate the casino until they could receive their own gaming license.<ref name=BetterEver>{{cite web |last= |first= |title='Business is better than ever', says Tickel of his new hotel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3431350/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=April 4, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The hotel, restaurants, and shops remained open,<ref name=Salinan>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Salinan takes over Landmark Resort |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3429446/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=April 2, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> with 700 other employees.<ref name=BetterEver/> The casino reopened on June 2, 1978, after a one-year gaming license had been granted to Frank Modica, a Las Vegas gaming figure who would temporarily operate the casino on the owners' behalf. The casino's bingo parlor remained closed as it was undergoing renovations.<ref name=Set-Reopen>{{cite news |title=Landmark casino set to reopen |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681084/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=June 1, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1978, Tickel, Wolfram, and Yelverton were approved by the Nevada Gaming Control Board and the Nevada Gaming Commission to be licensed as the landlords of the Landmark. At the time, Ed Wolfram was listed as a financial adviser on the licensing plan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Landmark investment plans get gaming board backing |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681100/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=October 14, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Landmark investors get license approval |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681115/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=October 20, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> As of April 1979, Jesse Jackson Jr. was the Landmark hotel manager, and was the only such manager in the Las Vegas hotel industry to be black.<ref>{{cite web |title=Speaking of People: Casino Hotel Manager |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=99QDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]] |date=April 1979 |accessdate=April 19, 2019|publisher = Johnson Publishing Company}}</ref> Gary Baldwin, a former investigator for the Nevada Gaming Control Board, was the Landmark's general manager and casino manager as of July 1979. That month, the gaming control board recommended that Baldwin be approved in his request to receive five-percent of pretax operating profits from the Landmark.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former gaming employee gets recommendation|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422675/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency= Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=July 12, 1979|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Tickels remained as co-owners of the Landmark until 1980,<ref name=ownership/> following Wolfram's approval to purchase their interest in the resort.<ref>{{cite web |title='Toy Let' canned |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/147718602/ |website=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=December 13, 1979 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1982, architect [[Martin Stern Jr.]] was hired to design a large expansion of the Landmark.<ref name=VTAT>{{cite web|title=Dream Projects from the Past, that were Never Built|url=http://www.vegastodayandtomorrow.com/dreams2.htm#.Wc1BnXmWwpM|website=VegasTodayAndTomorrow.com|accessdate=September 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211085021/http://www.vegastodayandtomorrow.com/dreams2.htm#.Wc1BnXmWwpM|archivedate=February 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Stern>{{cite web|title=Guide to the Martin Stern Architectural Records|url=https://www.library.unlv.edu/speccol/ead/MS-00382_stern.pdf|publisher=University of Nevada, Las Vegas|accessdate=September 28, 2017|pages=123\u2013125|date=July 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929001038/https://www.library.unlv.edu/speccol/ead/MS-00382_stern.pdf|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Revenue for the Landmark exceeded $26 million that year,<ref name=Takeover>{{cite news|title=Control board delays proposed takeover of Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681194/reno_gazettejournal/ |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=August 18, 1983|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> although the resort lost $500,000 during the month of November 1982. Up to that time, the Landmark had lost an average of $3 million every year since its opening.<ref name=Whiz>{{cite news|last=Macy|first=Robert|title=Gaming Whiz Turns Failure Into Success|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11431233/the_palm_beach_post/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=The Palm Beach Post|agency=Associated Press|date=December 24, 1983}}</ref>\n\nFederal investigators shut down Wolfram's firm on February 7, 1983, after they discovered $36 million of money missing in six accounts that were managed by him and his wife, ultimately leading to the discovery of his embezzlement.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=N. R.|first=Kleinfield|title=Beckwith Partner Gets 25-Year Jail Term|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/07/business/beckwith-partner-gets-25-year-jail-term.html|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=September 7, 1983|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044301/http://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/07/business/beckwith-partner-gets-25-year-jail-term.html|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Lawyer Patrick McGraw, [[trustee]] for Bell & Beckwith, was approved later that month to operate the Landmark until it could be liquidated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Special trustee approved for Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681154/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=February 18, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Walter J. Krasniewski Wednesday granted the trustee of the Bell & Beckwith brokerage authority to operate businesses assigned to him|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/02/23/US-Bankruptcy-Court-Judge-Walter-J-Krasniewski-Wednesday-granted/8976414824400/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|agency=United Press International|date=February 23, 1983|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000732/http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/02/23/US-Bankruptcy-Court-Judge-Walter-J-Krasniewski-Wednesday-granted/8976414824400/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> The expansion designed by Stern was cancelled,<ref name=VTAT/> and Ed Wolfram was convicted of embezzling later that year, after admitting to using money from his firm to pay for various businesses ventures, with the Landmark being the most expensive.<ref name=NYT/> Zula Wolfram, who had owed $5 million to Summa since her purchase of the Landmark, was forced to sell her majority share in the resort.<ref name=Takeover/>\n\n====Morris ownership====\nThe Landmark was entangled in a Toledo bankruptcy court in July 1983, at which point Bill Morris, a Las Vegas lawyer, began plans to purchase the resort.<ref name=Whiz/><ref>{{cite news |title=Deal in the works to purchase hotel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681276/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=July 21, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris, also a member of the [[Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority]] (LVCVA), had previously owned the [[Harrah's Las Vegas|Holiday Inn Center Strip hotel-casino]], as well as the [[Riverside Resort Hotel & Casino|Riverside Resort]] in nearby [[Laughlin, Nevada|Laughlin]].<ref name=Whiz/> Morris had also previously represented Plaza Tower, Inc. at the time that Hughes completed his purchase of the resort.<ref name=Climax1/> Morris intended to eventually expand the resort to 1,100 hotel rooms.<ref>{{cite news |title=Attorney gets state OK to buy Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681211/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=United Press International |date=August 26, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nYelverton and his wife stated that they had been sold a five-percent interest in the Landmark in 1979, but that the document mistakenly was never filed with the county recorder's office. In August 1983, the Yelvertons filed a state suit to prevent the sale to Morris, stating that they would not be compensated for their interest if the sale proceeded. At the time, Gary Yelverton was the Landmark's casino manager.<ref>{{cite news |title=Part owner sues to prevent sale |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-VgdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CFgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5386%2C3038287 |work=[[The Bryan Times]] |date=August 3, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> Later in the month, the Nevada Gaming Control Board delayed approval of Morris' purchase of the resort until his offer could be updated to include a $5 million payment for Summa \u2013 as part of his $18.4 million offer for the resort \u2013 to cover what Zula Wolfram owed to the company.<ref name=Takeover/> Morris purchased the Landmark for $18.7 million,<ref name=Borders/> and took over ownership on October 30, 1983.<ref name=Facelift/> The struggling resort had a profitable month in November 1983 under its new management.<ref name=Whiz/><ref>{{cite web|title=Patrick A. McGraw, Trustee, Plaintiff, v. Gary Yelverton, et al., Defendants|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/BR/87/476/2020266/|website=Law.Justia.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=May 26, 1988|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717033225/http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/BR/87/476/2020266/|archivedate=July 17, 2017}}</ref> Morris worked 18 hours a day to ensure the Landmark's success.<ref name=Whiz/>\n\n{{Quote\n|text=The Landmark's never really been given a fair chance. First, there has never been on-hands management on a day-in, day-out basis. Second, the operators have all tried to make the property do something it was not meant to do. They tried to compete with superstar productions, and a lot of money was lost in that competition. The property is ideally situated to serve the convention authority, and our operational thrust will be in that direction.\n|author=Bill Morris, 1983<ref name=Whiz/>|\n}}\n\nMorris spent nearly $3.5 million on [[#Features|a renovation of the Landmark]],<ref name=Morris-bio>{{cite news|title=William and Vivienne Morris|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11431032/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=October 18, 1984|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> which was underway in early December 1983. The resort remained open during renovations. At the time, the casino offered its Single-Deck Blackjack Tournament, with a $57 entry fee. Casino manager Ron Nadeau said \"we think this is the type of play that will catch on here. It is priced in a range that anyone can afford to join the action.\"<ref name=Facelift>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel is receiving a facelift|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11431095/arizona_republic/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=December 4, 1983|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris said that the Landmark would compete against rivals with its \"budget prices and good service.\"<ref name=Facelift/> By the end of 1983, Morris intended to capitalize on the resort's location with a planned expansion that would feature three 15-story towers with 1,500 hotel rooms, accompanied by a large domed family entertainment center. The expansion was to be built west of the Landmark on {{convert|11|acre|abbr=on}} of vacant land that Morris had purchased along with the resort.<ref name=Whiz/> The expansion did not occur, and the Landmark struggled throughout the 1980s.<ref name=Vegas7/>\n\nIn May 1985, the casino offered the \"More Than $100,000 Craps Tournament\".<ref>{{cite news|title=More Than $100,000 Craps Tournament|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422646/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=April 21, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> By June 1985,<ref>{{cite news|title=Soccer team in jeopardy|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459878/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=June 29, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris was negotiating a $28 million loan to pay for improvements and fire safety updates for the resort, which had failed to comply with fire safety standards; Clark County officials considered taking action against the resort because of its failed compliance. On July 29, 1985, the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS) filed a $2.1 [[lien]] against the property, because of Morris' failure to pay [[Withholding tax|withholding]] and [[payroll tax]]es for the resort's employees for the previous six months. Two days after the lien was filed, the Landmark filed for [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy to prevent the IRS from seizing assets such as casino cage money. The resort remained open despite the bankruptcy filing, and the casino had enough money to remain operational. The Landmark had debts totaling $30.6 million, while it had $30.6 million in assets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel seeks Chapter 11 protection|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459901/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=August 1, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris blamed the bankruptcy on McGraw, alleging that he derailed a $28.8 million refinancing of the Landmark 24 hours prior to the finalization of the loan. Morris said operations would continue as normal despite the bankruptcy filing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bankruptcy forced, says casino owner |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681229/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |date=August 2, 1985 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1986, Nevada National Bank requested that the bankruptcy be converted to a liquidation proceeding to pay off creditors, stating that the Landmark's bankruptcy reorganization plan could not succeed.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Landmark hearing put off |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/148137552/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=January 23, 1986 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> During the same month, Morris said he would have to cancel his reorganization plan and lay off 700 to 800 Landmark employees if a bankruptcy court did not allow the resort to abandon its union labor contracts. Part of Morris' reorganization plan involved cutting employee wages by 15 percent, including his own yearly salary of $145,000. The pay cut would give the Landmark an additional $6,500 per month, which would allow the resort to make its mortgage payments. Morris hoped to increase the hotel's room count after the resort's eventual emergence from bankruptcy, with additional financing from a national franchise hotel chain. He hoped that the Landmark would be out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy by March 1, 1986,<ref name=Borders>{{cite news|last=Borders|first=Myram|title=Landmark Hotel's Morris seeking to abandon union labor contracts|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459748/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=January 24, 1986|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> although it would ultimately remain in bankruptcy for the rest of its operation.<ref name=Orders/>\n\nIn January 1987, a small fire broke out in the resort's showroom, located next to the casino. Five employees were evacuated, and there were no injuries. Customers in the casino were unaware of the fire, which was quickly extinguished by the local fire department. The fire was determined to have likely been caused by an [[arsonist]].<ref name=Arson>{{cite news|title=Vegas Hotel Fire was arson|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423832/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=January 14, 1987|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fires may have been set by arsonist|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423789/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=January 15, 1987|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In July 1987, the Landmark began offering poker tournaments in its Nightcap Lounge each weekday night. To help bring in customers, two cash drawings were held during each tournament.<ref>{{cite news|title= Poker tourneys on weekdays at Landmark Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422615/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 26, 1987|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nBy April 1989, Morris and [[Drexel Burnham Lambert]] had begun a search for a new owner to take over the Landmark.<ref>{{cite web |last=Krane |first=Elliot S. |title=Landmark Hires Drexel to Find Buyer |url=https://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/site_services/news_archives/ |website=The Press of Atlantic City |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=April 9, 1989 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In November 1989, a U.S. bankruptcy court judge gave Morris until January 2, 1990 to find a buyer or refinancing. Otherwise, the Landmark would be liquidated to pay off creditors, in accordance with a court order.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Court moves closer to forcing Vegas hotel-casino sale |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=UPI NewsTrack |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=November 20, 1989 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref> On January 2, 1990, the Landmark was ordered into [[Chapter 7 bankruptcy]] after a judge ruled that the creditors would not be able to receive compensation under the reorganization plan.<ref name=Orders>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Judge orders Chapter 7 for Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/147591278/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=January 3, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Between $43 million and $46 million was owed to various creditors. Morris' gaming license expired that month after the resort failed to pay $500,000 in taxes and penalties. Richard Davis, a Las Vegas real estate executive and owner of a funeral home, was appointed by the bankruptcy court that month to temporarily operate the resort. On February 21, 1990, the Nevada Gaming Commission extended the gaming license and allowed the resort to stay open for at least two additional weeks while its financial problems were analyzed by state experts. At that time, the hotel had $562,000 in cash, including $175,000 in revenue that had accumulated in the prior six weeks.<ref name=Bankrupt>{{cite web|last=Borders|first=Myram|title=Bankrupt Landmark hotel-casino gets state reprieve|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/02/22/Bankrupt-Landmark-hotel-casino-gets-state-reprieve-By-MYRAM-BORDERS/2479635662800/|publisher=UPI|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=February 22, 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929045142/http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/02/22/Bankrupt-Landmark-hotel-casino-gets-state-reprieve-By-MYRAM-BORDERS/2479635662800/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy June 1990, the Landmark was still struggling,<ref name=WorldsLargest/> although the introduction of various casino programs helped improve revenue. Later that month, a U.S. bankruptcy court judge approved a request for the Landmark to be sold in a public auction scheduled for August 6, 1990. The request was made by Davis, who cited numerous failed attempts to sell the resort. More than 200 prospective buyers had inquired about the Landmark, but only five to ten of them were considered as having serious interest in the resort.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Bankruptcy judge orders Landmark sale |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149708447/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=June 20, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In July 1990, two Denver businessmen, David M. Droubay and Martin Heckmaster, offered $35.5 million to purchase the bankrupt resort.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=2 Denver businessmen bid for Las Vegas hotel |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=The Denver Post |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=July 6, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=$35.5 million offer accepted for Landmark sale |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149691709/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=July 3, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=$35.5 million offer accepted for Landmark sale (page 2 of 2)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149691523/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=July 3, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris was dissatisfied with the offer, stating that the property had been appraised as high as $70 million.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Landmark Hotel owner calls offer 'low ball' |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149700964/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=July 4, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Ultimately, Droubay and Heckmaster's plan to purchase the Landmark did not come together.<ref name=Spectrum/>\n\n===Closure (1990\u201395)===\nOn August 6, 1990, the bankruptcy hearing failed to attract a buyer for the Landmark. [[Ralph Engelstad]] and [[Charles Frias]], who both held substantial interest in the resort, had made $100,000 deposits which allowed them to bid at the hearing, but they did not do so and left the hearing without commenting. At the request of Davis' attorney, a U.S. bankruptcy judge granted permission to close the Landmark. Gaming operations began shutting down that afternoon, within an hour of the failed hearing. Slot machine and hotel operations were scheduled to shut down later in the week.<ref name=Spectrum>{{cite web |title=Landmark Hotel begins shutting down tables |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423265/the_daily_spectrum/ |website=The Daily Spectrum |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=August 7, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> With 498 rooms at the time,<ref name=Bankrupt/> the Landmark was unable to compete with new megaresorts, and was fully closed on August 8, 1990.<ref name=lvs1/>\n\nMorris, upset about the failed auction, said, \"Sometimes it comes down to good luck and bad luck. I had nothing but bad luck. Someone is going to come in and run the Landmark and look like a genius.\" Forrest Woodward, who managed the casino for Davis, said, \"This is just an obsolete gaming property that no one's interested in, considering the debt,\" which included $48 million; a portion of that was $10 million in unsecured claims. Davis' attorney predicted the Landmark would be closed for 100 days or more while creditors pursued a foreclosure sale.<ref name=Spectrum/> A week after the closure, Davis received permission from the U.S. bankruptcy court to abandon the property as trustee, due to the cost of maintaining security at the closed resort. Davis' attorney said it would cost between $60,000 and $200,000 each month to maintain the property. Creditors would be left to pay bills relating to the property until a foreclosure sale could take place.<ref>{{cite web |title=Landmark Hotel in court |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423198/reno_gazettejournal/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Creditors to Pick Up Tab |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=The Fresno Bee |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=August 19, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref> In December 1990, the property was purchased through a foreclosure sale by [[Lloyds Bank]] of London for $20 million. Lloyds Bank made the purchase in order to protect a $25 million loan it had made to Morris in 1988.<ref name=BankBuys>{{cite web |title=Bank buys Landmark Hotel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423161/reno_gazettejournal/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=December 6, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=London bank buys shuttered Las Vegas hotel-casino|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/12/07/London-bank-buys-shuttered-Las-Vegas-hotel-casino/2976660546000/|publisher=UPI|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=December 7, 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929045100/http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/12/07/London-bank-buys-shuttered-Las-Vegas-hotel-casino/2976660546000/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> By March 1993, the Landmark's contents had been liquidated through a sale conducted by National Content Liquidators.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Thousands show for Dunes closeout |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/152710747/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=March 19, 1993 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McNair |first=James |title=Company strips hotels 'down to walls' for profits |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/Dec/01/bz/bz30a.html |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |work=The Cincinnati Enquirer |date=December 1, 2002}}</ref>\n\nBy July 1993, representatives of Lloyds Bank had approached the LVCVA about the possibility of purchasing the Landmark. LVCVA was interested in the proposal, with plans to use the Landmark's 21-acre property either for a parking lot or expansion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas Convention Authority wants to buy closed Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874976/reno_gazettejournal/|date=July 3, 1993|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> LVCVA purchased the Landmark in September 1993,<ref name=ownership/> at a cost of $15.1 million.<ref name=Oakland>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Oakland Firm Gets Landmark-Demolition Job |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=San Jose Mercury News |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=October 11, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref><ref name=Elko/> During 1994, board members of LVCVA debated on whether to restore the Landmark or demolish it.<ref name=\"lvs1\"/> It was ultimately decided that the Landmark would be demolished, after only three LVCVA board members voted to save the building. Among those voting in support was [[Lorraine Hunt]], who later said that the Landmark \"was iconic and part of the history of Las Vegas. Had they kept it, it could have been the office for the Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Norm|title=Hunt Bono recalls Landmark opening, implosion|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/opinion/columns-blogs/norm-clarke/hunt-bono-recalls-landmark-opening-implosion|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=7 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105223419/http://www.reviewjournal.com/opinion/columns-blogs/norm-clarke/hunt-bono-recalls-landmark-opening-implosion|archivedate=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Demolition====\nLVCVA paid $800,000 for [[asbestos]] removal in the tower. Central Environmental Inc. was hired to remove the asbestos, while AB-Haz Environmental, Inc. was the asbestos removal consultant.<ref name=PutOff/> In mid-1994, AB-Haz Environmental began removing asbestos insulation from the Landmark.<ref name=April97/><ref name=May99/> The removal, scheduled for completion in August 1994, took nearly six months.<ref name=PutOff/> In October 1994, it was announced that the Landmark would be demolished the following month to make way for a 21-acre parking lot,<ref>{{cite news|title=Failed Landmark to be razed in Nov.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875039/reno_gazettejournal/|date=October 4, 1994|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> to be used by the Las Vegas Convention Center.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> Demolition of the tower was delayed until December 1994, before being delayed again to January 1995, to allow for the removal of additional asbestos. By that time, the Clark County Health District had proposed penalties against the asbestos companies.<ref name=PutOff>{{cite news|title=Demolition put off for closed Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875053/reno_gazettejournal/|date=November 29, 1994|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nBy February 1995, AB-Haz had twice declared the Landmark to be asbestos-free and safe for demolition, although Clark County officials discovered that some hotel floors still contained 90 percent of the asbestos. Up to that time, LVCVA had already paid a total of $1 million to the asbestos companies to have the asbestos removed from the hotel and an adjacent apartment complex, allowing for their demolition. The Clark County Air Pollution Control Division recommended a $450,000 fine against AB-Haz for failure to remove the asbestos, while LVCVA would have to spend an additional $1 million for further asbestos removal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Asbestos removal to cost $1 million|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875009/reno_gazettejournal/|date=February 28, 1995|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> AB-Haz was ultimately cited for violating air emission standards during the asbestos removal, and signed a settlement in which the company agreed to pay an $18,000 fine.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Indictments handed down as asbestos not removed |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/153426979/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=October 17, 1996 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=April97>{{cite news|title=Company challenges Landmark indictment|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/apr/03/company-challenges-landmark-indictment/|accessdate=May 11, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 3, 1997|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808000725/https://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/apr/03/company-challenges-landmark-indictment/|archivedate=August 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=May99>{{cite news|title=Asbestos-removal firms facing record fines|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/may/28/asbestos-removal-firms-facing-record-fines/|accessdate=May 11, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 28, 1999|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808000100/https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/may/28/asbestos-removal-firms-facing-record-fines/|archivedate=August 8, 2017}}</ref> Central Environmental was removing asbestos from the tower as of August 1995. Because of previous delays, officials for LVCVA had given up on setting a demolition date until all the asbestos was removed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Asbestos-removal delays demolition|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875071/reno_gazettejournal/|date=August 15, 1995|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In October 1995, LVCVA paid Iconco Inc. $740,000 to remove remaining asbestos from the resort, hoping to have it demolished in time for [[Conexpo-Con/Agg|ConExpo]] to be held on the property's new parking lot in March 1996.<ref name=Oakland/>\n\n[[Controlled Demolition, Inc.]] (CDI) was hired to [[Building implosion|implode]] the tower.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\" /><ref name=Elko>{{cite web |title=Landmark Hotel tower in Las Vegas will be imploded |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/477291637/ |website=Elko Daily Free Press |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=November 4, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> No [[blueprint]]s could be found for the tower, which CDI president Mark Loizeaux considered unusual. Demolition crews discovered secret stairwells in the tower, and Loizeaux said, \"We have learned everything as we have gone in. It was a very strange structure, very unique.\"<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/><ref name=Implode>{{cite news|title=Preparations made to implode Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874692/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=November 7, 1995|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A week before the Landmark tower was demolished, crews removed the remaining asbestos from the low-rise structures and subsequently tore them down. Crews then spent the final days of demolition by drilling in the tower to weaken and prepare it ahead of its planned implosion. Less than 100 pounds of dynamite was placed in certain locations throughout the tower's first four floors.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/>\n\n[[File:Landmark sign, Las Vegas (8370148248).jpg|thumb|right|A restored Landmark sign, located on the property of the former resort (2013)]]\nAt 5:37&nbsp;a.m. on November 7, 1995, the Landmark tower was demolished through implosion.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\" /><ref name=CT>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Las Vegas Landmark imploded |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/167723530/ |website=Chicago Tribune |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=November 7, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Reduced to rubble |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/153900120/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=November 8, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Mag>{{cite web |url=http://vegasmagazine.com/living/articles/in-depth-bringing-down-the-harmon |title=In Depth: Bringing Down the Harmon |publisher=Vegas Magazine |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223073857/http://vegasmagazine.com/living/articles/in-depth-bringing-down-the-harmon |archivedate=2014-12-23 }}</ref> An estimated 7,000 people arrived to witness the implosion.<ref name=CT/> Upon detonation, the tower's northwest half was brought down, followed by the second half, which caved in on itself, followed by a black cloud of dust ascending 150 feet into the air. Most of the material from the demolished structure was to be recycled and used in other construction projects.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> The 31-story tower was the tallest reinforced concrete building ever demolished in North America, and the second tallest building in the world to be demolished.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/><ref name=Good/> Demolition and related expenses cost $3 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=LVCVA to appeal $9 million land decision |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/24/lvcva-to-appeal-9-million-land-decision/ |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=April 24, 1996}}</ref> [[Frank Wright (historian)|Frank Wright]], curator of the [[Nevada State Museum, Las Vegas|Nevada State Museum and Historical Society]], said \"I kind of hate to see it come down,\" stating that the Landmark tower still represented what the then-upcoming [[Stratosphere Las Vegas|Stratosphere tower]] represented: \"the biggest and the tallest.\"<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> The property was to become occupied by 2,200 parking spaces, expected to be ready by March 1996.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/>\n\nOne of the Landmark's ground-level signs, with gold and blue cursive neon lettering, was restored by the [[Neon Museum]] and installed at the parking lot.<ref name=Vegas7/> As of 2017, the property contains 2,948 parking spaces for the Las Vegas Convention Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=LVCC Gold Lot - Parking Lot|url=http://en.parkopedia.com/parking/lot/lvcc_gold_lot/89109/las_vegas/?arriving=201611050000&leaving=201611050200|website=Parkopedia.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> In 2019, work was underway on an expansion of the convention center. It will be built on the former sites of the Landmark and the nearby [[Riviera (hotel and casino)|Riviera]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gillan |first=Jeff |title=Billion dollar Las Vegas Convention Center expansion 45 percent complete |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/billion-dollar-las-vegas-convention-center-expansion-45-percent-complete |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |work=KSNV |date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Space Needle from Elliott Bay 2.jpg|thumb|right|The Landmark's design was inspired by Seattle's Space Needle tower]]\nThe Landmark tower was designed by architects Gerald Moffitt and Ed Hendricks.<ref name=Thoughts/><ref name=LivesUp/><ref name=Sidewalk>{{cite news|last=Covey|first=Hilda|title=Sidewalk Superintendent|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-03-1966-422012/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 3, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The uniquely designed Landmark tower was the first of its kind to be built in Nevada;<ref name=The-News/> its design was inspired by the [[Space Needle]] tower located in [[Seattle]], Washington.<ref name=AP-1965/> When construction stopped in 1962, the project consisted of {{convert|127614|sqft|abbr=on}} of floor space, and included two basements that were 30 feet deep. The tower's height measured 297 feet, while its diameter measured 60 feet. The tower's dome measured 141 feet in diameter.<ref name=Scherer/> In 1966 \u2013 the year that construction resumed \u2013 architects George Tate and Thomas Dobrusky were hired to design new portions of the resort, including the ground-floor casino.<ref name=Stalled/><ref name=Sidewalk/>\n\n===Height===\nThe Landmark tower was billed as having 31 floors, although it skipped floors 13 and 28.<ref name=Layout>{{cite web|title=Layout of the Landmark|url=https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/copy-of-specs|website=Landmark Memorial|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> The Landmark tower was the tallest building in the state from 1962 to 1969.<ref name=Sep1962/><ref name=Suit1963/><ref name=Hughes-Pay/><ref name=NewSkyline/> In 1967,<ref>{{cite web|title=1967: Pieces of the \"L\" sign are airlifted into place|url=https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/gallery?lightbox=image_css|website=Landmark Hotel Memorial|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> a revolving letter \"L\" neon sign was installed at the top of the tower.<ref name=SeenCalif>{{cite news|title=Can be seen from California on a clear day: Scherer tells about Landmark Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=October 24, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929092236/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Excluding its rooftop sign, the tower stood {{convert|297|ft|m}},<ref name=Scherer/><ref name=OnAgain>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower: On Again-Off Again|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-10-1968-420780/|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 10, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> seven feet taller than the [[The Mint Las Vegas|Mint hotel]] in downtown Las Vegas.<ref name=May18-66/><ref name=TalkProgress/>\n\nConflicting numbers have been given for the tower's total height. According to Scherer, the sign measured {{convert|40|ft|m}}, and the tower measured {{convert|328|ft|m}}, including the sign.<ref name=SeenCalif/> At the time of opening, the Landmark tower was billed as having a height of {{convert|346|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Buys Another Vegas Resort|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598951/the_press_democrat/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=United Press International|date=June 26, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013528/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598951/the_press_democrat/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=To-Open/><ref name=NewSkyline/> By that time, the new 30-story International Hotel had become the tallest building in the state at {{convert|375|ft|m}}.<ref name=NewSkyline/><ref>{{cite web|title=Las Vegas Hilton|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/122181/las-vegas-hilton-las-vegas-nv-usa|accessdate=October 25, 2017|publisher=[[Emporis]]}}</ref> When it was demolished, the tower reportedly stood {{convert|356|ft|m}}.<ref name=Implode/><ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/><ref name=Good>{{cite news|title=The Good Guys|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/94163556/|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=Herald and Review|date=April 28, 1996|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> According to [[Emporis]], the tower stood {{convert|331.50|ft|m}} from the ground to its roof, while the tip raised the height to a total of {{convert|364|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Landmark|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/102790/landmark-las-vegas-nv-usa|accessdate=October 25, 2017|publisher=Emporis}}</ref>\n\n===Features===\nWhen it opened, the Landmark had a total of 400 [[slot machine]]s.<ref name=Finishing/> The ground-floor casino was {{convert|14000|sqft|abbr=on}}, while a second casino, consisting of {{convert|3000|sqft|abbr=on}}, was located in the dome on the 29th floor; it was the first high-rise casino in the state.<ref name=NewSkyline/> At the time of opening, the ground-floor casino featured red and black colors, while the upper casino used orange coloring and wood.<ref name=Key1/> The hotel contained 476 rooms and 27 suites for a total of 503, a small number in comparison to other Las Vegas resorts, which commonly had 1,000 rooms.<ref name=Key2/> The tower included 157 hotel rooms,<ref name=Exhaust/> while the remaining units were located on ground level.<ref name=SeenCalif/> The rooms in the tower used a floorplan shaped like pie slices.<ref name=CT/> By 1977, the room count had increased to 524,<ref name=Ohio/> before ultimately being lowered to 498 at the time of its closure in 1990.<ref name=Bankrupt/>\n\nThe Landmark's interior designer was Las Vegas resident Leonard Edward England,<ref name=Trial/><ref name=Key2/> who designed the ground floor to include a colorful and primitive [[Incan Empire|Incan]] theme, which gradually changed to a [[Space Age]] theme on subsequent floors.<ref name=Apr6-68/> The interior included $200,000 light fixtures,<ref name=Key2>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=John L.|title=$20 Million Key Opens Hughes' 6th Vegas Hotel (page two)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599165/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 3, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013625/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599165/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> glowing, red-colored Incan masks, and a wall sculpture made of [[Burnishing (metal)|burnished metal]] that represented a launch from [[Cape Canaveral|Cape Kennedy]]. The interior also included 65 tons of black and white polished marble,<ref name=NewSkyline>{{cite news|title=New skyline for Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598996/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=United Press International|date=July 1, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011939/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598996/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Apr6-68/> as well as carved [[mahogany]] woodwork from Mexico.<ref name=Apr6-68/> In addition, the interior featured murals depicting the eight [[Wonders of the World]], which included the Landmark tower.<ref name=Pearlman/> The interior, including the casino, was considered to be spacious.<ref name=Pearlman/><ref name=Apr6-68/>\n\nAfter Hughes agreed to purchase the resort, he had an island built in the middle of the hotel's 240-foot swimming pool,<ref name=Finishing>{{cite news|title=Finishing touches made for two Vegas hotel openings|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599016/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=July 1, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012523/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599016/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> which cost $200,000<ref name=Hoopla/> and was the longest in the world.<ref name=Time>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas: The Game Is Illusion|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,900980,00.html|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Time|date=July 11, 1969|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The Landmark's pool included waterfalls and three carpeted bridges leading to its center island, which featured palm trees.<ref name=Key2/> For the hotel, Hughes replaced 72-inch beds with 80-inch beds and had color televisions built into the walls of each room ahead of the resort's opening.<ref name=Finishing/>\n\nThe Landmark's second floor was used for offices.<ref name=Layout/> The tower's dome included five floors, although floors 26 and 30 were used by employees for maintenance equipment, elevator equipment, and dressing rooms.<ref name=Layout/> The shape and strength of the tower's bubble dome was maintained by [[perlite]] concrete and steel [[girder]]s.<ref name=InsideBubble/> The Landmark included a high-speed exterior glass elevator<ref name=Key1/> \u2013 located on the tower's west side<ref name=Regal1/> and facing the Las Vegas Strip<ref name=SeenCalif/> \u2013 which took people up to the five-story [[cupola]] dome.<ref name=Cleared/> Elevator Services was hired to install the Landmark's exterior elevator, capable of moving 1,000 feet per minute, allowing people to go from the ground floor to the 31st floor in 20 seconds. It was the fastest elevator in the [[Western United States]].<ref name=Elevator>{{cite news|title=Landmark's Elevator to be Speedy|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-25-1966-420864/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 25, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Hughes biographer [[Michael Drosnin]] stated that the elevator was prone to constant malfunctions, and that the Landmark's air-conditioning system \"never really worked.\"<ref name=Citizen/> The dome provided wraparound views of the city,<ref name=Cleared/><ref name=Regal1/> and was capable of holding over 2,000 people.<ref name=Apr6-68/> The dome included lounges and a night club,<ref name=Regal1/> as well as the high-rise casino on the 29th floor.<ref name=Hoopla/>\n\nAt the time of the Landmark's opening, the showroom and the Cascade Terrace coffee shop were located on the first floor,<ref name=Key1/><ref name=Key2/><ref name=presents>{{cite news|title=The Landmark Presents|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-16-1970-424109/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 16, 1970|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> while a steak and seafood gourmet restaurant known as Towers Restaurant was located on the 27th floor.<ref name=Key2/><ref name=presents/> A Chinese restaurant, the Mandarin Room, operated on the 29th floor.<ref name=Key2/><ref name=presents/>\n\n[[Image:VegasLandMark-Night.jpg|thumb|right|270px|A 1995 photo of the tower, modified to depict its operational appearance in the 1980s]]\nIn April 1971, plans were announced for a $750,000 expansion that would include luxury suites on the 29th floor, the highest in Las Vegas at the time. Also planned was the remodeling of the casino and lobby, and the expansion of a coffee shop.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel to expand in Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11460125/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=April 20, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044117/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11460125/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> The Skytop Rendezvous, a piano bar and dance floor on the top floor of the tower, was reopened as a [[discotheque]] on February 3, 1975, specializing in [[Middle of the road (music)|middle of the road music]]. The Landmark was the only major hotel in the state to have a discotheque.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vegas Landmark Opens a Disco|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA74&dq=landmark+hotel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkmZfR-JrUAhVqqFQKHSWeBUs4ChDoAQgrMAE#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 8, 1975}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas' Landmark Sets A Disco Record For First|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QhEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT3&lpg=PT3&dq=landmark+hotel&source=bl&ots=DnUZLOTgq0&sig=Gy6bwajSW-l76OpnXv41bqlHqVM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwr-fb9ZrUAhVowVQKHQ3VBJcQ6AEIZTAJ#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 22, 1975}}</ref> When Morris' renovation began in December 1983, the tower contained 150 rooms, a number that was expected to be reduced as the rooms would be enlarged and upgraded to first class standards. Other plans included changes to the coffee shop, new casino carpeting, and redesigning and renaming the 27th-floor restaurant as Anthony's Seafood and Prime Rib Room.<ref name=Facelift/>\n\nThe existing structures were renovated with financing from Valley Bank of Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Morris v. Bank of America Nevada|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/nevada/supreme-court/1994/22881-1.html|website=Law.Justia.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=November 30, 1994|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044255/http://law.justia.com/cases/nevada/supreme-court/1994/22881-1.html|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> New red stripes were also added along the windows running up the tower and the roof was painted red to match. The entrance had red-lit outriggers added and a new side entrance was added to the casino.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} The Love Song Lounge operated on the top floor during the mid-1980s, before and after Morris' renovation,<ref name=Facelift/><ref name=NYE/> and offered dancing.<ref name=Combines>{{cite news|title=Restaurant combines dining with a view|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459964/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 7, 1986|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> During 1985 through 1987, the resort also operated the Sunset Room on the 27th floor, offering piano-bar music and fine dining,<ref name=NYE/><ref>{{cite news|title=Strong Earthquake Rocks Southern California|url= https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/9c03b6_889919bb64dd4897b029cf633adcf2d1.pdf|accessdate=February 18, 2018|agency=Associated Press|work=The Post-Standard|date=November 24, 1987}}</ref> with an emphasis on steaks and seafood.<ref name=Combines/> The Poolside Room operated on the ground level.<ref name=NYE>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel and Casino offering variety of New Year's Eve activities|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422564/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 22, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Nightcap Lounge opened at the Landmark in 1986, and offered comedy acts.<ref name=Combines/>\n\n===Reception===\nIn 1962, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the $6 million project, \"By far the most spectacular project\", out of several Las Vegas resorts that were under construction; the newspaper further wrote that the Landmark was \"destined to become the [[Mark Hopkins Hotel|Mark Hopkins]] of Las Vegas.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hulse|first=Jerry|title=On the Go: All That Glitters Is That Las Vegas Gold|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381396/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 5, 1962|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045724/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381396/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> The following year, the ''[[Reno Evening Gazette]]'' opined that the Landmark had \"the most unusual exterior architecture in Nevada.\"<ref name=Reno63>{{cite news|title=Space Needle or Hotel?|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11706897/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=July 13, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=February 23, 1963|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093400/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11706897/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In 1966, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' wrote that the mushroom-shaped Landmark tower had \"the most spectacular design\" of all recent high-rise structures in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas: How It Has Grown\u2026|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=landmark+hotel+casino&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu4Jfe-prUAhXjqFQKHczACOQ4FBDoAQhLMAk#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel%20casino&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 27, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://books.google.com/books?id=KBIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=landmark+hotel+casino&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu4Jfe-prUAhXjqFQKHczACOQ4FBDoAQhLMAk#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel%20casino&f=false|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> In 1993, architecture critic [[Alan Hess]] noted the simplicity of the Landmark and the nearby International Hotel when compared with previous Las Vegas casinos, writing, \"As singular, self-contained forms, they showed none of the complexity of the different pieces and sequential additions that made the original Strip visually and urbanistically richer.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Viva Las Vegas: After Hours Architecture|first=Alan|last=Hess|page=92|publisher=Chronicle Books|year=1993|isbn=081180111X}}</ref> In 2002, Geoff Carter of ''[[Las Vegas Weekly]]'' wrote that the demolished Landmark was \"Vegas' coolest building and a veritable shrine to 1960s '[[Googie]]' architecture.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Geoff|title=Tourists For Breakfast: Designing Vegas|url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|work=[[Las Vegas Weekly]]|date=April 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020621082703/http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|archivedate=June 21, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Performances==\n[[Peggy Lee]] performed at the Landmark in 1969.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Vegas |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/270647964/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=September 21, 1969 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=News |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/460230289/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=September 28, 1969 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> During 1971, the Landmark became well known for its performances by [[Country music|country singers]], including [[Kay Starr]], [[Jimmy Dean]], [[Patti Page]], [[Bobbie Gentry]], and [[Danny Davis (country musician)|Danny Davis]] with his Nashville Brass band, as well as a four-week show starring [[Ferlin Husky]] and [[Archie Campbell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Country Gaining in Las Vegas Hotels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=landmark+hotel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4t_La95rUAhWljVQKHTPDAgUQ6AEIRDAH#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 6, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412114322/https://books.google.com/books?id=7QgEAAAAMBAJ#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|archivedate=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Grand Ole Opry Due Tonight at Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/383148311/ |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=January 7, 1971 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> [[Frank Sinatra]] also performed at the Landmark, and [[Bobby Darin]] made one of his final appearances there.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1995/nov/07/landmark-falls/|title=Landmark Falls|last=Buntain|first=Rex|date=November 7, 1995|publisher=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=September 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924141605/https://lasvegassun.com/news/1995/nov/07/landmark-falls/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In May 1974, the Landmark launched ''Red McIlvaine's Star Search'', a variety show featuring people from across the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=Red's New Talent Show at Landmark |url=http://d.library.unlv.edu/digital/collection/jhp/id/13483 |website=Las Vegas Israelite |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=May 10, 1974 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1975,<ref>{{cite news|title=Halsey Picnic Draws $5,500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=exEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Billboard|date=November 15, 1975|page=TO-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321172954/https://books.google.com/books?id=exEEAAAAMBAJ#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=March 21, 2017}}</ref> [[Jim Halsey|The Jim Halsey Company]] began ''Country Music USA'', a show at the Landmark that featured a different country music [[Headliner (performances)|headliner]] every two to three weeks. The show was usually sold out.<ref name=Halsey>{{cite book|last=Halsey|first=Jim|title=Starmaker: How to Make it in the Music Business|date=2010|publisher=Tate Publishing|isbn=978-1607995418|pages=72\u201374, 84|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4j-hJbUaPnoC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> [[Roy Clark]] and [[Mel Tillis]] made their debuts in ''Country Music USA'',<ref name=Delaney/> as did [[Freddy Fender]].<ref name=Halsey/> [[The Oak Ridge Boys]] made their Las Vegas debut in ''Country Music USA''.<ref name=Halsey/><ref name=Delaney>{{cite news|last=Delaney|first=Joe|title=New book a reminder of LV's country ties|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/feb/09/columnist-joe-delaney-new-book-a-reminder-of-lvs-c/|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 9, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929233129/https://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/feb/09/columnist-joe-delaney-new-book-a-reminder-of-lvs-c/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> [[Leroy Van Dyke]] performed in the show during 1975, with Fender as his [[opening act]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Colleen|title=Nashville Scene|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QhEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT47&lpg=PT47#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 22, 1975}}</ref><ref name=Dyke/> Van Dyke performed again at the Landmark later in the 1970s, with [[Sons of the Pioneers]] as his opening act.<ref name=Dyke>{{cite news|title=Leroy Van Dyke|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/life/leroy-van-dyke/|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=February 8, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929232954/https://www.reviewjournal.com/life/leroy-van-dyke/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Other artists who performed in ''Country Music USA'' included [[Barbara Fairchild]], [[Johnny Paycheck]] and [[Tommy Overstreet]],<ref>{{cite news|title=What's Happening in Country|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/165973595/|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 26, 1975|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929232019/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/165973595/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> as well as [[Jody Miller]], [[Roy Head]], and [[Hank Thompson (musician)|Hank Thompson]].<ref name=Hanford/> ''Country Music USA'' ran for two years, until 1977.<ref name=Hanford>{{cite news|last=Searl|first=Hanford|title=Country Rolls for Vegas Jackpot|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p00EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT94&lpg=PT94#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Billboard|date=October 15, 1977}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1982, the Landmark debuted ''Spellcaster'', an 80-minute family oriented show featuring country-western singer Roy Clayborne.<ref name=Todd/><ref name=Clayborne1>{{cite news|last=McCann|first=Steven|title=Landmark opens \"Spellcaster\" featuring Roy Clayborne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422893/arizona_republic/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=October 17, 1982|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Clayborne2>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Landmark featuring singer Roy Clayborne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/170383510/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=November 21, 1982|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> ''Spellcaster'', a production show with dancers and [[showgirl]]s,<ref name=Todd/> featured Clayborne singing 15 songs.<ref name=Clayborne1/><ref name=Clayborne2/> ''Spellcaster'' was named after one of the Wolframs' [[racing horse]]s,<ref name=Todd/> and was produced through Zula Wolfram's Las Vegas production company, Zula Productions.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Toledo stockbroker center of investigation|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/304344275/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=The News-Messenger|location=Fremont, Ohio|date=March 1, 1983|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The show was designed and directed by [[Larry Hart (musician)|Larry Hart]],<ref name=Todd/><ref name=Clayborne1/><ref name=Clayborne2/> a [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Performance, Contemporary|1979 Grammy Award]] winner,<ref name=Clayborne1/><ref name=Clayborne2/> and it ran for approximately eight months.<ref name=Todd/> At the time of ''Spellcaster'''s debut, Danny Hein and Terri Dancer also began performing in the resort's Galaxy Lounge. Hein and Dancer had four different shows consisting of various costumes and set decorations, and were accompanied by a five-person band of musicians who backed up the duo.<ref name=Clayborne1/>\n\nAs of 1987, the Landmark's showroom hosted minor acts and was considered small in comparison to other Las Vegas resorts.<ref name=Arson/> In May 1988, the Landmark began hosting magician [[Melinda Saxe]] in a [[family-friendly]] magic show,<ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda has a bag of tricks for Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11427985/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 22, 1988|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda continues Landmark shows during the summer|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11428008/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 26, 1988|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Graham|first=Jefferson|title=New family emphasis may strip Vegas of glitz, glamour|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19890721.1.50|accessdate=March 2, 2018|agency=Gannett News Service|work=San Bernardino Sun|date=July 21, 1989}}</ref> known as '''88 Follies Revue''<ref>{{cite news|title=Calendar|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/121232271/|accessdate=March 2, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=May 29, 1988|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and renamed ''Follies Revue '89'' the following year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda's magic showcased nightly|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459807/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=February 19, 1989|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda's 'Mystery of Malaquena' truly unique|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459821/arizona_republic/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=May 28, 1989|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Saxe's show at the Landmark closed in late 1989.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jerry Lewis Telethon may leave Entertainment Capital|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459665/arizona_republic/|accessdate=March 2, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=January 21, 1990|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> During early 1990, the main showroom featured ''Spellbound'', a magic show consisting of two illusionist teams. Dick Foster was the show's director and producer.<ref name=Spellbound>{{cite news|title='Spellbound' Presents Many Unusual Illusions|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459636/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=February 11, 1990|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Foster>{{cite news|title=Foster's Magic Isn't An Illusion|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459651/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=April 29, 1990|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture ==\nThe unfinished tower briefly appears in the 1964 film, ''[[Viva Las Vegas]]''.<ref name=LHM/><ref>{{cite news|last=Bornfeld|first=Steve|title=Viva Viva Las Vegas!|url=http://vegasseven.com/2014/05/13/viva-viva-las-vegas/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Vegas Seven|date=May 13, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045450/http://vegasseven.com/2014/05/13/viva-viva-las-vegas/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In 1971, [[Sean Connery]] and [[stuntmen]] rode atop the Landmark's exterior elevator as part of filming for scenes in the James Bond film ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]''{{hsp}}; the tower was among other Las Vegas resorts that stood in as the fictional Whyte House hotel-casino.<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond Bulletin|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874896/colorado_springs_gazettetelegraph/|accessdate=July 14, 2017|work=[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|Colorado Springs Gazette-Telegraph]]|date=April 26, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924044839/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874896/colorado_springs_gazettetelegraph/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Michaels|first=Ken|title=That's about it, 007|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874936/chicago_tribune/|accessdate=July 14, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|date=July 11, 1971|quote=Yesterday it was the outdoor elevator of the Landmark, the stunt boys climbing up the building playing Bond, almost killing themselves.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924092753/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874936/chicago_tribune/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Christopher|title=When James Bond came to Las Vegas|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/christopher-lawrence/when-james-bond-came-to-las-vegas-photos/|accessdate=July 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=November 4, 2015|quote=To film the scene of Bond sneaking into The Whyte House penthouse, Connery rode atop the exterior elevator at the Landmark.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045352/https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/christopher-lawrence/when-james-bond-came-to-las-vegas-photos/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In the 1980s, the Landmark appeared in the television series ''[[Vega$]]'' and ''[[Crime Story (U.S. TV series)|Crime Story]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Landmark Hotel|url=https://nevadafilm.com/map-location/the-landmark-hotel/?mpfy_map=4181&mpfy-pin=4965|publisher=Nevada Film Office|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> In October 1994, the exterior entrance of the Landmark was lit up for one night so it could be used for outdoor shots as the fictional Tangiers casino, featured in the 1995 film, ''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]''.<ref name=QOTD/><ref>{{cite web|last=Kachelriess|first=Rob|title=9 \"Casino\" Filming Locations You Can Still Hit in Vegas Today|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/las-vegas/where-martin-scorsese-s-casino-was-filmed-9-las-vegas-locations|website=[[Thrillist]]|accessdate=June 29, 2017|date=April 12, 2015|quote=The exteriors of the fictional Tangiers were shot at the Landmark Hotel\u2026 which has since been demolished.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093141/https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/las-vegas/where-martin-scorsese-s-casino-was-filmed-9-las-vegas-locations|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cling|first=Carol|title='Casino' unflinching in its view of Las Vegas and its mob past|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/movies/casino-unflinching-in-its-view-of-las-vegas-and-its-mob-past/|accessdate=June 29, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=November 22, 2015|quote=10/14/1994 The Landmark hotel is transformed into the mythical 'Tangiers' for the movie \"Casino\".|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093114/https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/movies/casino-unflinching-in-its-view-of-las-vegas-and-its-mob-past/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Landmark's implosion was filmed for use in director [[Tim Burton]]'s 1996 film, ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''.<ref name=lvs1/><ref name=CT/><ref name=Mag/> In the film, the Landmark is portrayed as the fictional Galaxy Hotel, which is destroyed by an alien spaceship.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scene In Nevada: Mars Attacks!|url=https://nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-mars-attacks/|publisher=Nevada Film Office|accessdate=September 23, 2017|date=January 25, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203032706/https://www.nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-mars-attacks/|archivedate=February 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Katsilometes |first=John |title=Tim Burton was shaken, for real, at Las Vegas Landmark implosion |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/tim-burton-was-shaken-for-real-at-las-vegas-landmark-implosion-1870485/ |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> Burton had stayed at the hotel a few times and was upset by the decision to demolish it, so he wanted to immortalize it in his film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Production notes |url=http://marsattacks.warnerbros.com/cmp/5-prodnotes4.html#lasvegas |publisher=Warner Bros. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203133559/http://marsattacks.warnerbros.com/cmp/5-prodnotes4.html#lasvegas |archivedate=February 3, 2009 |date=1996}}</ref> A scale model of the Landmark tower was also made for the production of ''Mars Attacks!''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bell |first=Josh |title=Geek Road Trip: Tim Burton takes us on a tour of his Las Vegas |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/geek-road-trip-tim-burton-takes-us-on-a-tour-of-his-las-vegas |website=Syfy Wire |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> The demolition of the Landmark also appears during the closing credits of the 2003 film, ''[[The Cooler]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scene In Nevada: The Cooler|url=https://www.nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-the-cooler/|publisher=Nevada Film Office|accessdate=August 9, 2017|date=July 12, 2017}}</ref> The Lucky 38, a fictional tower casino featured in the 2010 video game ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]'', partially resembles the Landmark.<ref>{{cite news |last=Witcher |first=T.R. |title=Unexpected Art |url=https://vegasseven.com/2010/11/04/unexpected-art/ |work=VegasSeven |date=November 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208081545/https://vegasseven.com/2010/11/04/unexpected-art/ |archivedate=December 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[The Drew Las Vegas]], tallest building in Nevada since 2008; scheduled to open in 2022 after a construction delay\n\n== Notes ==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N1SREuX3pXs Slideshow of Landmark photos]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qYbQqgx9T-w Landmark demolition video]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NT4iPWzsf94 Footage of the Landmark's implosion used for ''Mars Attacks!'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Kaj1ew3d2U Eyewitness News Las Vegas news coverage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EUpNz2mhA2Y KLAS-TV news coverage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xDJ2jiim7MY KSNV news coverage]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SEn5UhQllqw KTNV-TV news coverage]\n* [https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/ Tribute to the Landmark]\n\n{{Las Vegas casinos}}\n{{Las Vegas hotels}}\n{{Las Vegas skyscrapers}}\n{{Buildings in Las Vegas timeline}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Landmark Hotel And Casino}}\n[[Category:Casinos completed in 1969]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1969]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 1969]]\n[[Category:1990 disestablishments in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Defunct casinos in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Defunct hotels in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Paradise, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Demolished hotels in Clark County, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Demolished hotels in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished by controlled implosion]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1995]]\n[[Category:1969 establishments in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Casino hotels]]\n[[Category:Demolished hotels]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Casino\n| casino        = Landmark\n| logo          = Landmark Hotel & Casino Logo.png\n| logo_size     = \n| image         = Landmark hotel 1986.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| image_caption = The Landmark in 1986, four years before closure, and nine years before implosion\n| address       = 364 Convention Center Drive<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Diana Ross reaches out and touches Las Vegas audiences at Caesars |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/120914330/ |website=The Arizona Republic |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=July 21, 1985 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com |quote=The Landmark Hotel is located at 364 Convention Center Drive [...].}}</ref>\n|location=[[Paradise, Nevada]] 89109\n| coordinates   = {{coord|36.133051|-115.155808|region:US-NV_type:landmark|display=title, inline}}\n| date_opened   = July 1, 1969\n| names_pre     = \n| date_closed   = {{end date and age|August 8, 1990}}\n| casino_type   = Land\n| owner         = {{collapsible list|title=List|Frank Caroll (1961\u201366)<br/>Plaza Tower, Inc (1966\u201369)<br>[[Hughes Tool Company]] (1969\u201373)<br>[[Summa Corporation]] (1973\u201378)<br>Lou and Jo Ann Tickel (1978\u201380)<br>Zula Wolfram (1978\u201383)<br/>Bill Morris (1983\u201390)<br/>[[Lloyds Bank]] (1990\u201393)<br/>[[Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority]](1993\u201395)}}\n| architect     = '''Initial design''':<br>Gerald Moffitt<br>Ed Hendricks<br>'''1966 design''':<br>George Tate<br>Thomas Dobrusky\n| theme         = [[Inca Empire|Incan]]<br>[[Space Age]]\n| rooms         = 503 (1969)<br>524 (1977)<br>498 (1990)\n| space_gaming  = {{convert|14000|sqft|abbr=on}} (ground floor)<br>{{convert|3000|sqft|abbr=on}} (29th floor)\n| attractions   = \n| notable_restaurants   = \n| renovations   = 1971, 1983\n| website       = \n}}\n\nThe '''Landmark'''{{efn|Commonly known simply as the \"Landmark\". During the 1960s, it was also known as \"Landmark Tower\",<ref name=LivesUp/><ref name=NewLife/><ref name=OnAgain/> and sometimes as \"Landmark Hotel\";<ref name=WayUp/><ref name=Pearlman/> the latter name was in common usage from 1969 onward.<ref name=REG/><ref name=Ohio/><ref name=Facelift/><ref name=BankBuys/> \"Landmark Hotel and Casino\" received some usage as well.<ref name=NYT/><ref name=NYE/><ref name=Foster/>}} was a [[hotel]] and [[casino]] located in [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]], [[Nevada]], east of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] and across from the [[Las Vegas Convention Center]]. The resort included a 31-floor tower, inspired by the design of the [[Space Needle]] tower in [[Seattle]]. Frank Caroll, the project's original owner, purchased the property in 1961. Fremont Construction began work on the tower that September, while Caroll opened the adjacent Landmark Plaza shopping center and Landmark Apartments by the end of the year. The tower's completion was expected for early 1963, but because of a lack of financing, construction was stopped in 1962, with the resort approximately 80 percent complete. Up to 1969, the [[Topping out|topped-off]] tower was the [[List of tallest buildings in Nevada|tallest building in Nevada]] until the completion of the [[Westgate Las Vegas Resort & Casino|International Hotel]] across the street.\n\nIn 1966, the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|Central Teamsters Pension Fund]] provided a $5.5 million construction loan to finish the project, with ownership transferred to a group of investors that included Caroll and his wife. The Landmark's completion and opening was delayed several more times. In April 1968, Caroll withdrew his request for a gaming license after he was charged with [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] against the project's interior designer. The Landmark was put up for sale that month.\n\nBillionaire [[Howard Hughes]], through [[Hughes Tool Company]], purchased the Landmark in 1969 at a cost of $17.3 million. Hughes spent approximately $3 million to add his own touches to the resort before opening it on July 1, 1969, with 400 [[slot machine]]s and 503 hotel rooms. In addition to a {{convert|14000|sqft|abbr=on}} ground-floor casino, the resort also had a second, smaller casino on the 29th floor; it was the first high-rise casino in Nevada. Aside from the second casino, the five-story [[cupola]] dome at the top of the tower also featured restaurants, lounges, and a night club.\n\nDuring the 1970s, the Landmark became known for its performances by [[country music]] artists. The resort also played host to celebrities such as [[Danny Thomas]] and [[Frank Sinatra]]. However, the resort suffered financial problems after its opening and underwent several ownership changes, none of which resulted in success. The Landmark entered bankruptcy in 1985, and ultimately closed on August 8, 1990, unable to compete with new megaresorts. The [[Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority]] purchased the property in September 1993, and demolished the resort in November 1995, to add a 2,200-space parking lot for its convention center. In 2019, work was underway on a convention center expansion which includes the former site of the Landmark.\n\n== History ==\nFrank Caroll, also known as Frank Caracciolo,<ref>{{cite news|title=Howard Hughes confirms offer to buy Tower hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=October 24, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929092236/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> was a building developer from Kansas City. In 1960, he and his wife Susan decided to construct a hotel-casino and shopping center in [[Las Vegas]].<ref name=QOTD/> Frank Caroll received a gaming license that year.<ref name=Nov66/> In 1961, the Carolls purchased {{convert|22|acre|abbr=on}} of land at the northwest corner of Convention Center Drive and [[Paradise Road (Las Vegas)|Paradise Road]] in [[Paradise, Nevada]],<ref name=lvs1>{{cite news |title=Implosions |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/history/implosions/ |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |accessdate=September 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716202302/https://lasvegassun.com/history/implosions/ |archivedate=July 16, 2017 }}</ref> approximately half a mile east of the [[Las Vegas Strip]] and across from the [[Las Vegas Convention Center]].<ref name=Finishing/><ref name=NewSkyline/> Aside from a gas station, the property was vacant.<ref name=QOTD/>\n\n===Construction (1961\u201368)===\n====Commencement====\nThe Landmark was initially planned as a 14-story hotel with a casino, although the floor count increased as the project progressed.<ref name=NewLife2/> Fremont Construction, owned by Louis P. Scherer of [[Redlands, California]],<ref name=SeenCalif/> began construction of the tower at the end of September 1961, under a $1.5 million contract.<ref name=Scherer61>{{cite news|title=Scherer building Las Vegas Landmark Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381236/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Redlands Daily Facts]]|date=October 14, 1961|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011756/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381236/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Scherer/> Frank Caroll's company, Caroll Construction Company, also worked on the tower.<ref name=InsideBubble>{{cite news|title=Inside the Bubble|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-16-1962-421918/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 16, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> At the start of construction, the tower was to include 20 stories,<ref name=Scherer61/> while completion was planned for early 1963.<ref name=Scherer>{{cite news|title=$2.5 million for completion: Scherer awarded contract to finish Vegas project|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11380987/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=August 23, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011849/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11380987/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> The tower was built on a five-foot-thick base of concrete and steel, measuring 80 feet in diameter and resting on a base of [[caliche]] that descended 30 feet into the ground.<ref name=SeenCalif/> Consolidated Construction Company was the concrete subcontractor for the tower.<ref name=InsideBubble/>\n\nBy December 1961,<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambling Applicants Approved|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/148272289/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=December 19, 1961|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093132/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/148272289/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> Caroll had opened the two-story Landmark Plaza shopping center,<ref name=Elevator/><ref name=Vegas7/> built out in an L-shape<ref name=NewLife/><ref name=NewLife2/> at the base of the tower.<ref name=Elevator/><ref name=OnAgain/> The Landmark Apartments, with 120 units,<ref name=Hofferd>{{cite news|title=Hofferd Named Manager of Landmark Tower Hotel|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-10-1962-420675/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 10, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> were also built near the tower and operational by the end of 1961.<ref name=LHM>{{cite web|title=Landmark Construction|url=https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/construction|website=Landmark Hotel Memorial|accessdate=September 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093112/https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/construction|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Apartments|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-23-1962-420651/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 23, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In 1962, a bar known as Shannon's Saloon and a western music radio station, KVEG, began operating in the Landmark Plaza.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ear to the Door|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-22-1962-424151/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 22, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=KVEG1/><ref name=KVEG2/> In addition to studios, KVEG also had its offices in the shopping center.<ref name=KVEG1>{{cite news|title=Radio KVEG Makes Debut In Las Vegas|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-23-1962-421812/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 23, 1963|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=KVEG2>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-27-1962-421730/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 27, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nBy February 1962, the tower was planned to include 31 floors, making it the [[List of tallest buildings in Nevada|tallest building in Nevada]]. While plans for a separate hotel structure were being made, work began by pouring concrete on a continuous 24-hour schedule. The concrete pour was done with a [[slip forming]] method. With 21 floors expected to be added to the tower over a 12-day period, it was expected to reach the 24th floor by the end of the month.<ref name=LivesUp>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Lives Up To Its Name|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-21-1962-420693/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 21, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Inspect>{{cite news|title=Inspect Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-14-1962-420636/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 14, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In March 1962, at the request of Caroll, [[Clark County Commission]]ers removed a restriction which specified that gaming licenses could only be issued for ground-level casinos, as Caroll wanted to open a casino on the second floor of the Landmark's shopping center.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gambling Rises In the World\u2013Up to 2nd Floor|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381262/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Reno Evening Gazette]]|date=March 14, 1962|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924092959/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381262/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Casinos May Now Move Off Ground Levels|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-13-1962-420940/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 13, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> That month, Caroll received a $450,000 loan from Appliance Buyers Credit Corporation (ABCC),<ref name=May18-66/><ref name=May18-66B/> a subsidiary of [[Whirlpool Corporation|RCA-Whirlpool]].<ref name=PlansFiled/>\n\nConstruction had reached the 26th floor by the end of April 1962. Upon completion of the floor, work was to begin on the tower's bubble dome.<ref name=WayUp>{{cite news|title=Way Up|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-22-1962-424163/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 22, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> By June 1962, ABCC loaned an additional $300,000 to Caroll, who reached his $3 million loan limit with the company.<ref name=May18-66>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower May Finally Have Owner (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-18-1966-420724/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 18, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=May18-66B>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower May Finally Have Owner (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-18-1966-420717/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 18, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Caroll ultimately owed ABCC a total of $3.5 million.<ref name=PlansFiled/> In August 1962, the Landmark tower was designated as a civilian [[fallout shelter]], with the capacity to hold 3,500 people after its completion.<ref name=Shelter>{{cite news|title=Select Shelter|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-17-1962-420997/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 17, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> That month, work was underway on the steel framework base for the tower's glass bubble dome.<ref>{{cite news|title=Saucer in the Air|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-aug-21-1962-p-8/|accessdate=February 8, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 21, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nBy September 1962, the Landmark tower was nearing completion and had become the tallest building in Las Vegas<ref name=Sep1962>{{cite news|title=Pointing Skyward|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-25-1962-420754/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 25, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> and the state,<ref name=Inspect/><ref name=AP-1965/><ref name=To-Open/> being visible from 20 miles away.<ref name=AP-1965/> By that time, many stores in the Landmark Plaza had closed due to falling debris that included welding sparks, steel, tools, rivets, and cement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-28-1962-421803/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 28, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> A construction delay occurred in September 1962, when shipments of steel for the tower's dome were deemed inadequate and crews had to wait for new shipments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-25-1962-421810/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 25, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Construction was progressing rapidly on the tower's dome during October 1962, with steel and concrete still being added to the tower.<ref>{{cite news|title=Giant in Sky|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-30-1962-421930/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 30, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Completion was still scheduled for early 1963.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gigantic Mushroom|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-23-1962-421945/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 23, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The Aluminium Division of Apex Steel Corporation Limited was contracted to install a $40,000 aluminum undershine on the tower's dome, to provide a maintenance-free and clean-looking appearance for viewers on the ground. Crews used scaffolding and hoists to reach the area where aluminum sheets needed to be placed. Each day, it took crews 18 minutes to be lifted up. Due to delays arising from strong winds, it took crews two months for the aluminium to be attached.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Tale Revealed|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-24-1963-421912/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 24, 1963|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Delay====\nIn December 1962, construction of the tower was stopped when ABCC denied further funding and alleged that the Carolls had defaulted on payments.<ref name=May18-66B/><ref name=Suit1963/> The 31-story tower had been [[Topping out|topped off]] and the resort was approximately 80 percent complete, with $5 million already spent on the project.<ref name=AP-1965/> The tower's planned opening was delayed until April 1963,<ref>{{cite news|title=Toots by Boots|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-07-1962-421923/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 7, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> but it did not occur as scheduled. In May 1963, ABCC was planning a sale of the apartments, shopping center, and unfinished tower for the following month. The Carolls sought to halt the sale, and filed a $2.1 million damage suit against ABCC, alleging that the company stopped construction and refused to pay the contractors.<ref name=Suit1963>{{cite news|title=Damage Suit Filed Over New Facility|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874595/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=July 13, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=May 21, 1963|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013505/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874595/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> An [[injunction]] against [[foreclosure]] was granted in June 1963,<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Foreclosure Halted|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-19-1963-421902/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 19, 1963|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> but was later dissolved in August 1964.<ref name=May18-66B/><ref name=HeadsAuction>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Heads For Auction|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-22-1964-425411/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 22, 1964|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In October 1964, a sale of the tower was approved for later that month, after being requested by ABCC, which was still owed $3.5 million by Landmark Plaza Corporation. Up to that time, the tower had been appraised several times and was valued between $8 million and $9 million.<ref name=HeadsAuction/><ref name=Auction64>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Auction Slated|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707140/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=July 13, 2017|agency=United Press International|work=Nevada State Journal|date=October 6, 1964|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013629/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707140/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> Ownership subsequently changed, as did the resort's design plans.<ref name=AP-1965/>\n\nIn August 1965, Maury Friedman was working on a deal with [[RCA Victor]] to convert the Landmark's tower and apartment buildings into office space.<ref>{{cite news|title=Around the Horn|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-30-1965-421860/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 30, 1965|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> By the following month, Inter-Nation Tower, Inc. \u2013 a Beverly Hills-based corporation \u2013 was negotiating with RCA-Whirlpool to develop the tower and adjacent land as an international market place, an idea that was supported by local retailers and resorts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Here's the latest on the future of the Landmark Tower|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-14-1965-421886/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 14, 1965|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In December 1965, architect Gerald Moffitt said the Landmark's design had gone through many revisions and that his design plans had been impounded by a court; a spokesman said there were no plans to resume construction in the near future. It was estimated that an additional six months were needed to complete the tower.<ref name=AP-1965>{{cite news|last=Lengel|first=John|title=Nevada's Tallest Unoccupied Structure: Landmark Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438084/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|agency=Associated Press|date=December 27, 1965|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924095245/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438084/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe unfinished tower became an eyesore for visitors to the nearby convention center.<ref name=OnAgain/> During its vacancy, people noted that the building appeared to be tilted, similar to the [[Leaning Tower of Pisa]]; experts stated that this was an illusion caused when the building was viewed with nearby [[power pole]]s, which were tilted rather than the building itself.<ref name=AP-1965/><ref>{{cite news|title=Leaning Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438148/pensacola_news_journal/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=[[Pensacola News Journal]]|date=June 1, 1962|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929091137/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11438148/pensacola_news_journal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Thoughts>{{cite news|title=Thoughts While Shaving|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-06-1962-420704/|accessdate=October 13, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 6, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Local residents nicknamed it the \"Leaning Tower of Plaza\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Hertz|first=Murray|title=Sun Dial|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-10-1962-421766/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 10, 1962|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> the \"Leaning Tower of Las Vegas\", and \"[[Folly|Frank's Folly]].\"<ref name=QOTD>{{cite news|title=Question of the Day|url=https://www.lasvegasadvisor.com/question/2007-05-14/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Advisor|date=May 14, 2007}}</ref> Moffitt said, \"It doesn't tilt. There is only three-eights of an inch difference in diameter from top to bottom.\"<ref name=AP-1965/> In May 1966, early negotiations were being held with a prospective buyer of the Landmark.<ref name=TalkProgress>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Talk in Progress|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-26-1966-420776/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 26, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Resumption====\nIn July 1966, new design plans were filed with the county for the completion of the tower.<ref name=PlansFiled>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Plans Filed in Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707018/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=August 9, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=July 6, 1966}}</ref> Scherer planned to acquire additional property for use as a parking lot to accommodate the redesigned project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Flash|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-08-1966-421968/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 8, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=PlansFiled/> In August 1966, the [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|Central Teamsters Pension Fund]] provided a $5.5 million construction loan for the project.<ref name=NewLife>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower--New Life (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-17-1966-420736/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 17, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=NewLife2>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower--New Life (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-17-1966-420734/|accessdate=December 5, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 17, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Resume/> By that time, ownership had been transferred to Plaza Tower, Inc., made up of several investors, including the Carolls and Scherer, whose construction company was awarded a $2.5 million contract to finish the Landmark tower. Because of legal problems involved with the project, the acquisition of title required over 5,000 hours of legal work and the settlement of more than 40 lawsuits.<ref name=Resume>{{cite news|title=Vegas Hotel Construction to Resume|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381501/independent/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Press-Telegram|Independent]]|date=August 19, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381501/independent/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Scherer/><ref>{{cite news|title=Work to Be Resumed on Las Vegas Casino|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381499/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 19, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013638/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381499/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> Construction was underway again in early September 1966,<ref>{{cite news|last=Cronan|first=John|title=Only on Sunday|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-04-1966-424148/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 4, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> with completion expected in early 1967.<ref name=Scherer/> The shops and taverns in the Landmark Plaza were closed,<ref name=OnAgain/><ref>{{cite news|title=Last Wake|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-26-1966-421977/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 26, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Spot|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-sep-26-1966-421996/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=September 26, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> and the shopping center and gas station were demolished,<ref name=OnAgain/> so the land around the tower could be used to construct a casino, a hotel lobby, offices, and new shops.<ref name=NewLife/><ref name=NewLife2/> The adjacent Landmark apartments were to be converted into hotel rooms for the new resort.<ref name=Scherer/>\n\nIn November 1966, Caroll planned to install two slot machines inside the Landmark Coffee Shop, which sold food to construction workers from inside a temporary structure that was to become the site of a permanent building eventually. Caroll's plans were denied as his gaming license did not apply to the coffee shop. At the time, Caroll was also accused by sheriff [[Ralph Lamb]] of being uncooperative with police officers who were searching for a [[hoodlum]] at the Landmark Apartments.<ref name=Nov66>{{cite news|title=Landmark Builder Told 'License Down Drain'|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-11-1966-420950/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 11, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Landmark had been scheduled to open on September 15, 1967, but its opening was further delayed because of construction problems. In October 1967, a new opening date of November 15 was announced, with an official [[grand opening]] to be held on December 31, 1967.<ref name=The-News>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel Delays Opening in Las Vegas|url=http://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/9c03b6_1e36dace30794cd0b4c01329a4c25b9a.pdf|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=The News|location=Van Nuys, California|date=October 17, 1967|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012936/http://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/9c03b6_1e36dace30794cd0b4c01329a4c25b9a.pdf|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> In early November 1967, Scherer was awarded a $2.2 million contract for the final construction phase of the Landmark. Construction crews worked 24 hours a day for each day of the week during the final phase to have the 650-seat dinner showroom theater ready for the planned New Year's Eve opening. Also included in the final phase were clothing and jewelry shops, as well as a recreation area with swimming pools and a 20-foot waterfall.<ref>{{cite news|title=$2.183 million in Las Vegas: Scherer gets Tower bid|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707078/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=August 9, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=November 1, 1967|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011846/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707078/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy the time of its planned New Year's Eve opening, the tower was nearly complete, with an opening now scheduled for mid-January 1968.<ref name=Pittsburgh>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Harold V.|title=At Random: Report From Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381025/pittsburgh_postgazette/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=December 27, 1967|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012355/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381025/pittsburgh_postgazette/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> In December 1967, two groups \u2013 Plaza Tower Inc., the property's landlord group; and Plaza Tower Operating Corporation, the casino operating group \u2013 submitted a request for a gaming license to the [[Nevada Gaming Control Board]], which investigates licensees and top casino employees prior to issuing gaming licenses.<ref name=OnAgain/> The Landmark's opening did not occur as scheduled.<ref name=Withdraws/>\n\nDuring February and March 1968, the Landmark was declared as being completed,<ref name=Pearlman>{{cite news|last=Pearlman|first=Ralph|title=Vegas Daze and Nights|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-24-1968-424123/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 24, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=World's Greatest|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-feb-25-1968-427258/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 25, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com|quote=The completed, but as yet unopened Landmark Tower hotel.}}</ref><ref name=OnAgain/><ref name=Objection/> although it was stated the following year that some construction work remained unfinished.<ref name=Revamping/> At the time of its stated completion in 1968, a total of 200,000 hours had been spent working on the project, which used 100,000 yards of concrete and 100 tons of steel.<ref name=Apr6-68>{{cite news|title=One Never Knows\u2026 Until One Goes!|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-06-1968-424133/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 6, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The tower occupied {{convert|8.21|acre|abbr=on}} of the property,<ref>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Home, Downtown Taxes Jump Oftener Than Strip|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-21-1969-425421/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 21, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> and remained as the tallest building in the state.<ref name=Hughes-Pay/>\n\n===Further developments (1968\u201369)===\n====Gaming license====\nIn February 1968, an updated list of top casino employees was submitted to the gaming control board, which had up to 90 days to make a decision regarding the issuance of a gaming license. An opening date of mid-April 1968 was considered possible.<ref name=OnAgain/> In March 1968, the Nevada Gaming Control Board recommended against the issuance of a gaming license due to \"inadequate financial capabilities and resources of the operating corporation and of its principal investor\", referring to Caroll.<ref name=Withdraws/> However, the [[Nevada Gaming Commission]] had the Gaming Control Board reevaluate the license application.<ref name=Apr22-68/><ref name=BidWithdraw/>\n\nOn April 5, 1968, the Las Vegas media was given a tour of the Landmark.<ref name=Apr6-68/> During the event, Caroll beat the Landmark's interior designer, Leonard Edward England, for allegedly flirting with Caroll's wife. Caroll was arrested on April 17, 1968, on charges of [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] against England.<ref name=Trial>{{cite news|title=Frank Caroll Trial Slated|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-19-1968-422046/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 19, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=BidWithdraw/><ref name=DA/><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Against Casino Owner: $725,000 Assault Suit Filed|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-oct-26-1968-p-3/|accessdate=February 8, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 26, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> On April 22, 1968, Caroll withdrew his request for a gaming license,<ref name=Apr22-68>{{cite news|title=Caroll Rescinds Gaming Request For Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-23-1968-422070/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 23, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> a decision that was approved two days later.<ref name=BidWithdraw>{{cite news|title=Bid To Withdraw Gaming License Given Approval|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-apr-25-1968-422079/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 25, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The company then planned to receive new financing and to eventually submit a new gaming application. Approximately 600 people were expected to be employed at the Landmark upon its opening.<ref name=Withdraws>{{cite news|title=Vegas Casino Withdraws Game License Application|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707244/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=August 9, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=April 25, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012306/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707244/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> The Landmark was put up for sale in April 1968,<ref name=Sun-Realty/> and the charges against Caroll were dropped two months later on the condition that he not renew his gaming license application.<ref name=DA>{{cite news|title=Landmark Owner Sees D.A. Dismiss Charges|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-13-1968-422089/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 13, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Many Unanswered Questions Follow Franklin Action|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jun-18-1968-420919/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=June 18, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Plane crash====\nOn the night of August 2, 1968, 39-year-old Everett Wayne Shaw, a mechanic depressed by the break-up of his month-long marriage, stole a [[Cessna 180]] plane as part of an apparent suicide attempt. Shaw flew the plane toward the Landmark tower and pulled up just before hitting it. The plane brushed the top of the tower before crashing into the Las Vegas Convention Center across the street, approximately 200 yards away. Shaw was killed in the crash, which did not harm anyone else. Plane debris was found on the Landmark's roof and at its base, but the crash was not believed to have caused any damage to the building.<ref>{{cite news|title=Body Recovered From Wreck; Police Hunt Other Victims|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-03-1968-420805/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 3, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Police Hint Suicide In Plane Crash|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-04-1968-422106/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 4, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Vegas Plane Crash Considered Suicide|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/78950635/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|agency=United Press International|work=Nevada State Journal|date=August 4, 1968|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924050458/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/78950635/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Plane Crash Into Tower Held Suicide|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/166582890/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 4, 1968|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924044908/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/166582890/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Financial problems====\nIn May 1968, the Teamsters Pension Fund filed a notice of breach on the trust deed, alleging that Caroll, Plaza Tower Inc. and Plaza Tower Operating had been defaulting on loan payments since October 1967.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trust Deed Holders Sue For Building|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-16-1968-420788/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 16, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In late August 1968, Las Vegas-based Supreme Mattress Company filed a lawsuit stating that it had only received $4,250 in payments for $25,505 worth of bedding material that was sold to the Landmark in December 1967.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark May Be 'Matressless'|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-25-1968-425532/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 25, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 1968, a joint petition was filed to declare the Landmark bankrupt. The petition was filed by Vegas Valley Electric, Inc., a plumbing contractor, and Landmark architects George Tate and Thomas Dobrusky. By that time, the Teamsters Union Pension Fund agreed to delay its foreclosure until the property was sold. Simultaneously, Sylvania Electric Company had intended to foreclose on the property because of an unpaid $3.7 million bill relating to electronic equipment installed in the Landmark. The joint petition prevented Sylvania from taking over ownership of the property.<ref name=Stalled>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Foreclosure Stalled: Bankruptcy Hearings For Landmark Ordered (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-30-1968-422139/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 30, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Foreclosure Stalled: Bankruptcy Hearings For Landmark Ordered (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-30-1968-422134/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 30, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Sale negotiations and Howard Hughes====\nIn July 1968, there were five firms interested in purchasing the Landmark, which was expected to sell for $16 million to $17 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=For Sale Sign Still Out: Man Who Holds Official Pen Denies Landmark Tower Sold|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-11-1968-420793/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 11, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> One of the firms, Olla Corporation, withdrew consideration of a purchase later that month, while an announcement of the resort's sale was expected within several days.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Purchase Still Expected By Owners|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1968-422097/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Several companies made purchase offers that were ultimately rejected, including Rosco Industries Inc., based in Los Angeles.<ref name=Firm/> On October 12, 1968, Caroll denied a report that the Landmark would be leased to Royal Inns of America, Inc. and operated without a casino. At the time, negotiations were underway with three corporations interested in purchasing the resort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Lease Report Brings Swift Denial|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-13-1968-422151/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 13, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Howard Hughes 1938.jpg|right|thumb|[[Howard Hughes]], pictured in 1938, purchased the Landmark in 1969]]\nOn October 23, 1968, billionaire [[Howard Hughes]] reached an agreement to purchase the Landmark through [[Hughes Tool Company]] for $17.3 million,<ref name=Hughes-Pay/><ref name=Tool/> after previously denying reports in March 1968 that he was interested in purchasing the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaming Policy Board to View Hughes-Stardust Plan|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707311/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=March 13, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929045012/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11707311/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Laxalt Calls Meet To Discuss Hughes, Stardust Resort|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-13-1968-422029/|accessdate=December 7, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 13, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> As part of the sale agreement, Hughes' Hotel Properties, Inc. would accept responsibility for approximately $8.9 million owed to the Teamster Union, as well as approximately $5.9 million in other debts and a balance of $2.4 million to Plaza Tower, Inc.<ref name=Debut2/> At the time of the agreement, Hughes also owned five other hotel-casinos in Las Vegas.<ref name=Hughes-Pay>{{cite news|title=Hughes Will Pay $17.3 Million For 28-Story Las Vegas Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381043/arizona_daily_star/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Arizona Daily Star]]|date=October 24, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927113412/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381043/arizona_daily_star/|archivedate=September 27, 2017}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Justice]] then launched an [[United States antitrust law|antitrust]] investigation into Hughes' proposed purchase, after previously investigating his attempt to purchase the [[Stardust Resort and Casino]], a transaction that he was blocked from completing for antitrust reasons.<ref name=Firm>{{cite news|title=El Monte Firm Plans to Bid for Las Vegas Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616948/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 31, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927113550/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616948/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=September 27, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Objection/> As part of the investigation, the Department of Justice attempted to determine if there were other prospective buyers for the Landmark.<ref name=Firm/>\n\nBy December 1968, while the Department of Justice continued its investigation, negotiations were underway with several firms that were interested in purchasing the Landmark, which included a $20 million offer from Tanger Industries, a [[holding company]] based in [[El Monte, California]].<ref name=Firm/><ref name=Pearl>{{cite news|last=Pearl|first=Ralph|title=Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616924/honolulu_starbulletin/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]]|date=December 15, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11616924/honolulu_starbulletin/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Business Tide|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/338894725/|accessdate=February 8, 2018|work=[[The Des Moines Register]]|date=January 2, 1969|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> It was reported that Hughes' attempted purchase would be rejected by the Department of Justice, despite his offer to convert the building into office space.<ref name=Pearl/>\n\n====Hughes purchase and opening preparations====\nOn January 17, 1969, the Department of Justice approved Hughes' plan to purchase the Landmark as his sixth Las Vegas resort.<ref name=Objection>{{cite news|title=No Government Objection To Hughes on Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381065/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 18, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011941/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381065/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Gets Approval|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jKEwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oEQDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2627%2C1189644|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=[[The Virgin Islands Daily News]]|date=January 20, 1969}}</ref> Later that month, a $1.5 million lawsuit was filed against Hughes Tool Company by Pennsylvania resident James U. Meiler and New York brokerage firm John R. Roake and Son, Inc. Meiler and the brokerage firm stated that they were entitled to a $500,000 brokerage fee for previously arranging a sale of the Landmark to Republic Investors Holding Company, which was to pay between $15.3 million and $16 million for the resort until Hughes Tool Company agreed to purchase it. Meiler and the brokerage firm alleged that when Hughes Tool Company agreed to purchase the Landmark, it \"purposely and intentionally caused a restraining of interstate commerce\", referring to the $500,000 fee.<ref name=Tool>{{cite news|title=Hughes Tool Co. Sued By Broker Firm|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-24-1969-425426/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 24, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of January 1969, Hughes spokesmen stated that some construction on the resort was never finished; that some maintenance systems had not yet been installed; and that some repairs were needed. Hughes also planned to have some of the hotel rooms refurbished. Because of the additional work, the resort was not expected to open until at least July 1, 1969. Approximately 1,000 to 1,100 people were expected to be employed at the Landmark.<ref name=Revamping>{{cite news|title=Landmark Revamping Delays Opening Plans|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-30-1969-420817/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 30, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The Landmark was the only casino that Hughes had taken over before it was opened. As a result, Hughes was heavily involved in details regarding the project.<ref name=Vegas7>{{cite web|last=Rodgers|first=Lissa Townsend|title=A Brief History of Howard Hughes' Landmark Hotel|url=http://vegasseven.com/2016/11/03/brief-history-howard-hughes-landmark-hotel/|website=VegasSeven.com|accessdate=May 4, 2017|date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004064241/http://vegasseven.com/2016/11/03/brief-history-howard-hughes-landmark-hotel/|archivedate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> Hughes spent approximately $3 million to give the interior a lavish design and to [[#Features|add other touches to the resort]],<ref name=To-Open>{{cite news|title=Landmark to open July 1 in Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598932/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=June 25, 1969}}</ref><ref name=Key1>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=John L.|title=$20 Million Key Opens Hughes' 6th Vegas Hotel (page one)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599143/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 3, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599143/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> while the exterior of the Landmark buildings was left unchanged.<ref name=NewSkyline/>\n\nIn March 1969, Hughes applied for approval to operate the Landmark's gambling operations, with a tentative opening date of July 1, 1969. Hughes planned to operate the casino through his Nevada company, Hughes Properties Inc., which was overseen by Hughes executive Edward H. Nigro. Hughes planned for the resort to include 26 table games and 401 slot machines.<ref name=Debut1/><ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Applies To Operate The Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598764/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=March 5, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598764/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> Hughes' purchase of the Landmark was not complete at that time, and his representatives stated that the sale would not be completed unless gambling and liquor licenses were issued by the state.<ref name=Debut1>{{cite news|title=Hughes Gearing for July 1 Landmark Debut (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-05-1969-425434/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 5, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Debut2>{{cite news|title=Hughes Gearing for July 1 Landmark Debut (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-05-1969-425437/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 5, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In April 1969, Hughes received approval from the Gaming Control Board and from the state.<ref>{{cite news|title=Control Board Approves Bid For Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598857/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Nevada State Journal|date=April 15, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013644/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598857/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Given State Approval For 6th Casino|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598887/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=April 24, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013224/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598887/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHughes planned to personally oversee planning for the Landmark's grand opening; [[Robert Maheu]], who had worked for Hughes since the 1950s, said \"I knew from that point on that I was in trouble. He was completely incapable of making decisions.\"<ref name=Bio/> Across the street from the Landmark, [[Kirk Kerkorian]] was planning to open his [[Westgate Las Vegas Resort & Casino|International Hotel]] on July 2, 1969. Hughes and Maheu \u2013 who never met each other in person due to Hughes' [[reclusive]] lifestyle \u2013 had intense arguments about the Landmark's opening date that lasted for months. Maheu believed the Landmark should open on July 1, but Hughes did not want to commit to an exact date for various reasons. Hughes had wanted the Landmark's grand opening event to be better than Kerkorian's, but was concerned that the opening night would not go as planned. Hughes also did not want the opening date to be publicly announced too soon in the event that it should be delayed; Hughes wrote to Maheu: \"With my reputation for unreliability in the keeping of engagements, I dont [sic] want this event announced until the date is ''absolutely firmly'' established.\"<ref name=Citizen/>\n\nAdditionally, Hughes wrote to Maheu: \"I would hate to see the Landmark open on the 1st of July and then watch the International open a few days later and make the Landmark opening look like small potatoes by comparison.\" Maheu became concerned, as it was difficult to plan the grand opening without knowing the date.<ref name=Citizen>{{cite book|last=Drosnin|first=Michael|title=Citizen Hughes|date=2004|publisher=Broadway Books|isbn=0767919343|pages=318\u2013325|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Jlx-bcbx8_oC&pg=PA318&lpg=PA318|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> As the tentative opening date approached, Hughes became concerned about other events scheduled for July 1969 \u2013 such as the [[Apollo 11]] moon landing \u2013 which might distract from the publicity of the Landmark's opening.<ref name=Citizen/> By mid-June 1969, Hughes had still not given a definite opening date, which was still tentatively scheduled for July 1, although Hughes had wanted the Landmark to open sometime after the International Hotel.<ref name=Citizen/> Weeks before the tentative opening, Hughes obsessively made repeated changes to the guest list for the resort's opening night. Regarding who should be invited, Hughes had complex specifications for Maheu to follow. Maheu ultimately had to decide the guest list himself.<ref name=Bio/><ref name=Citizen/>\n\nOn June 16, 1969,<ref name=Cleared/> Sun Realty filed a claim against Plaza Tower, Inc., thus delaying Hughes' purchase of the Landmark and threatening its planned opening. Sun Realty alleged that it was owed a $500,000 [[finder's fee]] for locating Hughes as a buyer. The case was dismissed on June 25, 1969.<ref name=REG>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel Might Not Open on Schedule|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617560/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=June 24, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617560/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Way Cleared For Hughes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617572/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=June 26, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617572/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Cleared>{{cite news|title=Landmark Tower Opening Cleared|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617601/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=United Press International|date=June 27, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617601/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> On June 30, 1969, Sun Realty appealed the decision but was denied that day as it was unable to post a bond that would pay the $5.8 million worth of claims filed by approximately 120 other creditors after Plaza Towers Inc. entered bankruptcy.<ref name=Climax2/><ref name=Cleared/> Hughes' $17.3 million acquisition of the Landmark,<ref name=Climax1/> through Hughes Tool Company, was completed on July 1, 1969,<ref name=ownership/> a day after Hughes issued checks to three different entities to complete the purchase: $2.5 million to Plaza Towers; $5.8 million to fully pay unsecured creditors; and $9 million to pay off the Teamsters Union.<ref name=Climax1>{{cite news|title=It's Hughes' Landmark Now! 11th Hour Climax In Tower Deal (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-01-1969-421836/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 1, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Climax2>{{cite news|title=It's Hughes' Landmark Now! 11th Hour Climax In Tower Deal (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-01-1969-421842/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 1, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and operation (1969\u20131990)===\nThe Landmark opened on the night of July 1, 1969,<ref name=Finishing/><ref name=Key1/><ref name=Skyhigh>{{cite news|last=Browning|first=Norma Lee|title=Sky-High Casino|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599226/chicago_tribune/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|date=July 3, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924050517/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599226/chicago_tribune/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> a day before the International Hotel.<ref name=Hoopla/><ref name=Vegas7/> The resort was first unveiled to 480 VIP guests prior to the public opening, which was scheduled for after 9:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=Climax1/> [[Apollo 10]] astronauts [[Thomas P. Stafford]] and [[Eugene Cernan]] attended the grand opening, and were the first people to enter the new resort.<ref>{{cite news|title=Astronauts at Landmark opening|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599090/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=July 1, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093129/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599090/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Hoopla>{{cite news|last=Borders|first=Myram|title=Two Casino-Hotels Open in Las Vegas With Usual Hoopla|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11618366/lansing_state_journal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=United Press International|date=July 6, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093300/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11618366/lansing_state_journal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> Other guests included [[Cary Grant]], [[Dean Martin]], [[Jimmy Webb]], [[Phil Harris]], [[Tony Bennett]], [[Sammy Cahn]], [[Steve and Eydie]], and [[Wilt Chamberlain]].<ref>{{cite news|title=It's too hot for Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149621330/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=July 8, 1969|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924092957/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149621330/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> Nevada governor [[Paul Laxalt]], as well as senators [[Alan Bible]] and [[Howard Cannon]], were also at the opening.<ref name=Regal1/><ref name=Regal2/> Three members of the [[Los Angeles Rams]] were also in attendance: [[Jack Snow (American football)|Jack Snow]], [[Lamar Lundy]], and [[Roger Brown (defensive tackle)|Roger Brown]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Snyder|first=Jimmy|title=Sports|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-02-1969-425487/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 2, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nLocal, national and international media were also present for the grand opening, which was described by the ''[[Las Vegas Sun]]'' as resembling a Hollywood premiere.<ref name=Regal1/><ref name=Regal2/> A [[closed-circuit television]] camera filmed the festivities in the Landmark on opening night, with the footage being shown live to guests at Hughes' other hotels, the [[Sands Hotel and Casino|Sands]] and the [[New Frontier Hotel and Casino|Frontier]].<ref name=Regal1>{{cite news|last=Chrystal|first=Chris|title=Landmark's Debut Regal: Governor, Senators Join Vegans to Hail Grand Opening (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-02-1969-425466/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 2, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Regal2>{{cite news|last=Chrystal|first=Chris|title=Landmark's Debut Regal: Governor, Senators Join Vegans to Hail Grand Opening (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-02-1969-425480/|accessdate=December 12, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 2, 1969|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Hughes \u2013 who lived in a secluded penthouse at his nearby [[Desert Inn]] hotel-casino<ref name=Bio/><ref name=Citizen/> \u2013 did not attend the grand opening.<ref name=Skyhigh/><ref name=Citizen/> For opening night, comedian [[Danny Thomas]] was the first to perform in the Landmark's theater-restaurant showroom.<ref name=Key2/><ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> Hughes had earlier suggested a [[Rat Pack]] reunion or a [[Bob Hope]]-[[Bing Crosby]] reunion as the opening act, both of which were considered unlikely to happen.<ref name=Bio>{{cite news|last=Evans|first=K.J.|title=Howard Hughes|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/howard-hughes/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=September 12, 1999}}</ref>\n\nTelevision advertisements for the resort stated: \"In France, it's the Eiffel Tower. In India, it's the Taj Mahal. In Las Vegas, it's the Landmark.\"<ref name=Time/> Dick Parker, executive vice president for the Landmark, had stated during the previous year that the International and the nearby Las Vegas Convention Center would not harm the Landmark's business.<ref name=Pearlman/> The Landmark reportedly lost $5 million in its first week of operations,<ref name=QOTD/> and despite its close proximity to the convention center, the resort failed to make a profit during the subsequent years of its operation.<ref name=Ohio/><ref name=Whiz/> In October 1969, Sun Realty filed a damages lawsuit against Hughes Tool Company and Plaza Tower, Inc, alleging that the two companies conspired to avoid paying the realty company its $500,000 finder's fee. Aside from the finder's fee, Sun Realty also sought an additional $5 million in [[punitive damages]].<ref name=Suit>{{cite news|title=$5.5 million asked in suit against Hughes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617627/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=October 4, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929091349/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11617627/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In February 1971, the [[Supreme Court of Nevada|Nevada supreme court]] rejected the lawsuit, which had sought $3 million by that time.<ref name=Sun-Realty>{{cite news|title=Court rejects hotel suit against Hughes firm|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381118/arizona_republic/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[United Press International]]|date=February 27, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929092234/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381118/arizona_republic/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In December 1971, Hughes paid a little over $1 million to purchase {{convert|9.86|acre|abbr=on}} of adjacent land located west of the Landmark.<ref>{{cite web|title=Parcel Ownership History|url=http://sandgate.co.clark.nv.us/assrrealprop/ParcelHistory.aspx?instance=pcl2&parcel=16209703006|publisher=Clark County Assessor's Office|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Buys10/> Hughes had previously leased the property, which he had been using as a parking lot for the resort.<ref name=Buys10>{{cite news|title=Hughes Buys 10 acres on strip|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11460142/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 22, 1972|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1973, ownership of the Landmark was transferred to Hughes' [[Summa Corporation]],<ref name=ownership>{{cite web|title=Landmark property ownership|url=http://sandgate.co.clark.nv.us/assrrealprop/ParcelHistory.aspx?instance=pcl2&parcel=16209703007|publisher=Clark County Assessor's Office|accessdate=May 11, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000829/http://sandgate.co.clark.nv.us/assrrealprop/ParcelHistory.aspx?instance=pcl2&parcel=16209703007|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> formerly Hughes Tool Company.<ref name=Sale-Fails/> That year, the Landmark was valued at $25 million in a property appraisal.<ref name=Offered12m/> By 1974, [[William G. Bennett (gaming executive)|William Bennett]] and [[William Pennington (businessman)|William Pennington]] made an offer to buy the Landmark, but Hughes raised the price several times, from $15 million to $20 million; they bought the [[Circus Circus Las Vegas|Circus Circus]] resort instead.<ref name=WorldsLargest>{{cite news|last=Macy|first=Robert|title=Las Vegas hotel opens as world's largest|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422984/the_kokomo_tribune/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=The Kokomo Tribune|agency=Associated Press|date=June 1, 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929043950/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422984/the_kokomo_tribune/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> In January 1976, the Landmark began offering foreign-language gaming video tapes to its German, Japanese, and Spanish hotel guests, who frequently limited themselves to playing slot machines rather than table games because of language barriers. Summa general manager E. H. Milligan said, \"As far as we know, we are the first hotel in Las Vegas to present this service in this manner.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Gaming Tapes Available For Foreign Visitors|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jan-22-1976-423176/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=January 22, 1976|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The hotel and casino briefly closed in March 1976, as part of a hotel worker strike consisting of nearly 25,000 employees, affecting 15 Las Vegas resorts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas Jarred By Strike|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11436595/the_daily_herald/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency=United Press International|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]|date=March 12, 1976|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Hotels Package Deal Backfires|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-21-1976-423207/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 21, 1976|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The strike lasted two weeks before ending in late March.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Two-Week Strip Strike Comes To End|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/las-vegas-sun-mar-26-1976-p-4/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 26, 1976|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Hughes died of [[kidney failure]] the following month.<ref name=Bio/> James Wadsworth, general manager for the Landmark, resigned on January 9, 1977, so he could rejoin his private law firm. Perry Lieber, a Summa employee who once served as the Landmark's general manager, was chosen to replace Wadsworth.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark manager resigns|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11426838/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency= Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 10, 1977|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nBy May 1977, Summa was financially struggling; that month, the brokerage firm of [[Merrill Lynch|Merrill, Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith]] recommended that Summa sell its various holdings, including the Landmark. According to the brokerage firm, the Landmark \"has proven highly inefficient for hotel/casino operations and, in the opinion of Summa Corporation's management, does not warrant further investment.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hackman|first=Rick|title=To Survive, Summa Must Sell (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-04-1977-423236/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hackman|first=Rick|title=To Survive, Summa Must Sell (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-04-1977-423241/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n====Gas leak and fire====\nOn July 15, 1977, shortly after 4:00&nbsp;a.m., a water pipe burst in the tower's [[subbasement]], two floors below ground level. Two feet of water flooded the basement room and shorted out the main power panel, thereby cutting out electricity for the resort shortly before 5:00&nbsp;a.m. An [[Auxiliary generator|auxiliary power generator]] provided lighting for the resort. However, telephones, air conditioning, and four of the tower's five elevators were left non-functional because of the main power failure.<ref name=Exhaust>{{cite news|last1=Cavanaugh|first1=Wade|last2=Manning|first2=Mary|title=Generator Exhaust Found As Hotel Disaster Cause|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423270/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> [[Carbon monoxide]], [[freon]] and [[methane]], all originating from the auxiliary generator, infiltrated the tower through ventilation ducts, forcing an evacuation of the building.<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1/><ref name=Freon2/> Between 9:00&nbsp;a.m. and 11:00&nbsp;a.m., crews from [[Southwest Gas Corporation]] inspected the building with firemen and found no further traces of gas, allowing guests and employees to re-enter the building.<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1/><ref name=Freon2/>\n\nA second evacuation was ordered at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. after another power failure, which rendered the elevators inoperable once again. During the outage, 21 table games remained open with the use of [[emergency light]]s, while a bar gave away free drinks. Power was restored at 6:45&nbsp;p.m.,<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1/><ref name=Freon2/> although telephones remained inoperable. Guests were given the option to stay at one of Summa's other hotel properties.<ref name=Exhaust/> Despite the incident, hotel executives stated that the resort maintained 95-percent occupancy.<ref name=Freon2/> An investigation into the cause of the gas leaks could not begin that day due to the presence of fumes in the basement.<ref name=Probe/>\n\nDuring the incident, a news reporter and a cameraman for the local [[KLAS-TV]] news channel \u2013 also owned by Summa \u2013 were beaten and forced out of the hotel lobby by Landmark guards who were armed with clubs and flashlights. Damaged in the altercation was the recording unit for a $37,000 camera owned by KLAS. Other local news crews were allowed to stay at the property to cover the incident. Orders to remove KLAS were given to the guards by hotel management, which had been irritated by recent KLAS news stories that related to Summa's properties, including a story stating that negotiations were underway to sell the Landmark to an Arabian investor.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Newsmen Beaten by Landmark Guards|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423270/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|agency=United Press International|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=News Crew Claims They Were Beaten At Landmark Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459787/the_daily_herald/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency=United Press International|work=[[Daily Herald (Utah)|Daily Herald]]|date=July 17, 1977|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nA total of 138 people were hospitalized after inhaling the poisonous gases;<ref name=Defect/><ref>{{cite news|last=Spigelmyer|first=Sharon|title=Heavy Carbon Monoxide In Hotel Guests (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423264/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977 |via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Spigelmyer|first=Sharon|title=Heavy Carbon Monoxide In Hotel Guests (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423267/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977 |via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Spigelmyer|first=Sharon|title=Heavy Carbon Monoxide In Hotel Guests (page three)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-16-1977-423268/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 16, 1977 |via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> they were treated at four local hospitals.<ref name=Probe/> Among the hospitalized were nearly 100 hotel guests, and several firemen and ambulance drivers; most of the patients were released from the hospitals within three days of the incident.<ref name=Probe/> A 55-year-old man was the sole casualty in the incident.<ref name=Exhaust/><ref name=Freon1>{{cite news|title=In Landmark Disaster: Freon, Methane Filtered Through Hotel (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-17-1977-423274/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 17, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Freon2>{{cite news|title=In Landmark Disaster: Freon, Methane Filtered Through Hotel (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-17-1977-423282/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 17, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> An investigation into the cause of the gas leaks concluded on July 19, 1977, and found that a defective exhaust line on one of the emergency generators was responsible. The line had been installed during the hotel's construction. John Pisciotta, director of the Clark County Building Department, did not believe that he or anyone else would be able to determine how the line became damaged. Summa brought in the company which installed the system to have it repaired.<ref name=Probe>{{cite news|title=Hotel Poisoning Probe Scheduled|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-19-1977-423287/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 19, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Defect>{{cite news|title=Exhaust Line Defect Cause of Hotel Gas|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-jul-21-1977-423302/|accessdate=December 2, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=July 21, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 1977, at 3:44&nbsp;p.m., a [[two-alarm fire]] was reported in a hotel room on the 22nd floor, after a bartender in the 27th floor lounge smelled smoke. The entire room had caught on fire from a cigarette. The fire was extinguished with help from 45 firefighters, who put it out within five minutes of their arrival. However, the fire led to heavy smoke infiltrating the entire hotel and ground-floor through elevator shafts. The entire hotel was evacuated, and hundreds of guests and employees were allowed to return inside at approximately 5:15&nbsp;p.m., after smoke had been cleared from the resort's interior. The 22nd through 27th floors had moderate smoke damage. Five hotel guests were treated for [[smoke inhalation]], but none required hospitalization.<ref>{{cite news|last=Adler|first=Jeff|title=Tower Fire Clears Out Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-24-1977-423410/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 24, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cavanaugh|first=Wade|title=Guests Doubt LV Welcome After Blaze In Landmark|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-24-1977-423415/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 24, 1977}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel Fire Caused By Cigarette|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-25-1977-423420/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 25, 1977}}</ref>\n\n====Prospective buyers====\nIn late September 1977, Summa began negotiations with a group of Chicago investors that was interested in purchasing the Landmark,<ref name=Offered12m/><ref name=Offered12m2/> which had approximately 1,200 employees at the time.<ref name=Ohio/> The group \u2013 consisting of physicians, lawyers, and a Las Vegas art dealer \u2013 operated several fast-food restaurants and medical buildings in the [[midwestern United States]],<ref name=Offered12m/><ref name=Offered12m2/> and was led by attorney Myron Minuskin.<ref name=Attorney/>\n\nIn October 1977, Summa was in negotiations to sell the Landmark for $12 million to Nick Lardakis, a tavern owner who lived in [[Akron, Ohio]]. Simultaneously, Summa was also holding discussions with the Scott Corporation \u2013 a group of [[downtown Las Vegas]] entrepreneurs led by Frank Scott \u2013 which wanted to purchase the resort at a price of nearly $10 million.<ref name=Ohio>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Ohio Man Negotiating To Buy Landmark Hotel|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-12-1977-420853/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 12, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=GamingFigures>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=LV Gaming Figures Seen As Landmark Buyers|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-15-1977-423342/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 15, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Lardakis' acquisition of the Landmark was rejected that month as he was unable to raise the necessary funds to make the purchase;<ref name=Offered12m/> according to Summa, Lardakis' terms were \"unrealistic.\"<ref name=NoDecision/>\n\nOn October 17, 1977, the Chicago group offered $11 million in cash for the Landmark, but the group was rejected by Summa, which sought $12 million for the resort. The group made a $12 million cash offer the following morning. However, Summa's board of directors favored the $10 million offer by Scott Corporation, which had no down payment and included a 20-year payout period, while the Chicago group was opposed to a long-term mortgage arrangement with Summa. The Chicago group noted that Summa officials repeatedly declined to let the group examine the Landmark's 1973 property appraisal.<ref name=Offered12m>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=$12 Million Offered For Landmark (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-19-1977-420849/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 19, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Offered12m2>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=$12 Million Offered For Landmark (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-19-1977-423366/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 19, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Other offers came from Las Vegas heiress JoAnn Seigal and Beverly Hills management consultant Charles Fink, both of whom offered $12 million for the resort. Seigal also complained that Summa would not provide her with a property appraisal to base her negotiations.<ref name=NoDecision2/>\n\nOn October 19, 1977, the Beverly Hills-based Acro Management Consultants made a $16 million cash offer for the Landmark, the highest of five bids that had thus far been offered for the resort. Summa spokesman Fred Lewis said that Acro's bid was considered to be \"more of an inquiry\" than a serious offer,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Summa Gets $16 Mil. Cash Offer For Hotel|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-21-1977-423396/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 21, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> a belief that was later disputed by Acro vice president Leonard Gale, who also said, \"We realize the Landmark is the biggest lemon in Las Vegas. But we have a program that would be sensational and we know we could turn the place around.\"<ref name=Retains2/> On the day that Acro's offer was made, Summa announced that no decision had been made on a sale of the Landmark, reportedly due to disagreements within the company. William Lummis, a cousin of Hughes, had been named chairman of the Summa board earlier in the year. Lummis wanted to sell all of Summa's non-profitable properties, while [[chief operating officer]] [[Frank William Gay]], citing the purported desires of Hughes, wanted to expand and modernize such properties.<ref name=NoDecision>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Landmark Sale: No Decision Yet (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-20-1977-423386/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 20, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=NoDecision2>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Landmark Sale: No Decision Yet (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-20-1977-423379/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 20, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The Landmark was considered to be the weakest of Summa's six gaming and hotel properties in Nevada, as it had never made a profit up to that time.<ref name=Sale-Fails>{{cite news |title=Landmark sale fails |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681051/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=October 20, 1977 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Chicago group subsequently offered to pay all Landmark bills and debts during the final 60 days of a 90-day escrow period.<ref name=Attorney>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Attorney Bids for Resort|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-03-1977-423431/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 3, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nSumma officials held a meeting on November 3, 1977, but the company made no decision on selling the Landmark, which lost an average of $500,000 per month. By that time, the Scott Corporation stated that it would likely withdraw its offer to purchase the Landmark because of inability to obtain long-term financing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Summa Retains Ownership of Landmark (page one)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-04-1977-423440/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref name=Retains2>{{cite news|last=Hyman|first=Harold|title=Summa Retains Ownership of Landmark (page two)|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-04-1977-423446/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 4, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hotel Deal Pends|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-nov-06-1977-423450/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=November 6, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> In December 1977, it was stated that if the Landmark remained a Summa property, then the company would add six outdoor tennis courts to the resort, as well as 10 indoor courts that would be usable by all Summa hotel guests in the Las Vegas area.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dunne|first=Irene|title=Tennis Talk|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-dec-28-1977-423454/|accessdate=December 3, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=December 28, 1977|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1978, Summa announced that the Landmark would be sold to the Scott Corporation, with the sale price reportedly ranging between $10 million and $12 million. Up to that time, the resort had reportedly lost $15 million since its opening, despite numerous attempts to increase business. Experts believed that the Landmark suffered financially as a result of its low room-count (486 guest rooms at the time) and its location across the street from the Las Vegas Hilton (formerly the International), which was the world's largest hotel at the time. Frank Scott owned downtown Las Vegas' [[Union Plaza Hotel]], which had become one of the city's most successful casinos, and he said the same management principles used at the Union Plaza would be applied to the Landmark.<ref name=SellsFamed/>\n\n{{Quote\n|text=Gambling is a business\u2014a very unique business\u2014and sound policies applied and followed will result in a successful operation. We face a strong challenge in making the Landmark one of the truly fine casino-hotel operations in Las Vegas, and we look forward to accomplishing this goal.\n|author=Frank Scott, 1978<ref name=SellsFamed/>|\n}}\n\nScott intended to change the name of the resort, with \"The Plaza Tower\" as the favorite among several names under consideration at that time. Scott planned to take over operations once the sale received approval from Summa, county and state gaming officials, and courts that were handling Hughes' estate.<ref name=SellsFamed>{{cite news|title=Summa Corp. sells famed Landmark Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11436720/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency= Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=January 13, 1978|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Because higher offers were subsequently made for the Landmark, the Scott Corporation's offer was rejected by a judge who was monitoring the Hughes estate.<ref name=Gambling/><ref name=Direct/>\n\n====Wolfram/Tickel ownership====\nA group of midwestern investors \u2013 led by Lou Tickel and Zula Wolfram,<ref name=Possible/><ref>{{cite news |title=Summa says it made no promises in Landmark sale |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681248/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=November 11, 1986 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> and including Gary Yelverton<ref name=Set-Reopen/> \u2013 purchased the Landmark from Summa Corporation in February 1978,<ref name=Possible/> at a cost of $12.5 million.<ref name=BetterEver/> The purchase was financed using money that Wolfram's husband, Ed Wolfram, [[Embezzlement|embezzled]] from his brokerage firm, [[Bell & Beckwith]].<ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite news |title=Indictment charges money siphoned from brokerage used to buy casino |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681166/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=April 6, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Faye Todd, the Landmark's Entertainment Director and a Corporate Executive Assistant, primarily oversaw the Landmark's operations for the Wolframs, who lived in Ohio. The Wolframs were [[high roller]]s who frequently stayed at the Desert Inn resort when visiting Las Vegas. Todd met the Wolframs while working for the Desert Inn as Special Events Coordinator, and she became close friends with Zula Wolfram, who had been planning to purchase a Las Vegas hotel with her husband.<ref name=Todd>{{cite web|last=White|first=Claytee D.|title=An Interview with Faye Todd|url=http://digital.library.unlv.edu/api/1/objects/ohr/2/bitstream|publisher=University of Nevada, Las Vegas|accessdate=September 28, 2017|date=1998|pages=28\u201343|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000918/http://digital.library.unlv.edu/api/1/objects/ohr/2/bitstream|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Lou Tickel, a former [[magistrate]] judge and a resident of [[Salina, Kansas]], previously owned several other hotels. The group was confident that the Landmark would overcome its financial problems, and they planned to add a 750-room hotel tower to the property within two years.<ref name=Gambling>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Salinan gambling that Vegas hotel-casino can turn a profit |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3407581/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=February 28, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Direct>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Tickel to take direct hand in hotel operation |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3408179/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=March 1, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nThe sale was completed on March 31, 1978,<ref name=ownership/><ref name=Possible/> under the new ownership of Zula Wofram, and Lou and Jo Ann Tickel.<ref name=ownership/> However, the new owners had been unable to find someone with a gaming license and sufficient funds to continue operating the casino ahead of the sale's completion. The investment group had not yet applied with the county and state for gaming and liquor licenses, and Summa Corporation declined to continue operating the casino, citing a lack of interest in the property.<ref name=Possible>{{cite news |title=Landmark closure possible |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681075/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=March 29, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Landmark's casino, which had 272 employees,<ref name=Possible/> was closed on April 1, 1978, due to the lack of gaming licenses.<ref name=Salinan/><ref name=Set-Reopen/> The owners began a search for a suitable licensed individual who could temporarily operate the casino until they could receive their own gaming license.<ref name=BetterEver>{{cite web |last= |first= |title='Business is better than ever', says Tickel of his new hotel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3431350/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=April 4, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The hotel, restaurants, and shops remained open,<ref name=Salinan>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Salinan takes over Landmark Resort |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/3429446/ |website=Salina Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=April 2, 1978 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> with 700 other employees.<ref name=BetterEver/> The casino reopened on June 2, 1978, after a one-year gaming license had been granted to Frank Modica, a Las Vegas gaming figure who would temporarily operate the casino on the owners' behalf. The casino's bingo parlor remained closed as it was undergoing renovations.<ref name=Set-Reopen>{{cite news |title=Landmark casino set to reopen |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681084/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=June 1, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1978, Tickel, Wolfram, and Yelverton were approved by the Nevada Gaming Control Board and the Nevada Gaming Commission to be licensed as the landlords of the Landmark. At the time, Ed Wolfram was listed as a financial adviser on the licensing plan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Landmark investment plans get gaming board backing |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681100/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=October 14, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Landmark investors get license approval |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681115/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |date=October 20, 1978 |accessdate=December 3, 2018|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> As of April 1979, Jesse Jackson Jr. was the Landmark hotel manager, and was the only such manager in the Las Vegas hotel industry to be black.<ref>{{cite web |title=Speaking of People: Casino Hotel Manager |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=99QDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA7#v=onepage&q&f=false |work=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]] |date=April 1979 |accessdate=April 19, 2019|publisher = Johnson Publishing Company}}</ref> Gary Baldwin, a former investigator for the Nevada Gaming Control Board, was the Landmark's general manager and casino manager as of July 1979. That month, the gaming control board recommended that Baldwin be approved in his request to receive five-percent of pretax operating profits from the Landmark.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former gaming employee gets recommendation|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422675/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 2, 2018|agency= Associated Press|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=July 12, 1979|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Tickels remained as co-owners of the Landmark until 1980,<ref name=ownership/> following Wolfram's approval to purchase their interest in the resort.<ref>{{cite web |title='Toy Let' canned |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/147718602/ |website=Reno Evening Gazette |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=December 13, 1979 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1982, architect [[Martin Stern Jr.]] was hired to design a large expansion of the Landmark.<ref name=VTAT>{{cite web|title=Dream Projects from the Past, that were Never Built|url=http://www.vegastodayandtomorrow.com/dreams2.htm#.Wc1BnXmWwpM|website=VegasTodayAndTomorrow.com|accessdate=September 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211085021/http://www.vegastodayandtomorrow.com/dreams2.htm#.Wc1BnXmWwpM|archivedate=February 11, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Stern>{{cite web|title=Guide to the Martin Stern Architectural Records|url=https://www.library.unlv.edu/speccol/ead/MS-00382_stern.pdf|publisher=University of Nevada, Las Vegas|accessdate=September 28, 2017|pages=123\u2013125|date=July 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929001038/https://www.library.unlv.edu/speccol/ead/MS-00382_stern.pdf|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Revenue for the Landmark exceeded $26 million that year,<ref name=Takeover>{{cite news|title=Control board delays proposed takeover of Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681194/reno_gazettejournal/ |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=August 18, 1983|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> although the resort lost $500,000 during the month of November 1982. Up to that time, the Landmark had lost an average of $3 million every year since its opening.<ref name=Whiz>{{cite news|last=Macy|first=Robert|title=Gaming Whiz Turns Failure Into Success|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11431233/the_palm_beach_post/|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=The Palm Beach Post|agency=Associated Press|date=December 24, 1983}}</ref>\n\nFederal investigators shut down Wolfram's firm on February 7, 1983, after they discovered $36 million of money missing in six accounts that were managed by him and his wife, ultimately leading to the discovery of his embezzlement.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=N. R.|first=Kleinfield|title=Beckwith Partner Gets 25-Year Jail Term|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/07/business/beckwith-partner-gets-25-year-jail-term.html|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=September 7, 1983|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044301/http://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/07/business/beckwith-partner-gets-25-year-jail-term.html|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Lawyer Patrick McGraw, [[trustee]] for Bell & Beckwith, was approved later that month to operate the Landmark until it could be liquidated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Special trustee approved for Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681154/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=February 18, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Walter J. Krasniewski Wednesday granted the trustee of the Bell & Beckwith brokerage authority to operate businesses assigned to him|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/02/23/US-Bankruptcy-Court-Judge-Walter-J-Krasniewski-Wednesday-granted/8976414824400/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|agency=United Press International|date=February 23, 1983|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929000732/http://www.upi.com/Archives/1983/02/23/US-Bankruptcy-Court-Judge-Walter-J-Krasniewski-Wednesday-granted/8976414824400/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> The expansion designed by Stern was cancelled,<ref name=VTAT/> and Ed Wolfram was convicted of embezzling later that year, after admitting to using money from his firm to pay for various businesses ventures, with the Landmark being the most expensive.<ref name=NYT/> Zula Wolfram, who had owed $5 million to Summa since her purchase of the Landmark, was forced to sell her majority share in the resort.<ref name=Takeover/>\n\n====Morris ownership====\nThe Landmark was entangled in a Toledo bankruptcy court in July 1983, at which point Bill Morris, a Las Vegas lawyer, began plans to purchase the resort.<ref name=Whiz/><ref>{{cite news |title=Deal in the works to purchase hotel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681276/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |date=July 21, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris, also a member of the [[Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority]] (LVCVA), had previously owned the [[Harrah's Las Vegas|Holiday Inn Center Strip hotel-casino]], as well as the [[Riverside Resort Hotel & Casino|Riverside Resort]] in nearby [[Laughlin, Nevada|Laughlin]].<ref name=Whiz/> Morris had also previously represented Plaza Tower, Inc. at the time that Hughes completed his purchase of the resort.<ref name=Climax1/> Morris intended to eventually expand the resort to 1,100 hotel rooms.<ref>{{cite news |title=Attorney gets state OK to buy Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681211/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=United Press International |date=August 26, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nYelverton and his wife stated that they had been sold a five-percent interest in the Landmark in 1979, but that the document mistakenly was never filed with the county recorder's office. In August 1983, the Yelvertons filed a state suit to prevent the sale to Morris, stating that they would not be compensated for their interest if the sale proceeded. At the time, Gary Yelverton was the Landmark's casino manager.<ref>{{cite news |title=Part owner sues to prevent sale |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-VgdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CFgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5386%2C3038287 |work=[[The Bryan Times]] |date=August 3, 1983 |accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> Later in the month, the Nevada Gaming Control Board delayed approval of Morris' purchase of the resort until his offer could be updated to include a $5 million payment for Summa \u2013 as part of his $18.4 million offer for the resort \u2013 to cover what Zula Wolfram owed to the company.<ref name=Takeover/> Morris purchased the Landmark for $18.7 million,<ref name=Borders/> and took over ownership on October 30, 1983.<ref name=Facelift/> The struggling resort had a profitable month in November 1983 under its new management.<ref name=Whiz/><ref>{{cite web|title=Patrick A. McGraw, Trustee, Plaintiff, v. Gary Yelverton, et al., Defendants|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/BR/87/476/2020266/|website=Law.Justia.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=May 26, 1988|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717033225/http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/BR/87/476/2020266/|archivedate=July 17, 2017}}</ref> Morris worked 18 hours a day to ensure the Landmark's success.<ref name=Whiz/>\n\n{{Quote\n|text=The Landmark's never really been given a fair chance. First, there has never been on-hands management on a day-in, day-out basis. Second, the operators have all tried to make the property do something it was not meant to do. They tried to compete with superstar productions, and a lot of money was lost in that competition. The property is ideally situated to serve the convention authority, and our operational thrust will be in that direction.\n|author=Bill Morris, 1983<ref name=Whiz/>|\n}}\n\nMorris spent nearly $3.5 million on [[#Features|a renovation of the Landmark]],<ref name=Morris-bio>{{cite news|title=William and Vivienne Morris|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11431032/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=October 18, 1984|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> which was underway in early December 1983. The resort remained open during renovations. At the time, the casino offered its Single-Deck Blackjack Tournament, with a $57 entry fee. Casino manager Ron Nadeau said \"we think this is the type of play that will catch on here. It is priced in a range that anyone can afford to join the action.\"<ref name=Facelift>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel is receiving a facelift|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11431095/arizona_republic/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=December 4, 1983|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris said that the Landmark would compete against rivals with its \"budget prices and good service.\"<ref name=Facelift/> By the end of 1983, Morris intended to capitalize on the resort's location with a planned expansion that would feature three 15-story towers with 1,500 hotel rooms, accompanied by a large domed family entertainment center. The expansion was to be built west of the Landmark on {{convert|11|acre|abbr=on}} of vacant land that Morris had purchased along with the resort.<ref name=Whiz/> The expansion did not occur, and the Landmark struggled throughout the 1980s.<ref name=Vegas7/>\n\nIn May 1985, the casino offered the \"More Than $100,000 Craps Tournament\".<ref>{{cite news|title=More Than $100,000 Craps Tournament|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422646/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=April 21, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> By June 1985,<ref>{{cite news|title=Soccer team in jeopardy|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459878/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=June 29, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris was negotiating a $28 million loan to pay for improvements and fire safety updates for the resort, which had failed to comply with fire safety standards; Clark County officials considered taking action against the resort because of its failed compliance. On July 29, 1985, the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS) filed a $2.1 [[lien]] against the property, because of Morris' failure to pay [[Withholding tax|withholding]] and [[payroll tax]]es for the resort's employees for the previous six months. Two days after the lien was filed, the Landmark filed for [[Chapter 11]] bankruptcy to prevent the IRS from seizing assets such as casino cage money. The resort remained open despite the bankruptcy filing, and the casino had enough money to remain operational. The Landmark had debts totaling $30.6 million, while it had $30.6 million in assets.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel seeks Chapter 11 protection|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459901/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|agency=Associated Press|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=August 1, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris blamed the bankruptcy on McGraw, alleging that he derailed a $28.8 million refinancing of the Landmark 24 hours prior to the finalization of the loan. Morris said operations would continue as normal despite the bankruptcy filing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bankruptcy forced, says casino owner |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11681229/reno_gazettejournal/ |work=Reno Gazette-Journal |date=August 2, 1985 |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1986, Nevada National Bank requested that the bankruptcy be converted to a liquidation proceeding to pay off creditors, stating that the Landmark's bankruptcy reorganization plan could not succeed.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Landmark hearing put off |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/148137552/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=January 23, 1986 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> During the same month, Morris said he would have to cancel his reorganization plan and lay off 700 to 800 Landmark employees if a bankruptcy court did not allow the resort to abandon its union labor contracts. Part of Morris' reorganization plan involved cutting employee wages by 15 percent, including his own yearly salary of $145,000. The pay cut would give the Landmark an additional $6,500 per month, which would allow the resort to make its mortgage payments. Morris hoped to increase the hotel's room count after the resort's eventual emergence from bankruptcy, with additional financing from a national franchise hotel chain. He hoped that the Landmark would be out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy by March 1, 1986,<ref name=Borders>{{cite news|last=Borders|first=Myram|title=Landmark Hotel's Morris seeking to abandon union labor contracts|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459748/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=January 24, 1986|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> although it would ultimately remain in bankruptcy for the rest of its operation.<ref name=Orders/>\n\nIn January 1987, a small fire broke out in the resort's showroom, located next to the casino. Five employees were evacuated, and there were no injuries. Customers in the casino were unaware of the fire, which was quickly extinguished by the local fire department. The fire was determined to have likely been caused by an [[arsonist]].<ref name=Arson>{{cite news|title=Vegas Hotel Fire was arson|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423832/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=January 14, 1987|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fires may have been set by arsonist|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423789/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=January 15, 1987|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In July 1987, the Landmark began offering poker tournaments in its Nightcap Lounge each weekday night. To help bring in customers, two cash drawings were held during each tournament.<ref>{{cite news|title= Poker tourneys on weekdays at Landmark Hotel|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422615/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 26, 1987|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nBy April 1989, Morris and [[Drexel Burnham Lambert]] had begun a search for a new owner to take over the Landmark.<ref>{{cite web |last=Krane |first=Elliot S. |title=Landmark Hires Drexel to Find Buyer |url=https://www.pressofatlanticcity.com/site_services/news_archives/ |website=The Press of Atlantic City |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=April 9, 1989 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In November 1989, a U.S. bankruptcy court judge gave Morris until January 2, 1990 to find a buyer or refinancing. Otherwise, the Landmark would be liquidated to pay off creditors, in accordance with a court order.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Court moves closer to forcing Vegas hotel-casino sale |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=UPI NewsTrack |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=November 20, 1989 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref> On January 2, 1990, the Landmark was ordered into [[Chapter 7 bankruptcy]] after a judge ruled that the creditors would not be able to receive compensation under the reorganization plan.<ref name=Orders>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Judge orders Chapter 7 for Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/147591278/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=January 3, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Between $43 million and $46 million was owed to various creditors. Morris' gaming license expired that month after the resort failed to pay $500,000 in taxes and penalties. Richard Davis, a Las Vegas real estate executive and owner of a funeral home, was appointed by the bankruptcy court that month to temporarily operate the resort. On February 21, 1990, the Nevada Gaming Commission extended the gaming license and allowed the resort to stay open for at least two additional weeks while its financial problems were analyzed by state experts. At that time, the hotel had $562,000 in cash, including $175,000 in revenue that had accumulated in the prior six weeks.<ref name=Bankrupt>{{cite web|last=Borders|first=Myram|title=Bankrupt Landmark hotel-casino gets state reprieve|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/02/22/Bankrupt-Landmark-hotel-casino-gets-state-reprieve-By-MYRAM-BORDERS/2479635662800/|publisher=UPI|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=February 22, 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929045142/http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/02/22/Bankrupt-Landmark-hotel-casino-gets-state-reprieve-By-MYRAM-BORDERS/2479635662800/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy June 1990, the Landmark was still struggling,<ref name=WorldsLargest/> although the introduction of various casino programs helped improve revenue. Later that month, a U.S. bankruptcy court judge approved a request for the Landmark to be sold in a public auction scheduled for August 6, 1990. The request was made by Davis, who cited numerous failed attempts to sell the resort. More than 200 prospective buyers had inquired about the Landmark, but only five to ten of them were considered as having serious interest in the resort.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Bankruptcy judge orders Landmark sale |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149708447/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=June 20, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In July 1990, two Denver businessmen, David M. Droubay and Martin Heckmaster, offered $35.5 million to purchase the bankrupt resort.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=2 Denver businessmen bid for Las Vegas hotel |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=The Denver Post |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=July 6, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=$35.5 million offer accepted for Landmark sale |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149691709/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=July 3, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=$35.5 million offer accepted for Landmark sale (page 2 of 2)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149691523/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=July 3, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Morris was dissatisfied with the offer, stating that the property had been appraised as high as $70 million.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Landmark Hotel owner calls offer 'low ball' |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/149700964/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=July 4, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Ultimately, Droubay and Heckmaster's plan to purchase the Landmark did not come together.<ref name=Spectrum/>\n\n===Closure (1990\u201395)===\nOn August 6, 1990, the bankruptcy hearing failed to attract a buyer for the Landmark. [[Ralph Engelstad]] and [[Charles Frias]], who both held substantial interest in the resort, had made $100,000 deposits which allowed them to bid at the hearing, but they did not do so and left the hearing without commenting. At the request of Davis' attorney, a U.S. bankruptcy judge granted permission to close the Landmark. Gaming operations began shutting down that afternoon, within an hour of the failed hearing. Slot machine and hotel operations were scheduled to shut down later in the week.<ref name=Spectrum>{{cite web |title=Landmark Hotel begins shutting down tables |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423265/the_daily_spectrum/ |website=The Daily Spectrum |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=August 7, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> With 498 rooms at the time,<ref name=Bankrupt/> the Landmark was unable to compete with new megaresorts, and was fully closed on August 8, 1990.<ref name=lvs1/>\n\nMorris, upset about the failed auction, said, \"Sometimes it comes down to good luck and bad luck. I had nothing but bad luck. Someone is going to come in and run the Landmark and look like a genius.\" Forrest Woodward, who managed the casino for Davis, said, \"This is just an obsolete gaming property that no one's interested in, considering the debt,\" which included $48 million; a portion of that was $10 million in unsecured claims. Davis' attorney predicted the Landmark would be closed for 100 days or more while creditors pursued a foreclosure sale.<ref name=Spectrum/> A week after the closure, Davis received permission from the U.S. bankruptcy court to abandon the property as trustee, due to the cost of maintaining security at the closed resort. Davis' attorney said it would cost between $60,000 and $200,000 each month to maintain the property. Creditors would be left to pay bills relating to the property until a foreclosure sale could take place.<ref>{{cite web |title=Landmark Hotel in court |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423198/reno_gazettejournal/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Creditors to Pick Up Tab |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=The Fresno Bee |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=August 19, 1990 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref> In December 1990, the property was purchased through a foreclosure sale by [[Lloyds Bank]] of London for $20 million. Lloyds Bank made the purchase in order to protect a $25 million loan it had made to Morris in 1988.<ref name=BankBuys>{{cite web |title=Bank buys Landmark Hotel |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11423161/reno_gazettejournal/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=May 13, 2019 |date=December 6, 1990 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=London bank buys shuttered Las Vegas hotel-casino|url=http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/12/07/London-bank-buys-shuttered-Las-Vegas-hotel-casino/2976660546000/|publisher=UPI|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=December 7, 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929045100/http://www.upi.com/Archives/1990/12/07/London-bank-buys-shuttered-Las-Vegas-hotel-casino/2976660546000/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> By March 1993, the Landmark's contents had been liquidated through a sale conducted by National Content Liquidators.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Thousands show for Dunes closeout |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/152710747/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |date=March 19, 1993 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McNair |first=James |title=Company strips hotels 'down to walls' for profits |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/Dec/01/bz/bz30a.html |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |work=The Cincinnati Enquirer |date=December 1, 2002}}</ref>\n\nBy July 1993, representatives of Lloyds Bank had approached the LVCVA about the possibility of purchasing the Landmark. LVCVA was interested in the proposal, with plans to use the Landmark's 21-acre property either for a parking lot or expansion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas Convention Authority wants to buy closed Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874976/reno_gazettejournal/|date=July 3, 1993|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> LVCVA purchased the Landmark in September 1993,<ref name=ownership/> at a cost of $15.1 million.<ref name=Oakland>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Oakland Firm Gets Landmark-Demolition Job |url=https://nl.newsbank.com |website=San Jose Mercury News |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=October 11, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=NewsLibrary}}</ref><ref name=Elko/> During 1994, board members of LVCVA debated on whether to restore the Landmark or demolish it.<ref name=\"lvs1\"/> It was ultimately decided that the Landmark would be demolished, after only three LVCVA board members voted to save the building. Among those voting in support was [[Lorraine Hunt]], who later said that the Landmark \"was iconic and part of the history of Las Vegas. Had they kept it, it could have been the office for the Las Vegas Convention and Visitors Authority.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Norm|title=Hunt Bono recalls Landmark opening, implosion|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/opinion/columns-blogs/norm-clarke/hunt-bono-recalls-landmark-opening-implosion|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=7 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105223419/http://www.reviewjournal.com/opinion/columns-blogs/norm-clarke/hunt-bono-recalls-landmark-opening-implosion|archivedate=5 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Demolition====\nLVCVA paid $800,000 for [[asbestos]] removal in the tower. Central Environmental Inc. was hired to remove the asbestos, while AB-Haz Environmental, Inc. was the asbestos removal consultant.<ref name=PutOff/> In mid-1994, AB-Haz Environmental began removing asbestos insulation from the Landmark.<ref name=April97/><ref name=May99/> The removal, scheduled for completion in August 1994, took nearly six months.<ref name=PutOff/> In October 1994, it was announced that the Landmark would be demolished the following month to make way for a 21-acre parking lot,<ref>{{cite news|title=Failed Landmark to be razed in Nov.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875039/reno_gazettejournal/|date=October 4, 1994|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> to be used by the Las Vegas Convention Center.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> Demolition of the tower was delayed until December 1994, before being delayed again to January 1995, to allow for the removal of additional asbestos. By that time, the Clark County Health District had proposed penalties against the asbestos companies.<ref name=PutOff>{{cite news|title=Demolition put off for closed Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875053/reno_gazettejournal/|date=November 29, 1994|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\nBy February 1995, AB-Haz had twice declared the Landmark to be asbestos-free and safe for demolition, although Clark County officials discovered that some hotel floors still contained 90 percent of the asbestos. Up to that time, LVCVA had already paid a total of $1 million to the asbestos companies to have the asbestos removed from the hotel and an adjacent apartment complex, allowing for their demolition. The Clark County Air Pollution Control Division recommended a $450,000 fine against AB-Haz for failure to remove the asbestos, while LVCVA would have to spend an additional $1 million for further asbestos removal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Asbestos removal to cost $1 million|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875009/reno_gazettejournal/|date=February 28, 1995|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> AB-Haz was ultimately cited for violating air emission standards during the asbestos removal, and signed a settlement in which the company agreed to pay an $18,000 fine.<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Indictments handed down as asbestos not removed |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/153426979/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=October 17, 1996 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=April97>{{cite news|title=Company challenges Landmark indictment|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/apr/03/company-challenges-landmark-indictment/|accessdate=May 11, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=April 3, 1997|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808000725/https://lasvegassun.com/news/1997/apr/03/company-challenges-landmark-indictment/|archivedate=August 8, 2017}}</ref><ref name=May99>{{cite news|title=Asbestos-removal firms facing record fines|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/may/28/asbestos-removal-firms-facing-record-fines/|accessdate=May 11, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 28, 1999|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808000100/https://lasvegassun.com/news/1999/may/28/asbestos-removal-firms-facing-record-fines/|archivedate=August 8, 2017}}</ref> Central Environmental was removing asbestos from the tower as of August 1995. Because of previous delays, officials for LVCVA had given up on setting a demolition date until all the asbestos was removed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Asbestos-removal delays demolition|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11875071/reno_gazettejournal/|date=August 15, 1995|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|accessdate=October 25, 2017|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In October 1995, LVCVA paid Iconco Inc. $740,000 to remove remaining asbestos from the resort, hoping to have it demolished in time for [[Conexpo-Con/Agg|ConExpo]] to be held on the property's new parking lot in March 1996.<ref name=Oakland/>\n\n[[Controlled Demolition, Inc.]] (CDI) was hired to [[Building implosion|implode]] the tower.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\" /><ref name=Elko>{{cite web |title=Landmark Hotel tower in Las Vegas will be imploded |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/477291637/ |website=Elko Daily Free Press |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=November 4, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> No [[blueprint]]s could be found for the tower, which CDI president Mark Loizeaux considered unusual. Demolition crews discovered secret stairwells in the tower, and Loizeaux said, \"We have learned everything as we have gone in. It was a very strange structure, very unique.\"<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/><ref name=Implode>{{cite news|title=Preparations made to implode Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874692/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=Reno Gazette-Journal|date=November 7, 1995|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> A week before the Landmark tower was demolished, crews removed the remaining asbestos from the low-rise structures and subsequently tore them down. Crews then spent the final days of demolition by drilling in the tower to weaken and prepare it ahead of its planned implosion. Less than 100 pounds of dynamite was placed in certain locations throughout the tower's first four floors.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/>\n\n[[File:Landmark sign, Las Vegas (8370148248).jpg|thumb|right|A restored Landmark sign, located on the property of the former resort (2013)]]\nAt 5:37&nbsp;a.m. on November 7, 1995, the Landmark tower was demolished through implosion.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\" /><ref name=CT>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Las Vegas Landmark imploded |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/167723530/ |website=Chicago Tribune |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=November 7, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |title=Reduced to rubble |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/153900120/ |website=Reno Gazette-Journal |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=November 8, 1995 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Mag>{{cite web |url=http://vegasmagazine.com/living/articles/in-depth-bringing-down-the-harmon |title=In Depth: Bringing Down the Harmon |publisher=Vegas Magazine |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223073857/http://vegasmagazine.com/living/articles/in-depth-bringing-down-the-harmon |archivedate=2014-12-23 }}</ref> An estimated 7,000 people arrived to witness the implosion.<ref name=CT/> Upon detonation, the tower's northwest half was brought down, followed by the second half, which caved in on itself, followed by a black cloud of dust ascending 150 feet into the air. Most of the material from the demolished structure was to be recycled and used in other construction projects.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> The 31-story tower was the tallest reinforced concrete building ever demolished in North America, and the second tallest building in the world to be demolished.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/><ref name=Good/> Demolition and related expenses cost $3 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Thompson |first=Gary |title=LVCVA to appeal $9 million land decision |url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/apr/24/lvcva-to-appeal-9-million-land-decision/ |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |work=Las Vegas Sun |date=April 24, 1996}}</ref> [[Frank Wright (historian)|Frank Wright]], curator of the [[Nevada State Museum, Las Vegas|Nevada State Museum and Historical Society]], said \"I kind of hate to see it come down,\" stating that the Landmark tower still represented what the then-upcoming [[Stratosphere Las Vegas|Stratosphere tower]] represented: \"the biggest and the tallest.\"<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/> The property was to become occupied by 2,200 parking spaces, expected to be ready by March 1996.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/>\n\nOne of the Landmark's ground-level signs, with gold and blue cursive neon lettering, was restored by the [[Neon Museum]] and installed at the parking lot.<ref name=Vegas7/> As of 2017, the property contains 2,948 parking spaces for the Las Vegas Convention Center.<ref>{{cite web|title=LVCC Gold Lot - Parking Lot|url=http://en.parkopedia.com/parking/lot/lvcc_gold_lot/89109/las_vegas/?arriving=201611050000&leaving=201611050200|website=Parkopedia.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref> In 2019, work was underway on an expansion of the convention center. It will be built on the former sites of the Landmark and the nearby [[Riviera (hotel and casino)|Riviera]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gillan |first=Jeff |title=Billion dollar Las Vegas Convention Center expansion 45 percent complete |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/billion-dollar-las-vegas-convention-center-expansion-45-percent-complete |accessdate=September 15, 2019 |work=KSNV |date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Space Needle from Elliott Bay 2.jpg|thumb|right|The Landmark's design was inspired by Seattle's Space Needle tower]]\nThe Landmark tower was designed by architects Gerald Moffitt and Ed Hendricks.<ref name=Thoughts/><ref name=LivesUp/><ref name=Sidewalk>{{cite news|last=Covey|first=Hilda|title=Sidewalk Superintendent|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-oct-03-1966-422012/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=October 3, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> The uniquely designed Landmark tower was the first of its kind to be built in Nevada;<ref name=The-News/> its design was inspired by the [[Space Needle]] tower located in [[Seattle]], Washington.<ref name=AP-1965/> When construction stopped in 1962, the project consisted of {{convert|127614|sqft|abbr=on}} of floor space, and included two basements that were 30 feet deep. The tower's height measured 297 feet, while its diameter measured 60 feet. The tower's dome measured 141 feet in diameter.<ref name=Scherer/> In 1966 \u2013 the year that construction resumed \u2013 architects George Tate and Thomas Dobrusky were hired to design new portions of the resort, including the ground-floor casino.<ref name=Stalled/><ref name=Sidewalk/>\n\n===Height===\nThe Landmark tower was billed as having 31 floors, although it skipped floors 13 and 28.<ref name=Layout>{{cite web|title=Layout of the Landmark|url=https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/copy-of-specs|website=Landmark Memorial|accessdate=December 14, 2017}}</ref> The Landmark tower was the tallest building in the state from 1962 to 1969.<ref name=Sep1962/><ref name=Suit1963/><ref name=Hughes-Pay/><ref name=NewSkyline/> In 1967,<ref>{{cite web|title=1967: Pieces of the \"L\" sign are airlifted into place|url=https://www.landmarkhotelmemorial.com/gallery?lightbox=image_css|website=Landmark Hotel Memorial|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> a revolving letter \"L\" neon sign was installed at the top of the tower.<ref name=SeenCalif>{{cite news|title=Can be seen from California on a clear day: Scherer tells about Landmark Tower|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|accessdate=September 28, 2017|work=Redlands Daily Facts|date=October 24, 1968|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929092236/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422529/redlands_daily_facts/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Excluding its rooftop sign, the tower stood {{convert|297|ft|m}},<ref name=Scherer/><ref name=OnAgain>{{cite news|last=Barrows|first=Jim|title=Landmark Tower: On Again-Off Again|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-mar-10-1968-420780/|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=March 10, 1968|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> seven feet taller than the [[The Mint Las Vegas|Mint hotel]] in downtown Las Vegas.<ref name=May18-66/><ref name=TalkProgress/>\n\nConflicting numbers have been given for the tower's total height. According to Scherer, the sign measured {{convert|40|ft|m}}, and the tower measured {{convert|328|ft|m}}, including the sign.<ref name=SeenCalif/> At the time of opening, the Landmark tower was billed as having a height of {{convert|346|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hughes Buys Another Vegas Resort|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598951/the_press_democrat/|accessdate=June 11, 2017|work=United Press International|date=June 26, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013528/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598951/the_press_democrat/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=To-Open/><ref name=NewSkyline/> By that time, the new 30-story International Hotel had become the tallest building in the state at {{convert|375|ft|m}}.<ref name=NewSkyline/><ref>{{cite web|title=Las Vegas Hilton|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/122181/las-vegas-hilton-las-vegas-nv-usa|accessdate=October 25, 2017|publisher=[[Emporis]]}}</ref> When it was demolished, the tower reportedly stood {{convert|356|ft|m}}.<ref name=Implode/><ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\"/><ref name=Good>{{cite news|title=The Good Guys|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/94163556/|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=Herald and Review|date=April 28, 1996|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> According to [[Emporis]], the tower stood {{convert|331.50|ft|m}} from the ground to its roof, while the tip raised the height to a total of {{convert|364|ft|m}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Landmark|url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/102790/landmark-las-vegas-nv-usa|accessdate=October 25, 2017|publisher=Emporis}}</ref>\n\n===Features===\nWhen it opened, the Landmark had a total of 400 [[slot machine]]s.<ref name=Finishing/> The ground-floor casino was {{convert|14000|sqft|abbr=on}}, while a second casino, consisting of {{convert|3000|sqft|abbr=on}}, was located in the dome on the 29th floor; it was the first high-rise casino in the state.<ref name=NewSkyline/> At the time of opening, the ground-floor casino featured red and black colors, while the upper casino used orange coloring and wood.<ref name=Key1/> The hotel contained 476 rooms and 27 suites for a total of 503, a small number in comparison to other Las Vegas resorts, which commonly had 1,000 rooms.<ref name=Key2/> The tower included 157 hotel rooms,<ref name=Exhaust/> while the remaining units were located on ground level.<ref name=SeenCalif/> The rooms in the tower used a floorplan shaped like pie slices.<ref name=CT/> By 1977, the room count had increased to 524,<ref name=Ohio/> before ultimately being lowered to 498 at the time of its closure in 1990.<ref name=Bankrupt/>\n\nThe Landmark's interior designer was Las Vegas resident Leonard Edward England,<ref name=Trial/><ref name=Key2/> who designed the ground floor to include a colorful and primitive [[Incan Empire|Incan]] theme, which gradually changed to a [[Space Age]] theme on subsequent floors.<ref name=Apr6-68/> The interior included $200,000 light fixtures,<ref name=Key2>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=John L.|title=$20 Million Key Opens Hughes' 6th Vegas Hotel (page two)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599165/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=July 3, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810013625/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599165/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> glowing, red-colored Incan masks, and a wall sculpture made of [[Burnishing (metal)|burnished metal]] that represented a launch from [[Cape Canaveral|Cape Kennedy]]. The interior also included 65 tons of black and white polished marble,<ref name=NewSkyline>{{cite news|title=New skyline for Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598996/nevada_state_journal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=United Press International|date=July 1, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810011939/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11598996/nevada_state_journal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name=Apr6-68/> as well as carved [[mahogany]] woodwork from Mexico.<ref name=Apr6-68/> In addition, the interior featured murals depicting the eight [[Wonders of the World]], which included the Landmark tower.<ref name=Pearlman/> The interior, including the casino, was considered to be spacious.<ref name=Pearlman/><ref name=Apr6-68/>\n\nAfter Hughes agreed to purchase the resort, he had an island built in the middle of the hotel's 240-foot swimming pool,<ref name=Finishing>{{cite news|title=Finishing touches made for two Vegas hotel openings|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599016/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 10, 2017|work=Associated Press|date=July 1, 1969|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810012523/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11599016/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=August 10, 2017}}</ref> which cost $200,000<ref name=Hoopla/> and was the longest in the world.<ref name=Time>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas: The Game Is Illusion|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,900980,00.html|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Time|date=July 11, 1969|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The Landmark's pool included waterfalls and three carpeted bridges leading to its center island, which featured palm trees.<ref name=Key2/> For the hotel, Hughes replaced 72-inch beds with 80-inch beds and had color televisions built into the walls of each room ahead of the resort's opening.<ref name=Finishing/>\n\nThe Landmark's second floor was used for offices.<ref name=Layout/> The tower's dome included five floors, although floors 26 and 30 were used by employees for maintenance equipment, elevator equipment, and dressing rooms.<ref name=Layout/> The shape and strength of the tower's bubble dome was maintained by [[perlite]] concrete and steel [[girder]]s.<ref name=InsideBubble/> The Landmark included a high-speed exterior glass elevator<ref name=Key1/> \u2013 located on the tower's west side<ref name=Regal1/> and facing the Las Vegas Strip<ref name=SeenCalif/> \u2013 which took people up to the five-story [[cupola]] dome.<ref name=Cleared/> Elevator Services was hired to install the Landmark's exterior elevator, capable of moving 1,000 feet per minute, allowing people to go from the ground floor to the 31st floor in 20 seconds. It was the fastest elevator in the [[Western United States]].<ref name=Elevator>{{cite news|title=Landmark's Elevator to be Speedy|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-aug-25-1966-420864/|accessdate=October 15, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=August 25, 1966|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> Hughes biographer [[Michael Drosnin]] stated that the elevator was prone to constant malfunctions, and that the Landmark's air-conditioning system \"never really worked.\"<ref name=Citizen/> The dome provided wraparound views of the city,<ref name=Cleared/><ref name=Regal1/> and was capable of holding over 2,000 people.<ref name=Apr6-68/> The dome included lounges and a night club,<ref name=Regal1/> as well as the high-rise casino on the 29th floor.<ref name=Hoopla/>\n\nAt the time of the Landmark's opening, the showroom and the Cascade Terrace coffee shop were located on the first floor,<ref name=Key1/><ref name=Key2/><ref name=presents>{{cite news|title=The Landmark Presents|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/a-j-other-articles-clipping-may-16-1970-424109/|accessdate=December 1, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=May 16, 1970|via=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref> while a steak and seafood gourmet restaurant known as Towers Restaurant was located on the 27th floor.<ref name=Key2/><ref name=presents/> A Chinese restaurant, the Mandarin Room, operated on the 29th floor.<ref name=Key2/><ref name=presents/>\n\n[[Image:VegasLandMark-Night.jpg|thumb|right|270px|A 1995 photo of the tower, modified to depict its operational appearance in the 1980s]]\nIn April 1971, plans were announced for a $750,000 expansion that would include luxury suites on the 29th floor, the highest in Las Vegas at the time. Also planned was the remodeling of the casino and lobby, and the expansion of a coffee shop.<ref>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel to expand in Las Vegas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11460125/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=April 20, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044117/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11460125/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> The Skytop Rendezvous, a piano bar and dance floor on the top floor of the tower, was reopened as a [[discotheque]] on February 3, 1975, specializing in [[Middle of the road (music)|middle of the road music]]. The Landmark was the only major hotel in the state to have a discotheque.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vegas Landmark Opens a Disco|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MREEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA74&dq=landmark+hotel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkmZfR-JrUAhVqqFQKHSWeBUs4ChDoAQgrMAE#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 8, 1975}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas' Landmark Sets A Disco Record For First|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QhEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT3&lpg=PT3&dq=landmark+hotel&source=bl&ots=DnUZLOTgq0&sig=Gy6bwajSW-l76OpnXv41bqlHqVM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwr-fb9ZrUAhVowVQKHQ3VBJcQ6AEIZTAJ#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 22, 1975}}</ref> When Morris' renovation began in December 1983, the tower contained 150 rooms, a number that was expected to be reduced as the rooms would be enlarged and upgraded to first class standards. Other plans included changes to the coffee shop, new casino carpeting, and redesigning and renaming the 27th-floor restaurant as Anthony's Seafood and Prime Rib Room.<ref name=Facelift/>\n\nThe existing structures were renovated with financing from Valley Bank of Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Morris v. Bank of America Nevada|url=http://law.justia.com/cases/nevada/supreme-court/1994/22881-1.html|website=Law.Justia.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017|date=November 30, 1994|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044255/http://law.justia.com/cases/nevada/supreme-court/1994/22881-1.html|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> New red stripes were also added along the windows running up the tower and the roof was painted red to match. The entrance had red-lit outriggers added and a new side entrance was added to the casino.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} The Love Song Lounge operated on the top floor during the mid-1980s, before and after Morris' renovation,<ref name=Facelift/><ref name=NYE/> and offered dancing.<ref name=Combines>{{cite news|title=Restaurant combines dining with a view|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459964/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 19, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 7, 1986|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> During 1985 through 1987, the resort also operated the Sunset Room on the 27th floor, offering piano-bar music and fine dining,<ref name=NYE/><ref>{{cite news|title=Strong Earthquake Rocks Southern California|url= https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/9c03b6_889919bb64dd4897b029cf633adcf2d1.pdf|accessdate=February 18, 2018|agency=Associated Press|work=The Post-Standard|date=November 24, 1987}}</ref> with an emphasis on steaks and seafood.<ref name=Combines/> The Poolside Room operated on the ground level.<ref name=NYE>{{cite news|title=Landmark Hotel and Casino offering variety of New Year's Eve activities|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422564/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=February 18, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=December 22, 1985|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Nightcap Lounge opened at the Landmark in 1986, and offered comedy acts.<ref name=Combines/>\n\n===Reception===\nIn 1962, the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the $6 million project, \"By far the most spectacular project\", out of several Las Vegas resorts that were under construction; the newspaper further wrote that the Landmark was \"destined to become the [[Mark Hopkins Hotel|Mark Hopkins]] of Las Vegas.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hulse|first=Jerry|title=On the Go: All That Glitters Is That Las Vegas Gold|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381396/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=May 31, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 5, 1962|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045724/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11381396/the_los_angeles_times/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> The following year, the ''[[Reno Evening Gazette]]'' opined that the Landmark had \"the most unusual exterior architecture in Nevada.\"<ref name=Reno63>{{cite news|title=Space Needle or Hotel?|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11706897/reno_gazettejournal/|accessdate=July 13, 2017|work=Reno Evening Gazette|date=February 23, 1963|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093400/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11706897/reno_gazettejournal/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In 1966, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' wrote that the mushroom-shaped Landmark tower had \"the most spectacular design\" of all recent high-rise structures in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Las Vegas: How It Has Grown\u2026|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KBIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=landmark+hotel+casino&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu4Jfe-prUAhXjqFQKHczACOQ4FBDoAQhLMAk#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel%20casino&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 27, 1966|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012180710/https://books.google.com/books?id=KBIEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA47&dq=landmark+hotel+casino&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu4Jfe-prUAhXjqFQKHczACOQ4FBDoAQhLMAk#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel%20casino&f=false|archivedate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> In 1993, architecture critic [[Alan Hess]] noted the simplicity of the Landmark and the nearby International Hotel when compared with previous Las Vegas casinos, writing, \"As singular, self-contained forms, they showed none of the complexity of the different pieces and sequential additions that made the original Strip visually and urbanistically richer.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Viva Las Vegas: After Hours Architecture|first=Alan|last=Hess|page=92|publisher=Chronicle Books|year=1993|isbn=081180111X}}</ref> In 2002, Geoff Carter of ''[[Las Vegas Weekly]]'' wrote that the demolished Landmark was \"Vegas' coolest building and a veritable shrine to 1960s '[[Googie]]' architecture.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Carter|first=Geoff|title=Tourists For Breakfast: Designing Vegas|url=http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|work=[[Las Vegas Weekly]]|date=April 2002|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020621082703/http://www.lasvegasweekly.com/2002/04_11/art_tfb.html|archivedate=June 21, 2002}}</ref>\n\n==Performances==\n[[Peggy Lee]] performed at the Landmark in 1969.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Vegas |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/270647964/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |date=September 21, 1969 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=News |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/460230289/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=San Francisco Examiner |date=September 28, 1969 |via=Newspapers.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref> During 1971, the Landmark became well known for its performances by [[Country music|country singers]], including [[Kay Starr]], [[Jimmy Dean]], [[Patti Page]], [[Bobbie Gentry]], and [[Danny Davis (country musician)|Danny Davis]] with his Nashville Brass band, as well as a four-week show starring [[Ferlin Husky]] and [[Archie Campbell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Country Gaining in Las Vegas Hotels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7QgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=landmark+hotel&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4t_La95rUAhWljVQKHTPDAgUQ6AEIRDAH#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|accessdate=June 9, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 6, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412114322/https://books.google.com/books?id=7QgEAAAAMBAJ#v=onepage&q=landmark%20hotel&f=false|archivedate=April 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Grand Ole Opry Due Tonight at Landmark |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/383148311/ |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=January 7, 1971 |url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> [[Frank Sinatra]] also performed at the Landmark, and [[Bobby Darin]] made one of his final appearances there.<ref name=\"Las Vegas Sun\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/1995/nov/07/landmark-falls/|title=Landmark Falls|last=Buntain|first=Rex|date=November 7, 1995|publisher=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=September 23, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924141605/https://lasvegassun.com/news/1995/nov/07/landmark-falls/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In May 1974, the Landmark launched ''Red McIlvaine's Star Search'', a variety show featuring people from across the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=Red's New Talent Show at Landmark |url=http://d.library.unlv.edu/digital/collection/jhp/id/13483 |website=Las Vegas Israelite |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=May 10, 1974 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nIn early 1975,<ref>{{cite news|title=Halsey Picnic Draws $5,500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=exEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA52&lpg=PA52#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Billboard|date=November 15, 1975|page=TO-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170321172954/https://books.google.com/books?id=exEEAAAAMBAJ#v=onepage&q&f=false|archivedate=March 21, 2017}}</ref> [[Jim Halsey|The Jim Halsey Company]] began ''Country Music USA'', a show at the Landmark that featured a different country music [[Headliner (performances)|headliner]] every two to three weeks. The show was usually sold out.<ref name=Halsey>{{cite book|last=Halsey|first=Jim|title=Starmaker: How to Make it in the Music Business|date=2010|publisher=Tate Publishing|isbn=978-1607995418|pages=72\u201374, 84|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4j-hJbUaPnoC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> [[Roy Clark]] and [[Mel Tillis]] made their debuts in ''Country Music USA'',<ref name=Delaney/> as did [[Freddy Fender]].<ref name=Halsey/> [[The Oak Ridge Boys]] made their Las Vegas debut in ''Country Music USA''.<ref name=Halsey/><ref name=Delaney>{{cite news|last=Delaney|first=Joe|title=New book a reminder of LV's country ties|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/feb/09/columnist-joe-delaney-new-book-a-reminder-of-lvs-c/|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Las Vegas Sun|date=February 9, 2001|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929233129/https://lasvegassun.com/news/2001/feb/09/columnist-joe-delaney-new-book-a-reminder-of-lvs-c/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> [[Leroy Van Dyke]] performed in the show during 1975, with Fender as his [[opening act]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Colleen|title=Nashville Scene|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QhEEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT47&lpg=PT47#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 22, 1975}}</ref><ref name=Dyke/> Van Dyke performed again at the Landmark later in the 1970s, with [[Sons of the Pioneers]] as his opening act.<ref name=Dyke>{{cite news|title=Leroy Van Dyke|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/life/leroy-van-dyke/|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=February 8, 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929232954/https://www.reviewjournal.com/life/leroy-van-dyke/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> Other artists who performed in ''Country Music USA'' included [[Barbara Fairchild]], [[Johnny Paycheck]] and [[Tommy Overstreet]],<ref>{{cite news|title=What's Happening in Country|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/165973595/|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=October 26, 1975|url-access=subscription |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929232019/https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/165973595/|archivedate=September 29, 2017}}</ref> as well as [[Jody Miller]], [[Roy Head]], and [[Hank Thompson (musician)|Hank Thompson]].<ref name=Hanford/> ''Country Music USA'' ran for two years, until 1977.<ref name=Hanford>{{cite news|last=Searl|first=Hanford|title=Country Rolls for Vegas Jackpot|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p00EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT94&lpg=PT94#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=September 29, 2017|work=Billboard|date=October 15, 1977}}</ref>\n\nIn October 1982, the Landmark debuted ''Spellcaster'', an 80-minute family oriented show featuring country-western singer Roy Clayborne.<ref name=Todd/><ref name=Clayborne1>{{cite news|last=McCann|first=Steven|title=Landmark opens \"Spellcaster\" featuring Roy Clayborne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11422893/arizona_republic/|accessdate=February 5, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=October 17, 1982|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Clayborne2>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Landmark featuring singer Roy Clayborne|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/170383510/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=November 21, 1982|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> ''Spellcaster'', a production show with dancers and [[showgirl]]s,<ref name=Todd/> featured Clayborne singing 15 songs.<ref name=Clayborne1/><ref name=Clayborne2/> ''Spellcaster'' was named after one of the Wolframs' [[racing horse]]s,<ref name=Todd/> and was produced through Zula Wolfram's Las Vegas production company, Zula Productions.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Toledo stockbroker center of investigation|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/304344275/|accessdate=December 14, 2017|work=The News-Messenger|location=Fremont, Ohio|date=March 1, 1983|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> The show was designed and directed by [[Larry Hart (musician)|Larry Hart]],<ref name=Todd/><ref name=Clayborne1/><ref name=Clayborne2/> a [[Grammy Award for Best Gospel Performance, Contemporary|1979 Grammy Award]] winner,<ref name=Clayborne1/><ref name=Clayborne2/> and it ran for approximately eight months.<ref name=Todd/> At the time of ''Spellcaster'''s debut, Danny Hein and Terri Dancer also began performing in the resort's Galaxy Lounge. Hein and Dancer had four different shows consisting of various costumes and set decorations, and were accompanied by a five-person band of musicians who backed up the duo.<ref name=Clayborne1/>\n\nAs of 1987, the Landmark's showroom hosted minor acts and was considered small in comparison to other Las Vegas resorts.<ref name=Arson/> In May 1988, the Landmark began hosting magician [[Melinda Saxe]] in a [[family-friendly]] magic show,<ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda has a bag of tricks for Landmark|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11427985/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 22, 1988|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda continues Landmark shows during the summer|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11428008/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 26, 1988|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Graham|first=Jefferson|title=New family emphasis may strip Vegas of glitz, glamour|url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19890721.1.50|accessdate=March 2, 2018|agency=Gannett News Service|work=San Bernardino Sun|date=July 21, 1989}}</ref> known as '''88 Follies Revue''<ref>{{cite news|title=Calendar|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/121232271/|accessdate=March 2, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=May 29, 1988|via=Newspapers.com|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and renamed ''Follies Revue '89'' the following year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda's magic showcased nightly|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459807/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=February 19, 1989|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Melinda's 'Mystery of Malaquena' truly unique|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459821/arizona_republic/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=May 28, 1989|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Saxe's show at the Landmark closed in late 1989.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jerry Lewis Telethon may leave Entertainment Capital|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459665/arizona_republic/|accessdate=March 2, 2018|work=Arizona Republic|date=January 21, 1990|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> During early 1990, the main showroom featured ''Spellbound'', a magic show consisting of two illusionist teams. Dick Foster was the show's director and producer.<ref name=Spellbound>{{cite news|title='Spellbound' Presents Many Unusual Illusions|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459636/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=February 11, 1990|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=Foster>{{cite news|title=Foster's Magic Isn't An Illusion|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11459651/the_los_angeles_times/|accessdate=March 1, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|date=April 29, 1990|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture ==\nThe unfinished tower briefly appears in the 1964 film, ''[[Viva Las Vegas]]''.<ref name=LHM/><ref>{{cite news|last=Bornfeld|first=Steve|title=Viva Viva Las Vegas!|url=http://vegasseven.com/2014/05/13/viva-viva-las-vegas/|accessdate=September 23, 2017|work=Vegas Seven|date=May 13, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045450/http://vegasseven.com/2014/05/13/viva-viva-las-vegas/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In 1971, [[Sean Connery]] and [[stuntmen]] rode atop the Landmark's exterior elevator as part of filming for scenes in the James Bond film ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]''{{hsp}}; the tower was among other Las Vegas resorts that stood in as the fictional Whyte House hotel-casino.<ref>{{cite news|title=James Bond Bulletin|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874896/colorado_springs_gazettetelegraph/|accessdate=July 14, 2017|work=[[The Gazette (Colorado Springs)|Colorado Springs Gazette-Telegraph]]|date=April 26, 1971|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924044839/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874896/colorado_springs_gazettetelegraph/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Michaels|first=Ken|title=That's about it, 007|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874936/chicago_tribune/|accessdate=July 14, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|date=July 11, 1971|quote=Yesterday it was the outdoor elevator of the Landmark, the stunt boys climbing up the building playing Bond, almost killing themselves.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924092753/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/11874936/chicago_tribune/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Christopher|title=When James Bond came to Las Vegas|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/christopher-lawrence/when-james-bond-came-to-las-vegas-photos/|accessdate=July 14, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=November 4, 2015|quote=To film the scene of Bond sneaking into The Whyte House penthouse, Connery rode atop the exterior elevator at the Landmark.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924045352/https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/christopher-lawrence/when-james-bond-came-to-las-vegas-photos/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref> In the 1980s, the Landmark appeared in the television series ''[[Vega$]]'' and ''[[Crime Story (U.S. TV series)|Crime Story]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Landmark Hotel|url=https://nevadafilm.com/map-location/the-landmark-hotel/?mpfy_map=4181&mpfy-pin=4965|publisher=Nevada Film Office|accessdate=September 23, 2017}}</ref> In October 1994, the exterior entrance of the Landmark was lit up for one night so it could be used for outdoor shots as the fictional Tangiers casino, featured in the 1995 film, ''[[Casino (film)|Casino]]''.<ref name=QOTD/><ref>{{cite web|last=Kachelriess|first=Rob|title=9 \"Casino\" Filming Locations You Can Still Hit in Vegas Today|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/las-vegas/where-martin-scorsese-s-casino-was-filmed-9-las-vegas-locations|website=[[Thrillist]]|accessdate=June 29, 2017|date=April 12, 2015|quote=The exteriors of the fictional Tangiers were shot at the Landmark Hotel\u2026 which has since been demolished.|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093141/https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/las-vegas/where-martin-scorsese-s-casino-was-filmed-9-las-vegas-locations|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cling|first=Carol|title='Casino' unflinching in its view of Las Vegas and its mob past|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/movies/casino-unflinching-in-its-view-of-las-vegas-and-its-mob-past/|accessdate=June 29, 2017|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|date=November 22, 2015|quote=10/14/1994 The Landmark hotel is transformed into the mythical 'Tangiers' for the movie \"Casino\".|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924093114/https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/movies/casino-unflinching-in-its-view-of-las-vegas-and-its-mob-past/|archivedate=September 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Landmark's implosion was filmed for use in director [[Tim Burton]]'s 1996 film, ''[[Mars Attacks!]]''.<ref name=lvs1/><ref name=CT/><ref name=Mag/> In the film, the Landmark is portrayed as the fictional Galaxy Hotel, which is destroyed by an alien spaceship.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scene In Nevada: Mars Attacks!|url=https://nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-mars-attacks/|publisher=Nevada Film Office|accessdate=September 23, 2017|date=January 25, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203032706/https://www.nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-mars-attacks/|archivedate=February 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Katsilometes |first=John |title=Tim Burton was shaken, for real, at Las Vegas Landmark implosion |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/entertainment-columns/kats/tim-burton-was-shaken-for-real-at-las-vegas-landmark-implosion-1870485/ |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |work=Las Vegas Review-Journal |date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> Burton had stayed at the hotel a few times and was upset by the decision to demolish it, so he wanted to immortalize it in his film.<ref>{{cite web |title=Production notes |url=http://marsattacks.warnerbros.com/cmp/5-prodnotes4.html#lasvegas |publisher=Warner Bros. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203133559/http://marsattacks.warnerbros.com/cmp/5-prodnotes4.html#lasvegas |archivedate=February 3, 2009 |date=1996}}</ref> A scale model of the Landmark tower was also made for the production of ''Mars Attacks!''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bell |first=Josh |title=Geek Road Trip: Tim Burton takes us on a tour of his Las Vegas |url=https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/geek-road-trip-tim-burton-takes-us-on-a-tour-of-his-las-vegas |website=Syfy Wire |accessdate=December 26, 2019 |date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> The demolition of the Landmark also appears during the closing credits of the 2003 film, ''[[The Cooler]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scene In Nevada: The Cooler|url=https://www.nevadafilm.com/scene-in-nevada-the-cooler/|publisher=Nevada Film Office|accessdate=August 9, 2017|date=July 12, 2017}}</ref> The Lucky 38, a fictional tower casino featured in the 2010 video game ''[[Fallout: New Vegas]]'', partially resembles the Landmark.<ref>{{cite news |last=Witcher |first=T.R. |title=Unexpected Art |url=https://vegasseven.com/2010/11/04/unexpected-art/ |work=VegasSeven |date=November 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208081545/https://vegasseven.com/2010/11/04/unexpected-art/ |archivedate=December 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[The Drew Las Vegas]], tallest building in Nevada since 2008; scheduled to open in 2022 after a construction delay\n\n== Notes ==\n{{noteslist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N1SREuX3pXs Slideshow of Landmark photos]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qYbQqgx9T-w Landmark demolition video]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NT4iPWzsf94 Footage of the Landmark's implosion used for ''Mars Attacks!'']\